<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>SUMMARY</B></P>
<P>This supplementary proof reviews the proofs by Mr R J Metcalfe and Ms J
Perry which oppose the planning application for the RCF on the grounds that it
would have an adverse socio-economic impact.  I also comment on the proof and
evidence lead by Mr R B Hellier at the Public Inquiry into the Copeland Local
Plan Deposit Version, to which Mr Metcalfe's proof refers.</P>
<P><A NAME="Introduction"></A><B>1. INTRODUCTION</B></P>
<P>1.1 In this supplementary proof I comment on the proofs of evidence which
oppose the planning application for the RCF on the grounds that it will have an
adverse socioeconomic impact. I include in this comments on the proof and the
evidence lead by Mr R B Hellier at the Public Inquiry into the Copeland Local
Plan Deposit Version, to which Mr R J Metcalfe's proof of evidence for this
Inquiry makes reference.</P>
<P>1.2 First, I set out the issues which do not appear to be contested and
second, I comment on the issues which do appear to be contested.</P>
<P>1.3 <B>Issues Not Contested:</B> None of the proofs challenge the
methodology or the estimates of direct, indirect and induced employment
contained in my main proof of evidence [<A HREF="nrx10.htm"><B>PE/NRX/10</B></A>].
Nor do the proofs suggest there would be difficulties in meeting the demands
placed on local housing, education and health provision. Indeed, CCC/1 accepts
there will be no difficulties in this regard.</P>
<P>1.4 None of the proofs advance any evidence as to the impact of the RCF, if
any, on residential property values.</P>
<P>1.5 <B>Contested Issues:</B> The most notable feature of the proofs is that
they do not provide any new empirical evidence on socio-economic impacts.
Instead, they proceed by asserting there will be adverse impacts or by
reinterpreting the data, while ignoring the conclusions reached by other
studies.  This is most evident with regard to two documents</P>
<UL>
<LI> the study by the Government Enterprise Communication Unit (GECU) of
Newcastle  University, &quot;Perceptions of West Cumbria as a Destination for
Leisure Travel and  Inward Investment&quot; [COR/406]; and
</LI>
<LI>  the <B>P</B><I>ieda </I>study, &quot;The Impact of Nuclear Facilities
on Local Development&quot; [COR/402].
</LI></UL>
<P>1.6 It should not be lost sight of that the objectors' proofs make no
reference to other studies referred to in my proof of evidence which, using
different data sources, reach conclusions which reinforce the conclusions set
out in [COR/4O6] and [COR/402]. The relevant studies are [NRX/10/7], [NRX/10/9]
and [NRX/10/10].</P>
<P>1.7  In both cases, the objectors' proofs proceed by isolating and
exaggerating any adverse socio-economic impact which may arise from Sellafield,
while ignoring any beneficial socio-economic impact. I set out my detailed
comments below.</P>
<P><A NAME="Perceptions"></A><B>2. &quot;Perceptions of West Cumbria as a
Destination for Leisure Travel and Inward Investment&quot; [COR/406]</B></P>
<P>2.1 There are two versions of this report. The first was the subject matter
of an interim presentation made to the West Cumbria Development Agency on 27 May
1994. The second is the final report dated December1994 [COR/406].</P>
<P>2.2 My proof of evidence [<A HREF="nrx10.htm"><B>PE/NRX/10</B></A>] draws
on the final report and attempts to summarise its findings (paras 7.53-7.57). Mr
Hague of Newcastle University has confirmed that he considers this to be an
accurate summary of the final report. My correspondence with Mr Hague is
attached as <A HREF="#Appendix">Appendix 1</A>.</P>
<P>2.3 In his evidence to the Public Inquiry on the Cumbria Local Plan Deposit
Version, Mr Hellier stated his view <I>&quot;that there has been signjficant
editorial control over what has been put in this report&quot;</I> (Transcript,
Volume 2, p50). This allegation is based on the observation that certain tables
included in the interim presentation (specifically, Table 6 relating to inward
investment and Tables 11 and 12 relating to visitors) were included in the
interim presentation and excluded from the final report. Because of this he
considers that the results reached by the Newcastle University researchers are
questionable and implies that the editorial control may have been exercised
between the interim presentation and the final report.</P>
<P>2.4 Metcalfe in commenting on this research follows the same procedure as Mr
Hellier in that he refers (paragraph 5.5.13) to data drawn from the same tables
in the interim presentation but not to the conclusions reached by the authors in
their interim presentation and their final report.</P>
<P>2.5 In practice, both Mr Hellier and Mr Metcalfe are arguing that, on the
basis of the evidence available to them, the Newcastle University researchers
should have reached different conclusions. This requires one of two things to be
true:</P>
<UL>
<LI> either that the conclusions of the final report with respect to inward
investment and tourism were <B>materially</B> different from those originally
reached in the initial presentation, particularly with regard to the assessed
impact of Sellafield, and that these differences stem from the suppression of
data originally contained in the interim presentation,
</LI>
<LI> or that it is not possible to reach the conclusions of the interim
presentation and the final report given the complete data set on which the
researchers relied.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.6 There are differences in the length and structure of the interim
presentation and the final report. For example, the documentation for the
interim presentation comprises 38 pages (including tables), whereas the final
report (excluding the final references also excluded from the interim
presentation) is only 28 pages (including tables). However, the conclusions
reached in the interim presentation and the final report are materially the
same.</P>
<P>2.7<B> </B>In my proof of evidence [<B>PE/NRX/10</B>] I quote the major
conclusions of the final report with regard to inward investment in paragraphs
<A HREF="nrx10.htm#Para7.56">7.56</A> and <A HREF="nrx10.htm#Para7.57">7.57</A>
and with regard to visitors in <A HREF="nrx10.htm#Para7.59">7.59</A>. These
quotes are produced below, along with quotations drawn from the interim
presentation. I would suggest that comparison demonstrates that the Newcastle
University researchers were consistent and did not change their main conclusions
between the interim presentation and final report.</P>
<P></P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
<TR ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD COLSPAN="2"><B>MAIN CONCLUSIONS: INWARD INVESTMENT</B></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><B>Interim Presentation</B></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><B>Final Report</B></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><I>&quot;West Cumbria is popularly perceived to
be isolated geographically, economically and socially within the UK and Europe&quot;
(p15)</I><BR><BR>
<I>&quot;The principal perceived advantage of the area, its quality of life, is
not a significant factor in the choice of destination for relocation&quot; (p15)</I><BR><BR>
<I>&quot;The result is that few firms consider Cumbria, let alone West Cumbria,
as a location&quot; (p15)</I><BR><BR>
<I>&quot;The area has no clear identity with commerce or industry, other than
the Sellafield site which has a number of difficult connotations&quot; (p15)</I><BR>
<I>&quot;As a source of technology and other resources the Sellafield site, in
conjunction with BNFL's technology transfer initiative and the emerging Science
Park at Westlakes, could be considered as the principal industrial assets of
West Cumbria&quot; (p15)</I>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><I>&quot;Cumbria was perceived to be isolated
from markets, commerce, communities and culture and its serious geographical
isolation to be compounded by road, rail and air links&quot; (p6)</I><BR><BR>
<I>&quot;The perceived advantages of the area (Cumbria) are inconsistent with
the requirements of a destination for inward investment ... the area is very
unappealing to a majority of decision makers involved in industrial relocation.&quot;
(p6)</I><BR><BR>
<I>&quot;... Sellafield is not a significant deterrent to inward investment in
West Cumbria, and with the proper infrastructure for the transfer or
exploitation of its technologies, could be turned into a considerable asset&quot;
(p7)</I>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P></P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
<TR ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD COLSPAN="2"><B>MAIN CONCLUSIONS: VISITORS</B></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><B>Interim Presentation</B></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><B>Final Report</B></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><I>&quot;Persons who had visited West Cumbria
perceived the natural environment of the Lake District to be its principal asset
and the built environment outwith the Lake District as dismal, dull and
depressed, lacking in tourist facilities, and to be inaccessible by road. Those
who had not visited West Cumbria had few other perceptions of the area other
than as part of the Lake District (its principal positive attribute). This
survey suggests that the vast majority of persons are no more or less likely to
visit West Cumbria because of the presence of BNFL at Sellafield&quot;</I>(p24)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><I>&quot;The majority of respondents were aware
of the Sellafield site and the Visitors Centre which was perceived to be one of
the major attractions within the area. Our sample survey revealed that the vast
majority of persons are no less likely to visit West Cumbria because of the
presence of BNFL at Sellafield, indeed some 6% of respondents were more likely
to visit the area to see the heavily promoted Sellafield visitors Centre&quot;
(p11)</I>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.8 I would suggest that while there are textual changes as often occurs
between an interim presentation and a final report, the Newcastle University
researchers cannot be regarded as having <B>materially</B> changed their main
conclusions.</P>
<P>2.9 These could be summarised as follows. West Cumbria, because of its
relative isolation and poor communications, is not a location which can be
expected to be attractive to mobile investment.  Indeed, very few mobile
investments consider even Cumbria seriously. As to tourist visitors, few who
have not been to West Cumbria have any clear image of the area. Visitor
perceptions are dominated by the Lake District and to the extent that potential
visitors do have an image of West Cumbria, these are often negative. As to
Sellafield, both with regard to inward investment and visitors, even in the
absence of Sellafield the fortunes of the area with regard to inward investment
and tourist visitors could not be expected to change significantly for the
better.</P>
<P>2.10 This comparison of the conclusions of the interim presentation and the
final report do not suggest that these have been subject to <I>&quot;significant
editorial control&quot; as </I>suggested by Mr Hellier. I now turn to
considering whether the conclusions of the interim presentation and the final
report are consistent with the complete data set on which the researchers
relied.</P>
<P>2.11 The first point to make is that the researchers evidently did not
consider their conclusions at odds with their data. The specific tables to which
Mr Hellier refers were set out in the interim presentation and the main
conclusions in that presentation were carried forward to the final report.</P>
<P>2.12 It is important to understand that in considering both inward
investment and tourism, the Newcastle University researchers were drawing on
more than one source of information and/or expertise and that their conclusions
relate to the body of that evidence as a whole. In short, if particular elements
are selected and these are not put in context, then this will not lead to a
balanced conclusion.</P>
<P>2.13 The Newcastle University researchers rest their conclusions on inward
investment on:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>14 companies who had considered a site in Cumbria but who had subsequently
not moved to Cumbria</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>in re-analysis of a survey of 212 companies carried through by Scantel for
the Cumbria Marketing Initiative</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP" NOWRAP="NoWrap">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>a series of focus group meetings with persons in the development agencies
involved in promoting Cumbria as an investment location.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.14 Mr Hellier in his proof of evidence to the Copeland Local Plan relies
on (a) above. He observes, correctly, that 4 of these 14 companies (28.5%)
unprompted and 7 of these (50%) prompted considered Sellafield to be a
disadvantage to operating in West Cumbria (the data are contained in Figure 6 of
the interim presentation). However, accessibility considerations are clearly
most important of all and the reasons why Sellafield are classified as a
disadvantage are not apparent ie. whether the answer reflects labour
availability, labour cost or &quot;blight&quot; considerations.</P>
<P>2.15 It is quite evident from the text of the presentation that the
Newcastle University researchers had wished to interrogate a larger sample of
companies who had considered Cumbria The Northern Development Company (NDC) and
INWARD had indicated they would provide a sample of 35 to 50 firms but <I>&quot;around
a dozen&quot; </I>(p6) originally approached refused to participate in the
study. The researchers were ultimately driven back on 75 references supplied by
Cumbria Council's Economic Development Department but NDC were able to supply
only 48 usable contacts from this list, of which 28 proved uncontactable and 11
refused to be interviewed. This left the 14 companies who co-operated.</P>
<P>2.16 The Newcastle University researchers, not unnaturally, wished to test
the <I>&quot;validity of the small group of respondents &quot; </I> (p7).  This
was provided by the focus group discussions and the Scantel sample of 212
companies moving or expanding within the UK.</P>
<P>2.17 The Newcastle University researchers report that the <I>&quot;principal&quot;
</I>theme emerging from the focus group discussions was<I> &quot;that West
Cumbria is perceived by inward investors as being remote and isolated from road,
rail and air communications, and from centres of economic activity&quot; </I>(p13).
Further, <I>&quot;it was also suggested that the area is perceived to be weak
in terms of the cultural and other amenities, such as shops, theatres and other
facilities&quot;</I> (p13).</P>
<P>2.18 As to Sellafield and the nuclear industry it was suggested that
Sellafield has both a positive and a negative influence on inward investment.
The negative effect flowed from the external perceptions of outsiders as a
consequence of <I>&quot;the negative publicity that the site brought to the
area...</I>&quot; The positive side flowed from the presence of BNFL and the
Westlakes Science Park (p14).</P>
<P>2.19 The Scantel survey indicated that 96% of the 212 companies <I>&quot;had
never considered moving to Cumbria&quot; (p8</I>) and that for both unprompted
and prompted responses the most frequently mentioned factor influencing choice
of location was proximity to markets.</P>
<P>2.20 I would suggest that in the light of the above evidence, it is not
surprising that the researchers should conclude that <I>'few firms consider
Cumbria, let alone <U>West</U> Cumbria, as a location&quot;</I>, (p15). This is
due to its perceived isolation. The Sellafield site itself may have both
negative and positive impacts but is not a dominant consideration.</P>
<P>2.21 As the researchers point out (see 2.20), few companies consider
Cumbria, far less West Cumbria, as a location. This strongly supports the view
that powerful considerations of remoteness are at work, a conclusion supported
by the results of [NRX/10/7] and [NRX/10/9].</P>
<P><B>Visitors</B></P>
<P>2.22 The Newcastle University researchers base their conclusions of visitor
perceptions on their own survey of tourist visitors who had or had not visited
West Cumbria, and on previous research conducted by the English Tourist Board
and Ecotec.</P>
<P>2.23 Persons who had visited West Cumbria had clearly not been deterred by
the existence of Sellafield. As to those who had not visited West Cumbria, the
Sellafield Visitors Centre was the most widely known visitor attraction in West
Cumbria (known to more than 60% of respondents, the next best known attraction
being mentioned by slightly less than 40%; see Table 9). Sellafield was the most
frequently mentioned <I>&quot;bad thing&quot; </I>about West Cumbria (mentioned
by some 35%; see Table 11). The former response suggests Sellafield Visitors
Centre will attract some potential visitors and the latter response that
Sellafield will deter some potential visitors. The Newcastle University
researchers do clearly state in their final report the conclusion (p11) that
<I>&quot;the vast majority of persons are no less likely to visit West Cumbria
because of the presence of Sellafield&quot;, </I>this being supported by Figure
12.  This Figure also shows that the balance reporting that Sellafield would
make visits <I>&quot;less likely&quot; </I>outweighs the balance who report its
impact as making a visit <I>&quot;more likely&quot;.</I></P>
<P>2.24<B> </B>The Newcastle University researchers point out (interim
presentation pp2l-22) that both the ETB and the Ecotec studies provide evidence
that there are a range of factors which give the Cumbrian coast an unfavourable
perception as a destination for a leisure trip, at least relative to the Lake
District; and the Cumbria Tourist Board, reviewing the ETB study, concluded that
Sellafield did not emerge as a significant deterrent to tourist visits [<B>PE/NRX/10
</B>, para <A HREF="nrx10.htm#Para7.60">7.60</A>].</P>
<P>2.25 The conclusion of the Newcastle University researchers is that <I>&quot;the
vast majority of persons are no more or less likely to visit West Cumbria
because of the presence of BNFL at Sellafield&quot; </I>(interim presentation
p24 and final report p11)  is therefore consistent both with previous studies
and their own data.</P>
<P><A NAME="Impact"></A><B>3. &quot;The Impact of Nuclear Facilities on Local
Development&quot; [COR/402].</B></P>
<P>3.1 Two proofs of evidence by Mr Metcalfe (Copeland Borough Council) and by
Ms I Perry (Cumbrian Friends of the Earth Groups) make reference to this report.
Both proceed by summarising those parts of the report which are perceived to
indicate the possibility of adverse socio-economic impacts, while ignoring
evidence indicating the possibility of beneficial socio-economic impacts. Both
proofs ignore the overall conclusions of the report which include the following
passage (para 7.13):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The results of our surveys do flat suggest that the blighting
effects of Sellafield and other nuclear facilities are substantial. They are
restricted problems of recruiting higher levels of staff, highly localised
depression of property prices and some possible discouragement of inward
investment. The existence of Sellafield does not appear to have induced firms to
move away from the area, nor have we been able to establish any adverse impact
on the output of existing firms - although at least one firm appears to fear
that such an effect could exist. Amongst the development agencies there is a
perception that at Sellafield the proposed DRP may further discourage inward
investment. On the basis of the existing evidence, however, the evidence does
not suggest that the DRP would have a substantial impact on economic behaviour&quot;.</I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>3.2 Even where specific instances of a possible adverse impact are
identified it is necessary<I> </I>to treat the evidence cautiously. For
example, Ms Perry confuses two different cases in the following quotation and,
consequently, reaches an erroneous conclusion:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;One firm closed in the 80s had not cited ... blight as a direct
cause of closure, but it was admitted that management had expressed concerns
about the blight effect of Sellafield, and in rationalisation plans it may well
have been a determining factors when deciding which factory to close&quot;.</I>
[PE/CFE/1, para 34]</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>3.3 The 1980s closure is discussed at two points in [COR/402] at paras 3.3
and 3.35-3.36.  Both Copeland Borough Council and the West Cumbria Development
Agency cited the closure as the consequence of the blighting impact of
Sellafield. However, as the text of COR/402 makes clear, the closure was part of
a UK rationalisation programme.  The company executive interviewed specifically
and categorically denied any suggestion that the closure was due to Sellafield.</P>
<P>3.4<I> </I>In the second part of her sentence Ms Perry appears to be
referring to the quite separate case discussed in [COR/402] paras 3.23-3.24 and
3.38. The management of this company had expressed a concern that Sellafield
might adversely effect sales but also stated that, to the date of the interview,
<I>&quot;it did not believe that it had lost any custom due to Sellafield&quot;
</I>(3.24). The business was in the process of relocating from Cumbria but Ms
Perry's speculation that <I>&quot;the blight effect of Sellafield may well have
been a determining factor when deciding which factory to close &quot; </I>is
quite unfounded. On the contrary, the company explicitly rejected the suggestion
that the relocation was due to Sellafield para 3.38).</P>
<P>3.5 There is also further evidence relating to the executive who aborted the
interview in circumstances which suggest a concern that being &quot;<I>associated</I>&quot;
with Sellafield could adversely impact on sales [<B>PE/NRX/10</B>, para
<A HREF="nrx10.htm#Para7.68">7.68</A>]. Subsequent to that interview in 1992,
the company completed a postal questionnaire on another assignment undertaken by
<B>P</B><I>ieda</I> and there has been extensive coverage of the plants
activity in the trade press.  The plant's output has been increasing and its
parent company has recently (in 1995) invested heavily in the plant. Whatever
the reason for aborting the interview there is no evidence that there has been
any adverse impact on the plants output or on new investment.</P>
<P>3.6 The other references by Mr Metcalfe and Ms Perry which relate to adverse
impacts concern inward investment and labour recruitment. The West Cumbria
Development Agency (WCDA) did claim <I>&quot;to be aware of two cases where the
proximity of Sellafield had been the deciding factor in companies choosing not
to locate in West Cumbria,&quot; </I>but two comments are relevant. First, the
WCDA would not name the companies and it is not possible, therefore, to verify
the substance of their claim. This is a concern, especially because the WCDA
wrongly attributed the 1980s closure to Sellafield (see para 3.3 above).</P>
<P>3.7 Second, even given its recorded concern that two inward investment
projects might have been lost by the proximity of Sellafield, COR/402 (para
4.37) makes it clear that WCDA still considered Sellafield to have a mainly
positive impact on local development.</P>
<P>3.8 Much the same point can be made over recruitment. One firm unprompted
and three firms prompted, reported that some job offers were turned down because
of the existence of Sellafield but this was restricted to some managerial posts
and was not a common occurrence. Even the plant who mentioned Sellafield
unprompted confined its comment to <I>&quot;managerial professional&quot; </I>staff
and bracketed with Sellafield a range of other factors which made it difficult
to recruit such staff. The other factors referred to were remoteness, career
advancement considerations and a bad perception of social facilities in terms of
<I>&quot;no football team, theatres, shopping centres etc&quot;. </I>For all
the firms interviewed these considerations are much more important than
Sellafield, whose main impact on recruitment is to raise local wage and salary
levels.</P>
<P>3.9 What is most apparent in the proofs of Mr Metcalfe and Ms Perry is that
they make no attempt to strike a balance on the basis of the existing evidence.
Thus they do not report any of the favourable impacts described in COR/402. For
example, they ignore the following evidence:</P>
<UL>
<LI> paragraphs 3.28/3.29 - reported increased investment and output resulting
from Sellafield
</LI>
<LI> paragraph 4.14 - beneficial impact of Sellafield on technology base, local
purchasing power and quality standards
</LI>
<LI> paragraphs 4.26/4.29 - beneficial impact of Sellafield on suppliers'
employment and standards, on the development of Westlakes Science Park and the
short-term benefits of additional construction work
</LI>
<LI> paragraph 4.30 - beneficial impact of Sellafield on the local economy
</LI>
<LI> paragraphs 4.32/4.33 - beneficial impact of Sellafield on inward
investment and technology transfer
</LI>
<LI> paragraph 4.37- BNFL's contribution to West Cumbria Development Fund and
to development of Westlakes Science Park
</LI>
<LI> paragraphs 4.42/4.43 - positive impact of Sellafield on employment and
economic activity
</LI>
<LI> paragraph 4.46- net positive impact of Sellafield on inward investment
</LI>
<LI> paragraph 4.50- potential beneficial impact of DRP.
</LI></UL>
<P>3.10 Nor do Mr Metcalfe or Ms Perry take into account the survey of other
areas with concentrations of nuclear facilities and the conclusion that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;There was no evidence from the survey of any significant long-term
adverse impact on local economic development in any of the areas considered&quot;
</I>[COR/402, para 6.50]</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>4. CONCLUSIONS</B></P>
<P>4.1 The arguments presented in regard to the alleged adverse socio-economic
impacts of Sellafield reduce to two basic propositions:</P>
<UL>
<LI> that local dependence on the nuclear industry is undesirable; and
</LI>
<LI> that such dependence inhibits the diversification of the economy through
reducing tourism and inward investment.
</LI></UL>
<P>4.2  There is no argument that West Cumbria and particularly those
communities adjacent to the Sellafield site, are heavily dependent on the
employment and income offered by the nuclear industry. This is clearly
recognised in my proof of evidence [NRX/10]. However, this is not unusual. Where
more remote, otherwise rural areas do succeed in attracting a major employer
they do become dependent on these employers became their very remoteness makes
them unattractive to a wide range of economic activity.</P>
<P>4.3 It follows from this, however, that the alternative is not the same
level of employment with many, diverse employers. The alternative is a much
lower level of employment, a net loss of people through out-migration and a
ageing population. That is, a remote, rural area which attracts a major
employer, particularly one which offers higher level skills and wages and
salaries, may be &quot;dependent&quot; on that major employer, but that is
preferable to the alternative.</P>
<P>4.4 Such an employer offers major benefits:</P>
<UL>
<LI> substantial direct employment
</LI>
<LI> wages and salaries above the local norm
</LI>
<LI> indirect and induced employment through the local sourcing of inputs by
the major employer and increased local purchasing power.
</LI></UL>
<P>4.5  The evidence is that the Sellafield site has produced all of these
benefits and on a very substantial scale. The nature and scale of these benefits
is clearly recognised by the local communities (see the NEMS study, C0R/410,
which shows very clear local recognition of the economic benefits resulting from
the Sellafield works).</P>
<P>4.6  I now turn to whether or not the existence of the nuclear industry does
inhibit the diversification of the local economy.</P>
<P>4.7 In one sense it must be expected to do so. To the extent that the
nuclear industry increases local employment and incomes it may have some impact
on the cost levels of some local employers. Similar considerations apply to the
local authorities and health services for whom rates of pay are determined by
reference to nationally determined scales. The other side of the same coin is
that there will be impacts on a wide range of local industries, particularly
supplying businesses and service activities. Here, as elsewhere, greater
economic prosperity and security of employment over a range of skilled jobs
brings stability, knowledge and expertise to the local area which would not
otherwise occur. These are of particular benefit to the local communities
adjacent to Sellafield.</P>
<P>4.8 Some impact on costs is always likely to be evident for a major employer
in a relatively small, remote community.  However, there is no evidence that the
scale of the &quot;problem&quot; is large in West Cumbria. Here, as elsewhere,
greater economic prosperity inevitably brings with it some costs. The evidence
is that the cost-benefit equation is massively to the benefit of the local
communities adjacent to Sellafield.</P>
<P>4.9  The proofs of evidence arguing against the RCF application suggest that
the existence of Sellafield has had a serious adverse impact on inward
investment and tourism. No new evidence is provided to support this assertion.
Even where an attempt is made to reinterpret the evidence (as with COR/406 and
COR/402) the reinterpretation is selective and contrary to the conclusions of
the authors of the report who did not report an adverse impact on inward
investment and tourism to set against the evident local benefits of higher
employment and higher income that Sellafield provides.</P>
<P><A NAME="Appendix"></A><B>APPENDIX  - CORRESPONDENCE</B></P>
<P><B>Letter 1</B></P>
<P><B>P</B><I>ieda</I> plc<BR>Planning, Economic and Development Consultants<BR><BR></P>
<P><BR>3 July 1995<BR>DIM/RR/7897<BR>Mr R A Hague<BR>Government Enterprise
Community Unit<BR>Department of Politics<BR>University of Newcastle-Upon-Tyne<BR>NEWCASTLE-UPON-TYNE<BR>NEl
7RU<BR><BR></P>
<P>Dear Mr Hague</P>
<P>Thank you for your prompt response to my fax message of 28 June contained in
your letter of 30 June. Your comments were most helpful and I apologise for not
picking up the typing error rate of 60%. Of course, it was intended to be 6%.</P>
<P>I attach herewith the text of my Proof which has been revised to try to take
account or your comments raised in your letter or 30 June. Would you please note
that the new paragraph numbers run from 5.53-5.63 instead of 5.51-5.61 as
previously.</P>
<P>In para 5.55 (old 5.53)1 have made amendments to reflect the comments in
your letter. </P>
<P>In 5.59 (old 5.57) 1 have also made amendments to reflect you comments.</P>
<P>I have rephrased<B> </B>5.62 (old 5.60) and hope that the new phrasing is
one which you would accept as being reasonable.</P>
<P>As regards 5.63 (old 5.61), I thought it best to let your report speak for
itself and have therefore summarised by utilising on a quote from your own
report.</P>
<P>In the light of these changes I hope you would now agree that the draft
Proof is an accurate summary of your December 1994 Report and I look forward to
hearing from you.</P>
<P>Yours sincerely</P>
<P>Professor Donald I MacKay</P>
<P>Chairman</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Letter 2</B></P>
<P>University of Newcastle<BR>Department of Politics</P>
<P>30 June 1995</P>
<P>Professor D Mackay<BR><B>P</B><I>ieda</I> plc<BR>10 Chester Street<BR>Edinburgh<BR>EH3
7RA</P>
<P>Dear Professor MacKay</P>
<P>Thank you for your fax message of 28 June. I was away from Newcastle
(examining in Edinburgh actually) when your enquiry arrived; my colleague Rick
Wylie and I have discussed the points you raise and our responses to your
questions are as follows:</P>
<P>Q1. You ask us whether your Draft Proof of Evidence is an accurate summary
of the conclusions in our December 1994 report. We reply section by section:</P>
<P>5.51  This is accurate.</P>
<P>5.52  This is accurate.</P>
<P>5.53  This is accurate, but we would make two minor points.</P>
<P>a) The reference to 212 companies involves a reanalysis by GECU of a survey
originally carried out by Scantel for the Cumbria Marketing initiative.</P>
<P>b) The focus group of Cumbria marketing Group did contain a representative
from Copeland Borough Council (participants were guaranteed anonymity; the
representative from Copeland was not, however, Mr Hellier).</P>
<P>5.54 and 5.55 We stand by the conclusions presented in the December 1994
report.</P>
<P>5.56  We don't know what Documents 4 and 6 refer to, and so cannot comment.</P>
<P>5.57  Two points here.</P>
<P>a) The conclusions on tourism were based on a survey involving 1,000
personal interviews (not 500).</P>
<P>b) There is a serious inaccuracy in the figure given in the quotation in
5.57. Line 5, paragraph 2 should read &quot;some 6%&quot; and not &quot;some 60%&quot;.
For the original figure, see May 1994 report 3.2.9 (page 22) where we give a
figure of 7%. In the December 1994 report, section 2.2.2 (page 11) we rounded
the percentages off and gave the figure as &quot;some 6%&quot;.</P>
<P>5.58 and 5.59 These paragraphs do not appear to refer to our research.</P>
<P>5.60 We would not put the distinction so hard and fast.  Some of our
questions <U>were</U> intended to tap people's risk perceptions about
Sellafield, though not specifically with reference to Nirex or the repository
project.</P>
<P>5.61 We would <U>not</U> subscribe to this view, on the basis of our
evidence.</P>
<P>Q2. Our considered view is that there are not substantive differences
between the conclusions offered in the interim report of May 1994 and those of
the final report in December 1994.  We would make just two points, however.</P>
<P>a). In May 1994, argued (section 4.0, page 25) that the nuclear industry &quot;should
be more actively promoted to position the area within the community of
organisations and individuals in the nuclear-related industries.&quot;  In other
words, we wish to argue that the isolation of West Cumbria is not a handicap so
far as the market for nuclear-related goods, services and technologies is
concerned.  In December 1994, we comment (Section 3.2, page 13) that &quot;the
aim should be not merely to educate West Cumbria about its distinguished
industrial heritage and coastal heritage but also, for example, to set BNFL
Sellafield in the context of the area's industrial development, which has once
again put it on the leading edge of technology.&quot;</P>
<P>There is no contradiction here.  These objectives are distinct but not
inconsistent.  The May 1994 report offered interim findings of our research. 
The aim of the December report was not only to present findings but also to
offer recommendations for a strategy to help solve the problem of West Cumbria's
image.</P>
<P>b). A point which emerged in the exchanges between the QC and Mr Hellier
concerns apparent differences in Tables between the May and December reports.
The data presented as four tables in the May 1994 (Tables 11 and 12) were
re-combined and presented as a single table, calibrated in whole numbers, in the
December 1994 report (table 11 refers) with an explanatory box clarifying the
findings.  The intention here was in no sense to minimise or conceal findings
related to Sellafield - indeed, Sellafield is more clearly shown to be a
negative influence in the December document - but to emphasise the relative
weakness of tourists' perceptions of West Cumbria (whether positive or
negative), other than as an extension of the Lake District (coded in this
question as the natural environment inland).</P>
<P>Q3. Mr Hellier's remark about 'significant editorial control' is unfounded
and quite gratuitous.  From the initial framing of the research questions,
through execution, analysis and final presentation, the research project was
under the control of Mr Wylie, myself and Sir Bernard Ingham (Honorary Director
of the Government Enterprise Communication Unit, who led the presentation on the
report at the West Cumbria Development Agency's offices in Workington on
December 7 1994).  The West Cumbria Development Fund (and BNFL, as the major
financial sponsor of the Fund) were kept informed of the research as it
developed, but at no stage was there any 'editorial control' exercised or
attempted.</P>
<P>Please do not hesitate to contact either Rick Wylie or myself, if we can be
of any further assistance.</P>
<P>Yours sincerely,</P>
<P>R.A. Hague</P>
<P>Senior Lecturer in Politics</P>
<P>Deputy Director, GECU</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Letter 3</B></P>
<P><B>P</B><I>ieda</I> plc<BR>Planning, Economic and Development Consultants<BR><BR></P>
<P><BR>3 July 1995<BR>DIM/RR/7897<BR>Mr R A Haig<BR>Government Enterprise
Community Unit<BR>Department of Politics<BR>University of Newcastle-Upon-Tyne<BR>NEWCASTLE-UPON-TYNE<BR>NEl
7RU<BR><BR></P>
<P>Dear Mr Haig</P>
<P>You may recall that I spoke to you by telephone on 16 June concerning the
report &quot;Perceptions of West Cumbria as a Destination for Tourism and Inward
Investment&quot;.  I explained that I was representing Nirex in the forthcoming
Inquiry on the Rock Characterisation Facility and that in my Proof of Evidence I
would be drawing upon your report.  I also explained that at the recent Public
Inquiry into the Copeland Local Plan, Mr R B Hellier, who is the Head of
Economic Development and Local Plans for Copeland Borough Council, gave evidence
relating to your report and your previous presentation of your interim results
in May 1994.</P>
<P>I have now had an opportunity to consider in detail what Mr Hellier had to
say and I have also now had access to his Proof of Evidence at the Public
Inquiry into the Copeland Local Plan.  I attach the relevant sections of his
Proof of Evidence which relate to para 4.9 and to the accompanying Appendix
which appears to come directly from your May 1994 presentation.</P>
<P>Of greater significance I attach what Mr Hellier said in his
cross-examination by Mr Robin Barratt QC who is acting on behalf of Nirex.  The
relevant attachments are from the transcript and relate to pages 47-57.  This is
followed by the re-examination of Mr Hellier by Mr Hockman representing Copeland
Borough Council.  The relevant part of the transcript is pages 57-63.</P>
<P>For your purpose possibly the most important pages are pages 49-50 and page
62.</P>
<P>Mr Hellier seems to be saying that the data provided in your May 1994
presentation are difficult to reconcile with the conclusions of your December
1994 report and, further, that the difference he claims to detect is a
consequence of &quot;significant editorial control&quot; over your final report.
 You will note that Mr Barratt acting for Nirex puts the point that Mr Hellier
does not make reference in his answers to the conclusions you reached in May
1994 presentation and that these conclusions are very close to those presented
in your December 1994 report.  In short, Mr Hellier did not refer in his
evidence to your conclusions but, rather, drew his own conclusions from your
evidence.</P>
<P>I also enclose paras 5.51-5.61 from my draft Proof of Evidence which will be
part of Nirex's case at the Inquiry on the Rock Characterisation Facility.  This
seeks to summarise the conclusions reached in your December 1994 report.</P>
<P>I would be grateful if you could respond to the following questions:</P>
<OL>
<LI> Is my draft Proof of Evidence an accurate summary of the conclusions
reached in your December 1994 report?
</LI>
<LI> Do you believe there are any substantive differences between the
conclusions reached in your December 1994 report and your interim conclusions
reached in your May 1994 presentation?  If so, could you explain what factors
caused you to revise your conclusions?
</LI>
<LI> How do you respond to Mr Hellier's view that &quot;significant editorial
control&quot; was exercised over your final report?
</LI></OL>
<P>I have copied this letter to your colleague Mr R Wyllie who I also spoke to
on 16 June and who I understand carried out the bulk of the research.  I have
written to you both because I have drawn on your report for my proof and wish to
ensure that I have reported its conclusions accurately.  It is now quite urgent
that my Proof is finalised and I wonder if it would be possible to respond to
the above questions no later than Tuesday 4 July.</P>
<P>Yours sincerely,</P>
<P>Professor Donald I MacKay</P>
<P>Chairman</P>
