<P><B>CHRISTOPHER HERBERT BALCH will say:
</B></P>
<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1. PERSONAL DETAILS
</B></P>
<P>1.1 I hold the degrees of Master of Arts in Geography from the University of
Cambridge and Master of Philosophy in Urban Design and Regional Planning from
the University of Edinburgh. I am a Corporate Member of the Royal Town Planning
Institute and a Professional Associate of the Royal Institution of Chartered
Surveyors, being a Crawter, Galsworthy and Gilchrist prizewinner.
</P>
<P>1.2 I am a Director of Pieda plc, Planning, Economic and Development
Consultants with responsibilities for the planning and environmental consultancy
of the firm's English offices. Pieda regularly advises clients in central and
local government, development agencies and corporations and private companies on
the planning aspects of development proposals.
</P>
<P>1.3 I have directed a number of Department of the Environment Planning
Research projects and was principal author of a report concerned with evaluating
the effectiveness of land use planning. I have extensive experience in the field
of economic regeneration and tourism. I was responsible for preparatory work
leading to the establishment of the Leeds Development Corporation and have acted
as a Consultant to the World Tourism Organization.
</P>
<P>1.4 I have personally been involved in advising on the planning issues
associated with radioactive waste disposal for some fifteen years. My experience
covers:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Advising on planning appeals by the then United Kingdom Atomic Energy
Authority (UKAEA), against refusal of planning permission for test drilling as
part of a research programme into hard rock formations in South West Scotland
(Loch Doon area) and the Northumberland National Park (Cheviot Hills);
</LI>
<LI>Advising on the planning and environmental aspects of the Natural
Environment Research Council's Institute of Geological Sciences' research
programme into argillaceous formations in England and Wales;
</LI>
<LI>Advising United Kingdom Nirex Limited ('Nirex') on the planning and
non-nuclear environmental aspects of their programme to identify and investigate
sites for near surface and deep disposal of low and intermediate level
radioactive wastes;
</LI>
<LI>Advising Nirex on the planning and non-nuclear environmental aspects of
their programme to establish a national deep repository for low and intermediate
level wastes which is now focused upon investigations of the Borrowdale Volcanic
Group ('BVG') inland of British Nuclear Fuels plc's ('BNFL') Sellafield Works;
and
</LI>
<LI>Assisting Nirex in the preparation of environmental assessments of
applications for the drilling of exploratory geological boreholes in the
Sellafield area, including the presentation of expert planning evidence with
respect to their appeals against refusal to permit exploratory drilling in the
Lake District National Park.
</LI></UL>
<P>1.5 Since October 1992, I have directed a multi-disciplinary team employed
by Nirex to advise on the planning and non-nuclear environmental implications of
the RCF development at Longlands Farm, Gosforth. Pieda and its sub-consultants,
RPS Cairns, Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, W S Atkins and the Centre for
Field Archaeology assisted Nirex in the preparation of an environmental
statement accompanying the application for the RCF.
</P>
<P>1.6 I am therefore familiar with the application which is the subject of
this appeal and with the surrounding area.</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B> 2. SUMMARY
</B></P>
<P>2.1 This proof of evidence addresses the planning issues raised by the
appeal and deals with the effect of the RCF on land use and recreation.
</P>
<P>Nature of the Development
</P>
<P>2.2 The proposed RCF development involves mineral exploration, the deposit
of waste on land and the construction of buildings. The purpose of the
development is the carrying out of searches and tests into the geology and
hydrogeology of the Borrowdale Volcanic Group ('BVG').
</P>
<P>2.3 The RCF is part of the extensive science programme that will enable
Nirex to decide whether or not to make a planning application to develop a
repository for disposal of radioactive waste and to produce a full assessment of
post-closure safety.
</P>
<P>Planning History of Nirex's Programme of Investigation at Sellafield
</P>
<P>2.4 The history of Nirex's programme of research in the Sellafield area
demonstrates that geological and hydrogeological investigations have been deemed
acceptable in planning terms.
</P>
<P>2.5 An initial appeal decision in 1991, reinforced by a further decision in
1993 in the more stringent conditions of the Lake District National Park,
established that:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Proposals should be judged in terms of their local environmental and
amenity impacts and not in terms of any hypothetical future development; and
</LI>
<LI>Where conflict with policy arises this may be justified in terms of the &quot;need&quot;
for investigations which are recognised as being of national importance.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.6 Cumbria County Council adopted this approach in granting consent for the
RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole developments at Longlands Farm. However in refusing consent
for the RCF itself, the County Council have departed from precedent arguing that
the development needs to be fully justified as a &quot;halfway&quot; commitment
to the development of a repository at Sellafield.
</P>
<P>Statutory Development Plan Policy
</P>
<P>2.7 At the time of the determination of the application and the submission
of the Appeal, the Statutory Development Plan was:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The Approved Structure Plan (Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan
1st Alteration); and
</LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI>The Adopted Local Plan (Mid Copeland Local Plan).
</LI></UL>
<P>2.8 The RCF satisfied the requirements of and generally accorded with these
development plan policies.
</P>
<P>2.9 In relation to Policy C1 of the Approved Structure Plan, the development
is in accordance with Government policy and offers very clear social and
economic benefits, nationally and locally, which outweigh any environmental harm
caused.
</P>
<P>2.10 In relation to Policy C6 of the Approved Structure Plan, it has been
shown that there is clear justification and need for the development which
outweighs any temporary environmental harm caused; the proposal goes as far as
is practicable in minimising adverse impacts and producing longer term benefits;
and that the development would not directly affect the appearance or character
of the National Park; and that there are no alternatives to an RCF at Longlands
Farm to obtain in situ information to reduce uncertainties and gaps in knowledge
about the PRZ at Sellafield.
</P>
<P>2.11 Policy 6C of the Adopted Local Plan gives general support to Nirex's
programme of investigations which is aimed at identifying a site for the deep
disposal of radioactive waste.
</P>
<P><B>Other Material Considerations
</B></P>
<P>Emerging Development Plan Policies
</P>
<P>2.12 The emerging Development Plans policies are contained in:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The Draft Replacement Structure Plan (Cumbria and Lake District Structure
Plan 1991 to 2006). This will have become part of the Statutory Development Plan
shortly before the commencement of this Inquiry; and
</LI>
<LI>Copeland Borough Local Plan Deposit Version (Deposit Draft Local Plan)
which has been through a Local Plan Inquiry. The Inspector's Report is currently
awaited.
</LI></UL>
<P>Evidence shows that the development is generally in accord with the relevant
policies, indeed the Deposit Draft Local Plan specifically provides for
development of the RCF in the countryside, subject to the terms of Deposit
Policy ENV33 and the Council's proposed changes to it.
</P>
<P>2.13 In relation to Policy 2 of the Replacement Structure Plan, the RCF is
not an inappropriate form of development and does not have an unacceptable
affect on key conservation interests.
</P>
<P>2.14 The RCF is not in conflict with Policies 5 and 11 as it will not
directly affect the scenic beauty and landscape qualities of the Lake District
National Park either in the short or longer term.
</P>
<P>2.15 In relation to Policy 13 the RCF meets an important need which cannot
be met other than in a countryside location. The site of the RCF is not covered
by any landscape designation and the development will produce clear benefits
which outweigh any temporary environmental harm it will cause. Policies DEV1 and
ENV33 of the Deposit Draft Local Plan make provision for the RCF to be located
in open countryside.
</P>
<P>2.16 Given the nature of the development and the agreed approach to
landscape treatment, the RCF does not conflict with Policy 25, which is
inappropriately cited in the County Council's reasons for refusal.
</P>
<P>2.17 The RCF is a major development, encompassed by Policy 54 of the Draft
Replacement Structure Plan. The information produced by Nirex shows that the
national, regional and local benefits which flow from the development clearly
outweigh any harm or risks to the local or wider environment as required by
Clause i.
</P>
<P>2.18 It has been accepted that the development will be carried out in such a
manner as to cause least practical harm (Clause ii) and that adverse impact
during construction and operation will be minimised (Clause iii).
</P>
<P>2.19 It has been shown that the RCF will not have a detrimental effect upon
the present characteristics and qualities of the landscape of the National Park.
It is therefore concluded that the RCF fulfils the tests set out in Policy 54.
Policy 57 is concerned with nuclear development which the RCF is not.
</P>
<P>2.20 Policy DEV1 of the Deposit Draft Local Plan seeks to limit development
in the countryside, subject to certain exceptions. These include the
construction of an RCF. Indeed, Policy ENV33 of the Deposit Draft Local Plan
indicates that the local planning authority will support the development of an
RCF subject to it meeting certain criteria.
</P>
<P>Weight to be Attached to Policies
</P>
<P>2.21 I conclude that the greatest weight should be attached to the policies
of the Statutory Development Plan with which the development conforms.
</P>
<P>2.22 The policies of the Replacement Structure Plan, have been through all
the stages of plan preparation and are about to be adopted. They are not subject
to outstanding objections. The proposed development broadly conforms with these
policies.
</P>
<P>2.23 While less weight should be applied to the Copeland Local Plan Deposit
Version those policies which relate to the RCF proposal are not subject to
fundamental objection and should therefore be accorded some consideration.
</P>
<P> 2.24 On the basis of my assessment of the development against the policies
in the Statutory Development Plan and of emerging policies I therefore believe
that planning consent should be granted in accordance with the requirements of
Section 54A. This view is confirmed when account is taken of other factors.
</P>
<P>Government Policy
</P>
<P>2.25 It has been shown that the investigation of the Sellafield area has the
support of Government policy on radioactive waste management which has recently
reaffirmed support for deep disposal and continued site investigations. In the
White Paper which was published on the 4th July 1995 the Governments sets out
its view that the RCF is part of Nirex's programme of investigations aimed at
selecting a repository site, and that a full public inquiry will be held into an
application for the repository itself, wherever it may be situated.
</P>
<P>Form and Siting of the RCF
</P>
<P>2.26 It has been shown that the form and siting of the RCF is appropriate to
the function which it is intended to fulfil. No alternative site or form has
been suggested for the RCF, which has taken into account local environmental
factors.
</P>
<P>Environmental Impact
</P>
<P>2.27 In terms of environmental impact it has been concluded that:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">1)</TD>
<TD>The RCF can be accommodated into the landscape without significant adverse
effect. It does not directly impinge on the Lake District National Park and will
not be detrimental to the present character and qualities of the Park;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>2)</TD>
<TD>Beyond short term disruption to two rights of way during the establishment
of Services Corridors, the RCF will not have any effect on public access and
recreation;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>3)</TD>
<TD>The agricultural land affected by the development is mostly Grade 3B and
not subject to special protection. Restoration proposals will allow the site to
be returned to productive agriculture, save for the loss of a small area to
landscape planting;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>4)</TD>
<TD>The proposal will not directly affect designated nature conservation sites.
Indeed the area is of no special ecological interest. Measures to control
effluent and limit drainage will give adequate protection to a population of
Natterjack toads some kilometres from the site. Measures will be adopted to
mitigate the effect of loss of, and reduced accessibility to, ground used by
badgers for foraging;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>5)</TD>
<TD>The loss of one minor archaeological feature will be of low significance;
and,
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>6)</TD>
<TD>Air quality, water quality and noise and vibration levels in the vicinity
of the sites will be well below established standards. The local residents at
nearby premises will not experience a nuisance due to these factors during site
construction or operation.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>Highways Impact
</P>
<P>2.28 The increase in traffic flows as a result of the development will be
within the increase that can be expected due to national growth on surrounding
roads over the planned life of the development. Adequate highway and junction
capacity exists to serve the site.
</P>
<P>Socio-Economic Impact
</P>
<P>2.29 The socio-economic impact of the RCF will be unambiguously positive,
creating and generating nearly 1,690 man years of employment to the benefit of
the local area. There is no evidence that the RCF will inhibit inward investment
and tourism to West Cumbria.
</P>
<P>Conclusion
</P>
<P>2.30 Overall, the RCF will provide very clear benefits in terms of:
</P>
<UL>
<LI> Helping to secure a long term solution to the safe disposal of the
nation's low and intermediate level radioactive waste. In this regard the RCF is
fundamental to one of the principles of sustainable development in that it will
provide the information necessary for this and future generations to take
decisions about the long term protection of the environment;
</LI>
<LI>Assisting Nirex in deciding whether or not to make a planning application
for a deep repository in the Sellafield area and to produce a full assessment of
post closure safety; and
</LI>
<LI>Supporting local employment and income for the duration of the development.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.31 The national and local benefit which will result from the development
which is in general accordance with the provisions of both statutory and
emerging development plans clearly outweighs the limited and temporary
environmental effects which may arise. In my opinion there is a clear case for
consent to be granted.
</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3. BACKGROUND AND SCOPE
</B></P>
<P><B>Background
</B></P>
<P>3.1 In 1992, following Nirex's decision to pursue its investigations into
the suitability of the Sellafield area for a Deep Waste Repository ('DWR')
through the construction of an RCF, Pieda were requested to assist with the
preparation of an environmental statement. The purpose of this was to accompany
a future planning application to be submitted to Cumbria County Council. The
work took place against the background of previous research which had been
undertaken since 1989 to evaluate and assess the suitability of Sellafield as a
potential location for a DWR.
</P>
<P>3.2 Throughout this period, Pieda and its sub-consultants have:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Collected baseline information on local environmental conditions;
</LI>
<LI>Assisted Nirex with consultations with local interests, including the local
authorities;
</LI>
<LI>Advised Nirex on the non-nuclear environmental implications of proposals
which it might bring forward for a DWR in the Sellafield area; and
</LI>
<LI>Monitored and, where appropriate, commented upon the development of County
and Borough planning policies.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Scope
</B></P>
<P>3.3 It is against this background that I present evidence to the Inquiry on
behalf of Nirex. I will address the planning issues raised by the appeal, and
deal with the effect of the proposed RCF on land use and recreation.
</P>
<P>3.4 In presenting my planning evidence I will refer to the evidence of other
witnesses appearing on behalf of Nirex.</P>
<P><A NAME="History"></A><B>4. PLANNING HISTORY OF NIREX'S PROGRAMME OF
INVESTIGATION AT SELLAFIELD
</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction
</B></P>
<P>4.1 In this section of my evidence I examine the planning history
surrounding Nirex's programme of geological investigations in the Sellafield
area, focusing on past decisions and upon the planning authorities'
consideration of the appeal proposal.
</P>
<P><B>Regional Boreholes
</B></P>
<P>4.2 In 1988, British Nuclear Fuels plc, acting as agent for Nirex, applied
to Cumbria County Council for consent for temporary engineering works; involving
the drilling of a geological exploratory borehole at Sellafield, Seascale,
Cumbria. The application was refused by the Council on the grounds that it was
premature and part of a scheme directed to the importation of radioactive waste
into Cumbria, leading to a prejudicial impact on policies designed to attract
further industry and tourism. An appeal was made to the Secretary of State for
the Environment to be determined on the basis of written representations.
</P>
<P>4.3 The Visiting Officer in his report recommended that the appeal should be
allowed. He dismissed the argument that the planning assessment of the proposal
should be based on the premise that it was an integral component of a further
scheme directed to the importation of radioactive waste to Cumbria and stated
that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;the planning consideration of this proposal should be focused on
its local environmental impact.&quot; [COR/201](1)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.4 The Secretary of State for the Environment accepted these conclusions
and issued a decision letter on 21 March 1989 upholding the appeal. Within this
letter the Secretary of State noted that: 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;the temporary use of the site to drill an exploratory borehole
would do no more than provide accurate information about the underlying
geological structure which would assist in the formulation of policies and
proposals about the possible future use of the site. He considers that the
present proposal should therefore be considered solely on the basis of its local
environmental impact.&quot; [COR/201](2)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.5 The timing of this decision coincided with the Secretary of State's
statement to the House of Commons in which he expressed the Government's support
for Nirex's recommendation that detailed geological studies should be undertaken
in the vicinity of Sellafield and Dounreay to enable it to decide on their
suitability as potential repository sites. The Secretary of State made it clear
that Nirex would have to obtain the necessary planning permissions through the
normal procedures and that only when these investigations had been undertaken
would Nirex be in a position to submit proposals for a substantive development
and seek the necessary approvals. [GOV/210](3)
</P>
<P>4.6 The significance of this decision was clearly recognised by Cumbria
County Council who have subsequently granted consent for a further 11 regional
boreholes. The extent and location of these operations is shown in
<A HREF="#Table4.1">Table 4.1</A> and Figure 1.2 of the Environmental Statement
[COR/101](4). In only one case, Borehole 11, was consent withheld. In this case,
however it was possible to identify an alternative site (Borehole 11A) which
could overcome concerns with local environmental impact.
</P>
<P>National Park Boreholes
</P>
<P>4.7 In April 1992, Nirex were refused planning consent by the Lake District
National Park Special Planning Board for investigatory boreholes at two sites
within the National Park on the grounds that the developments would have:
</P>
<UL>
<LI> <I>&quot;an unacceptable harmful effect on the landscape which would be
out of keeping and out of character in this sensitive western area of the Lake
District National Park. Accordingly, the proposal would be contrary to Structure
Plan Policy C2
</I></LI>
<LI><I>the noise and disturbance likely to accrue from the development as a
whole and the drilling in particular would have an adverse effect on the
residential amenities enjoyed by nearby residents
</I></LI>
<LI><I>the impact of the conditions necessary to meet road safety standards
and the additional traffic generated on the narrow country roads,
</I></LI>
<LI><I>would change the character and appearance of these roads to the overall
detriment of the area and contrary to Structure Plan Policy T6 of the approved
Structure Plan.&quot; [COR/201](5)
</I></LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="Table4.1"></A></P>
