<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">2.2</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">18</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">02/06/92</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">06/10/92</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="-1">further testing at site permitted for four
years</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">Holmrk. 13</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">050 035</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">0.34</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">60</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">23/05/94</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">01/02/95</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="-1">five year permission includes monitoring</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD COLSPAN="7"><FONT SIZE="-1"><SUP>1</SUP> Total site area includes the
surface area beneath which the inclined borehole passes.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>4.8 Following these refusals, Nirex submitted alternative applications
involving the use of a shorter rig (22 metres rather than 49 metres) and in the
case of Borehole 9, a more sheltered site (Borehole 9A). However, the Lake
District Special Planning Board maintained their objection and refused consent
for these applications, in October 1992, on similar grounds.
</P>
<P>4.9 A public local inquiry was held between 24th November and 8th December
1992, and the Inspector's decision was issued on 11th February 1993.
[COR/201](6) He dismissed two of the appeals on the basis that alternative
applications had been submitted which met the identified need in a less visually
intrusive manner.
</P>
<P>4.10 In allowing the alternative appeals, the Inspector reaffirmed the
planning approach used in reaching the appeal decision on Borehole 1. He
identified the key issues as:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">1)</TD>
<TD>How the need for the boreholes measures up to the tests laid down by
national and local policy in relation to development proposed within National
Parks.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>2)</TD>
<TD>The effect that each proposal would have on: those living near the borehole
sites by virtue of the noise and traffic generated; the safety and amenity of
local roads in the vicinity of Gosforth; the visual amenity and landscape of the
National Park; and on other conservation interests.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>3)</TD>
<TD>In the light of the conclusions on the environmental and amenity effects
involved, the acceptability of the proposals against Structure Plan Policy C6.
[COR/201](7)
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>4.11 In relation to need the Inspector stated that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;I am in no doubt that detailed and thorough geological and
hydrogeological investigations are an essential part of the process of
developing a convincing safety case, and I consider it to be in the national
interest to pursue geological investigations at this site to the extent that it
is necessary to either rule it out or to verify that a cogent safety case can be
produced.&quot; [COR/201](8)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>He concluded that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;the exploratory phases of the repository project are sufficiently
exceptional for there to be a good case in national terms for proceeding with
two boreholes within the Park.&quot; [COR/201](9)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.12 The Inspector's decision was guided by environmental and amenity
considerations and particular attention was paid to the guidance on National
Parks set out in PPG 7. [GOV/102](10) This Guidance Note reiterates the two
statutory purposes of National Parks: the conservation of the natural beauty of
the countryside and the promotion of their public enjoyment; it states that the
conservation of the natural beauty of the countryside is to be given great
weight in planning policies and in development control decisions; and it points
out that special considerations apply to major development proposals which are
more national than local in character and that such development should not take
place in National Parks save in exceptional circumstances.
</P>
<P>4.13 The Inspector went on to point out that PPG 7 states that proposals
which are more national than local in character must be subject to the most
rigorous examination, and be shown to be in the public interest before being
allowed to proceed. Consideration of such projects should include an assessment
of the need for the development in terms of national considerations, and the
impact of permitting or refusing it on the local economy; the cost of and scope
for developing elsewhere outside the area or of meeting the need for it in some
other way; and any detrimental effect on the environment and the extent to which
that should be moderated.
</P>
<P>4.14 Applying these stringent tests the Inspector concluded that two of the
appeals relating to the taller rigs and the more exposed site (Borehole 9)
should be dismissed, but that given the need for the development in national
terms, the environmental harm caused by the two alternatives was not so serious
as to justify their rejection. Accordingly he upheld the appeals on Borehole
Site 8A and 9A, imposing some 27 and 22 conditions respectively.
</P>
<P><B>RCF Boreholes
</B></P>
<P>4.15 By the time the Public Inquiry into the boreholes in the Lake District
National Park took place in November 1992, Nirex had announced its intention to
proceed with its investigations of the potential repository zone at Sellafield
by means of a Rock Characterisation Facility. [COR/504](11)
</P>
<P>4.16 In November 1992, Nirex submitted an application to Cumbria County
Council (Application 4/92/9023) for some eight deep boreholes on land at
Longlands Farm, near Gosforth, part of which forms the subject of this appeal.
These referred to as Boreholes RCF1, RCF2, RCF3, RCF4, RCM1, RCM2, RCM3 and RCM4
were intended to help in finalising the location and planning for the
construction of the RCF. A further application (Application 4/92/9024) was
submitted for five, out of a possible ten, PRZ boreholes, intended to establish
a ring of monitoring boreholes around the potential repository zone to provide
baseline data prior to any underground excavation. <A HREF="#Table4.2">Table
4.2</A> and Figure 2.11 of the Environmental Statement provide information on
the scale and location of these applications. [COR/101](12)
</P>
<P><A NAME="Table4.2"></A></P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
