<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">25/05/93</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="-1">post drilling works permitted to continue for
four years</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>4.17 In a report of the 31st March 1993, the County Planning Officer
examined the strategic planning issues which were considered relevant to these
applications. It was concluded that given the lack of any landscape designation
covering Longlands Farm, only Approved Structure Plan Policy C1, and Replacement
Structure Plan Policy 13 could strictly be applied. However, it was argued that
the development of the RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes series was of sufficient impact and
national significance for it to be more appropriately considered as a major
development and thus evaluated against Approved Policy C6 and Replacement Policy
54. Indeed the Planning Officer stated that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;In my judgement the proposals will, in the short term, have
greater impact on the countryside near Gosforth than any subsequent RCF or
repository development both visually and in terms of traffic.&quot; [COR201](13)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.18 The County Planning Officer went on to argue that while the proposals
do not involve nuclear materials, they are a step towards and caused by the
intended development of a deep repository and so could appropriately be judged
against some aspects of Replacement Policy 57 which deals with nuclear
reprocessing and waste disposal. Accordingly the Planning Officer indicated that
the proposals should be judged in terms of:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Evidence that it is the &quot;best practical environmental option
in terms of location &quot;. In other words that the development cannot be
located elsewhere Replacement Policy 56i(a).
</I></P>
<P><I>Whether...national....benefits outweigh.....harm to the
local.....environment - Replacement Policy 53i(b).
</I></P>
<P><I>Whether the scheme will be carried out in such a manner as to cause
least practicable harm - Replacement Policy 53ii(c) and 56vi(d), with both
direct and indirect impacts....minimised - Replacement Policy 53iii(e).
</I></P>
<P><I>Whether there is adequate provision of infrastructure - Draft
Replacement Policy 56iii&quot;(f). [COR/20](14)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.19 In considering the issue of location the Planning Officer pointed to
the dilemma the County Council faced in that it did not want any approval to be
seen as prejudicing its strenuous campaign for a wide ranging public inquiry or
planning inquiry commission into the whole question of repository site selection
and government policy. At the same time, however, it was faced with advice from
its consultants, ERL, and the Radioactive Waste Management Advisory Committee,
which supported the need for yet further investigation. Indeed the Planning
Officer stated that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;in situ characterisation of the repository zone, initially
through this borehole programme, will be essential in deciding whether to commit
to the RCF and subsequently to development of a repository site near the
Sellafield site. On its own the regional borehole data is not considered likely
to provide sufficient information to confirm suitability one way or another.
Taken generally, this implies a 'need' for the boreholes, the subject of this
application, which would override any other strategic objections including
disturbance due to the scale if development in the open countryside near
Gosforth&quot;[COR/201](15)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.20 The Planning Officer went on to quote the decision of the Inspector in
relation to the boreholes in the Lake District National Park, and concluded:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;In the light of this precedent in the more demanding
circumstances of a National Park, it would be difficult to justify refusal,
taking the RCF/RCM/PRZ boreholes in isolation.&quot;[COR/201](16)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>He therefore advised that the applications should be supported, given that
the national context and the precedents set, offer no effective strategic policy
grounds to justify refusal.
</P>
<P>4.21 The Planning Officer considered the harm which the boreholes would
cause to the local environment, the manner of the development and the provision
of infrastructure. He again concluded:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;It is my view that, despite its significant local impacts, this
further major additional step in the borehole programme, taken in isolation
would be difficult to resist. I do not consider that there are strategic policy
grounds which could be used to justify refusal, given the overriding national
context for the proposals. I am also satisfied that the works and access
arrangements now proposed go as far as can be reasonably required in minimising
local impact. However, the question remains as to how far these applications
should be seen as the first stage in the development of the RCF, rather than as
a preliminary to it.&quot; [COR/201](17)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>On the basis of the advice given, the planning application for boreholes
related to the RCF were approved by full Council in May 1993.
</P>
<P><B>RCF Application
</B></P>
<P>4.22 Nirex submitted its planning application (Application 4/94/9011) for
the construction of a Rock Characterisation Facility at Longlands Farm, Gosforth
to Cumbria County Council on the 29th July 1994. The application was accompanied
by an Environmental Statement [COR/101](18), which Nirex accepted in its letter
of the 8th September 1994, falls within the meaning of Schedule 2 para 2(b) of
the Town and County Planning (Assessment of Environmental Effects) Regulations
1988 on the basis that the development involves deep drilling. [NRX/11/1](19).
</P>
<P>4.23 On the 3rd October 1994, the County Council's Head of Planning wrote to
Nirex indicating that while they were broadly content with the level of
information provided in the Environmental Statement [NRX/11/1](20), they were
not satisfied, however, that the material provided showed how the Sellafield
area came to be the sole focus of detailed investigation. A formal request was
made for the release of additional detailed material to the County Council
concerning the detailed reasoning for the Company's decision to focus attention
on Sellafield. A further letter on the 24th October set out a request for
additional information covering geological and safety assessment issues.
[NRX/11/1](21)
</P>
<P>4.24 Nirex responded to the County Council in letters dated the 22nd and
24th November, [NRX/11/1](22,23) providing additional information. In its letter
of the 22nd November, Nirex indicated its view that the information requested
was not material to the RCF application, stressing that the purpose of the RCF
is to allow further scientific investigation of the Sellafield area.
Notwithstanding this position however, Nirex provided the County Council with a
note entitled `Disposal of Intermediate and Low Level Waste: Deep Repository
Programme, Comparison and Ranking of Siting Options' [COR/104](24) and a note
entitled `Deep Disposal of Radioactive Waste; Geological Indicators of Potential
Suitability of Sellafield Site. [COR/104](25). In its letter of the 24th
November, Nirex set out a list of technical reports which it intended to publish
covering safety assessment of geological investigations, in addition to material
previously made available to the County Council. On this basis the Director of
Economy and Environment reported to an Extraordinary Meeting of Cumbria County
Council on 20th December, called to consider and determine the RCF planning
application. [COR/104](26)
</P>
<P>4.25 Following examination of the purpose of the RCF, a description of the
development and a review of consultation replies, letters of representation
received, public meetings and an Opinion Survey, the report set out a two part
planning assessment of the proposals. Part One assessed the application against
the policies of the Replacement Structure Plan. No assessment was undertaken
against the policies of the Statutory Development Plan. The assessment focused
upon the following issues:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Impacts on the open countryside, landscape and adjacent National Park;
</LI>
<LI>Impact on the local environment and amenity, including the road network;
</LI>
<LI>Whether any impacts have been reduced to the minimum practicable;
</LI>
<LI>Impacts on the social and economic well being of West Cumbria; and
</LI>
<LI>Whether in the event of the proposal being out of accord with policies in
the Structure Plan, the applicant has convincing reasons for the development
proceeding.
</LI></UL>
<P>4.26 In relation to countryside and landscape issues, the report concluded
that the:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;RCF is a major development, industrial in character, in the open
countryside and would undoubtedly have an adverse visual impact on the
surrounding area including the National Park.&quot; [COR/104](27)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>However, the report acknowledged that Nirex had gone as far as practicable
in minimising the development's impact on the landscape, and that the current
proposals were temporary (about 12 years overall).
</P>
<P>4.27 In relation to environmental and amenity impacts the report concluded
that there are no ecology, archaeology, land quality and restoration, air
quality, water quality, noise and vibration or highways matters which could not
be resolved and covered by condition or agreement in the event of approval.
</P>
<P>4.28 The assessment acknowledged that Nirex has minimised the environmental
impacts from the RCF development as far as practicable and concluded that in
planning terms the impact of surface development for an additional five years
for Phase 2 and Phase 3 of the experimental programme is not so great as to
justify the restriction of the proposal to Phase 1 only.
</P>
<P>4.29 In examining the social and economic impacts of the RCF, the report
acknowledged the positive impacts highlighted in the Environmental Statement,
and the commitment to local training, employment and use of local contractors
wherever possible. It accepted the possibility that with adequate explanation
the development will not have an adverse impact on local employment or tourism.
However the report indicated that the issue of public perception needs to be
addressed, and that this may best be achieved through a public inquiry to test
the proposals in a `transparent' manner.
</P>
<P>4.30 The second part of the planning assessment then went on to assess
whether there are convincing reasons for the development to proceed to override
conflict with countryside, landscape and National Park policies. In planning
terms the report suggested this should be reduced to a central question - is
there a necessity to have this development on this particular site? The report
examined this in the following terms:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Does the RCF proposal sit within a clear national policy context and is it
consistent with it?
</LI>
<LI>Can the focus of investigation on a site at Sellafield be justified?
</LI>
<LI>Is there a reasonable prospect of making a safety case at this site?
</LI></UL>
<P>4.31 The report argued that given the reviews being undertaken of the
nuclear industry and radioactive waste management policy by Government, there
was no clear national policy context within which the RCF proposal can sit. It
acknowledged, however, that this would be significantly changed, especially if
the draft policy basis was affirmed.
</P>
<P>4.32 In relation to site selection, while acknowledging Nirex's contrary
view, the report argued that the RCF represented a `halfway' commitment to the
development of a repository at Sellafield, and that the choice therefore needed
to be fully justified in planning terms. The Planning Officer expressed the view
that while the information provided by Nirex offered:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;significant new insight into the focusing process it does not, of
itself provide sufficient detail on which to be satisfied that the site has
properly become the sole focus of attention.&quot; [COR/104](28)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.33 In addressing the issue of whether there is a reasonable prospect of
making a safety case at the Sellafield site, the report expressed concern about
the amount of publicly available information, particularly related to the Post
Closure Safety Assessment. However it acknowledged the recommendations of ERM
that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;proper assessment of a site for the long term disposal of
radioactive waste needs to include a stage of underground experimentation and
validation in the form of some facility resembling a URL (Underground Rock
Laboratory). The timing of such a stage has generally been considered to be at
the early stage of repository construction&quot; [COR/104](29)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The report concluded that the information at hand had not yet provided
convincing reasons for proceeding with the RCF, sufficient to overcome the
concerns expressed in the advice received.
</P>
<P>4.34 In summing up the Planning Officer expressed his opinion that granting
planning permission for the RCF would require convincing reasons for overturning
important Structure Plan policies. These reasons should be that national policy
is settled and the RCF is consistent with it and that the site selection process
and the site characterisation so far demonstrate convincingly that the
Sellafield site is the `one to go for'. Should these reasons be provided the
Planning Officer could see no case for withholding planning consent.
</P>
<P>4.35 However, the report argued that convincing reasons had not been
provided by Nirex. Accordingly, the Council were advised either to refuse the
application on the grounds that it conflicts with Structure Plan policies and
that convincing reasons for the development to proceed have not been provided or
to defer the application pending the outcome of the national reviews.
</P>
<P><B>County Council Decision and Appeal
</B></P>
<P>4.36 In the event the Council voted to refuse permission for the development
on the leading to this Appeal.
</P>
<P><B>Conclusions
</B></P>
<P>4.37 The history of Nirex's programme of research in the Sellafield area
demonstrates that geological and hydrogeological investigations have been deemed
acceptable in planning terms.
</P>
<P>4.38 An initial appeal decision in 1989, reinforced by a further decision in
1993 in the more stringent conditions of the Lake District National Park,
established that:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Proposals should be judged in terms of their local environmental and
amenity impacts and not in terms of any hypothetical future development; and
</LI>
<LI>Where conflict with policy arises this may be justified in terms of the
`need' for investigations which are recognised as being of national importance.
</LI></UL>
<P> 4.39 Cumbria County Council adopted this approach in granting consent for
the RCF/RCM/PRZ borehole development at Longlands Farm. However, in refusing
consent for the RCF itself, the County Council have departed from precedent
arguing that the development needs to be fully justified as a `halfway'
commitment to the development of a repository at Sellafield.</P>
<P><A NAME="DevelopmentPlan"></A><B>5. DEVELOPMENT PLAN CONTEXT
</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction
</B></P>
<P>5.1 In this section of my evidence I examine:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The relationship of the RCF proposal to the policies and proposals in the
former Development Plans for the area;
</LI>
<LI>The relationship of the RCF proposal to the policies and proposals in
emerging development plans for the area; and
</LI>
<LI>The weight which I believe should be attached to development plan policies
in the light of advice set out in PPG1.
</LI></UL>
<P>5.2 In order to determine which policies may be material to the
consideration of this appeal, it is necessary to examine the nature and purpose
of the development proposed and to consider how similar developments have been
dealt with in the past.
</P>
<P><B>Purpose of the Development
</B></P>
<P>5.3 The application form submitted by Nirex indicates that the RCF will
involve mineral exploration, the deposit of waste on land and the construction
of buildings. The purpose of the development is the carrying out of searches and
tests into the geology and hydrogeology of the Borrowdale Volcanic Group.
</P>
<P>5.4 The letter accompanying the application describes the purpose of the RCF
as being:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;to provide data on the geological and hydrogeological
characteristics of the potential repository host rocks, the Borrowdale Volcanic
Group (BVG) and overlying strata, for model validation for long term safety
assessment purposes, for repository design and for the selection of repository
construction methods. The RCF is part of the extensive science programme that
will enable Nirex to decide whether or not to make a planning application to
develop a deep repository for disposal of radioactive waste and to produce a
full safety assessment of post-closure safety&quot;. [NRX/11/1](30)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.5 The exploratory nature of the proposals is reflected in the fact the
development will be temporary (lasting about 12 years) and that the application
makes provision for full site restoration. The RCF is clearly an investigatory
application, the determination of which does not prejudge the decision as to the
suitability of the site for a repository. I therefore believe that it should be
judged against the background of Government policy which supports Nirex's
programme of research in the Sellafield area, development plan policies and the
local environmental impacts arising. This is how all previous applications for
investigations in the Sellafield area have been judged, as I have demonstrated
in Section 4 of this proof.
</P>
<P>5.6 In essence the application before this Inquiry is a fact finding
exercise with no certainty that development will follow. In 1976, the Stevens
Committee, charged with advising on Planning Control over Mineral Working
argued:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;In general terms we think that it cannot be right to determine
any planning application on a consideration of some other hypothetical
development for which permission has not been, and may never be sought.... . We
therefore recommend that applications for permission to explore minerals should
continue to be dealt without regard to the merits and demerits of possible
future development.&quot; [GOV/114](31)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.7 This approach is enshrined in Circular No 2/85 which deals with Planning
Control over Oil and Gas Operations. This advises that in relation to
exploration:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;each application should be considered on its merits and should
not be influenced by any hypothetical future development.&quot;[GOV/113](32)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.8 This has been the approach which has been consistently followed at
public inquiries concerned with geological investigations associated with
radioactive waste management since 1980, as the following examples demonstrate.
The Inspector appointed to hear an appeal by the then UKAEA in 1981 against
refusal to permit drilling of boreholes on two sites in the Northumberland
National Park noted that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;uncertainty can only be resolved by investigation and analysis.
On the geological investigation basis, I consider that these applications should
be permitted as part of the investigatory process.&quot; [NRX/11/2](33)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.9 In 1991, the decision letter concerning an appeal by Nirex against
refusal to permit a seismic survey on the Dounreay area by Highland Regional
Council specifically considered whether the planning consideration of
investigatory work could be separated from the ultimate purpose of that work. It
concluded as follows:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;It is noted that the planning authority and those who have
submitted representations objecting to the application under appeal are
primarily opposed, not to the seismic survey proposals themselves, but to the
possibility that they could provide information rendering a nuclear waste
repository at Dounreay more likely. However, any proposal for such a repository
would be dealt with separately if and when it arose and it is considered
therefore that objections based on concern that the seismic survey would open
the way to the establishment of a repository are not relevant to the current
appeal. In coming to this decision on the present appeal the Secretary of State
has therefore confined himself to considering the planning issues relevant to
the proposed seismic survey. He has considered that the only significant
planning issues to arise concern the immediate environmental impacts of the
proposed development.&quot; [NRX/11/3](34)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.10 It remains the case that Government will require any proposal to
develop a repository to be subject to normal planning procedures involving a
full public inquiry. This would be clearly the appropriate point at which to
examine the question of the need for a repository and any alternative sites for
it. Indeed, until a decision has been reached on whether to pursue an
application for a repository in a particular location, such considerations
remain hypothetical and not relevant in planning terms.
</P>
<P>5.11 Thus when considering the relationship between the RCF and development
plan policies, one must focus attention on the specific purpose of the
development. This is important because PPG 1 gives guidance as to the approach
which decision makers should take given the provisions of Sections 70(2) and 54A
of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990. [GOV/101](35)
</P>
<P>5.12 Section 70(2) requires the decision maker to have regard to the
development plan, so far as it is material to the application, and to any other
material considerations. Where the development plan is material to the
development proposal, and must therefore be taken into account, Section 54A
requires the application or appeal to be determined in accordance with the plan,
unless material considerations indicate otherwise.
</P>
<P><B>Statutory Development Plans
</B></P>
<P>5.13 At the time of the Secretary of State's Rule 6(10) letter, which
identified the issues on which he particularly wished to be informed, the
Statutory Development Plan policies and proposals for the area of the RCF were
contained in:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan 1st Alteration, approved
on the 16th December 1987, (the former Structure Plan). [COR/302](36)
</LI>
<LI>The Mid Copeland Local Plan, adopted on the 28th March 1990 (the Adopted
Local Plan). [COR/305](37)
</LI></UL>
<P>The Former Structure Plan
</P>
<P>5.14 The former Structure Plan set out a strategy for a County experiencing
a diverse range of economic and physical circumstances. It was based upon a set
of principles which were intended to be considered in relation to each other so
that in individual instances decisions on a proposal were made on the balance of
advantages and disadvantages it may have had.
</P>
<P>5.15 In relation to the RCF proposal at Longlands Farm, the following
principles provided a context within which to consider specific development plan
policies.
</P>
<P><B> Principle 1. To maintain Cumbria's population at or near its present
level whilst endeavouring to achieve a more balanced age structure.</B> The
population of Copeland and Barrow-in-Furness was expected to continue to
decline, over the Structure Plan period. The strategy aimed to halt this
process.
</P>
<P><B>Principle 2. To take advantage of the economic potential the County
possesses.</B> In order to provide employment opportunities the strategy sought
to build on assets which could form the basis of localised economic growth.
Although not specifically mentioned the nuclear industry clearly represented
such an asset.
</P>
<P><B>Principle 3. To encourage the provision of additional jobs to meet
specific local needs.</B> The Strategy recognised the particular need for new
jobs in areas of high unemployment and where jobs were being lost through the
decline of traditional industries. This included parts of West Cumbria which
have been subject to decline in traditional extractive and manufacturing
industries.
</P>
<P><B>Principle 4. To recognise Cumbria's role as a food and timber producer.</B>
The strategy sought to limit development on better agricultural land in lowland
parts of the County in recognition of the contribution which farming makes to
employment in Cumbria.
</P>
<P><B>Principle 7. To conserve the County's scenic beauty, its historic
heritage and wildlife habitats.</B> With over half of the County subject to
nationally recognised landscape designations, the Strategy incorporated measures
to protect and enhance environmental resources.
</P>
<P><B>Principle 8. To preserve and enhance the natural beauty of the two
National Parks and to promote their quiet enjoyment by residents and visitors.</B>
Following Government policy, the strategy gave particular priority to the
preservation and enhancement of natural beauty in National Parks. This involved
an automatic presumption against major developments which would adversely affect
the character of the Parks.
</P>
<P><B>Principle 9. To recognise the varying emphasis between social need,
economic potential and environmental conservation in different parts of the
County.</B> Recognising great economic and physical diversity within the County,
the policies and proposals of the former Structure Plan indicated in only a few
cases the priorities that should be set in certain instances. Judgements had to
be made on the weight to be given to various policies when assessing the
desirability of specific proposals. It is against this background that
individual development proposals should have been viewed, in the light of those
relevant policies.</P>
<P>The Adopted Local Plan
</P>
<P>5.16 The Adopted Local Plan for Mid Copeland was prepared against the
background of a forecast increase in the District's population combined with
policies aimed at attracting new industry to offset the anticipated contraction
in Sellafield's workforce. Covering the period from 1987 to 1996 the Plan
complements the other Local Plans for North Copeland (Whitehaven, Egremont and
North East Copeland Local Plans). Both the Mid Copeland and the Egremont Local
Plans include proposals to accommodate the pressures for development arising
from the presence of Sellafield. In addition to development within the
Sellafield Works, the Mid Copeland Plan allocated 8.0 hectares of land at Pelham
House, Calder Bridge to take advantage of enquiries for high quality industrial
and office accommodation attracted by proximity to Sellafield. [COR/305](38)
</P>
<P>5.17 The Egremont Local Plan points to the beneficial effect which
Sellafield has in sustaining population and employment in the town. While
expressing concerns about over dependence on the nuclear industry the Plan
emphasised that the Egremont area provides the best location for businesses
generated by Sellafield linkages. [NRX/11/4](39)
</P>
<P>Relevant Policies
</P>
<P>5.18 <A HREF="#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A> lists the policies of the statutory
development plans which were considered by Nirex at the time of the RCF planning
application. It is based on Table 3.1.1 of the Environmental Statement which
incorporated an assessment of the degree to which the RCF proposal is in
accordance or in conflict with development plan policies.
</P>
<P>5.19 The policies considered to be of principal relevance in the former
Structure Plan are Policies C1 and C6. These state:
</P>
<P><B>Policy C1:</B> in the countryside outside the National Park development
will not be permitted unless essential in the interests of agriculture or
forestry or where the social or economic benefits clearly outweigh the
environmental costs.
</P>
<P><B>Policy C6:</B> proposals for major developments in the countryside will
be resisted unless:
</P>
<P>a. any environmental harm is clearly outweighed by the need for the proposal
</P>
<P>b. the proposed scheme will be carried out in such a manner as to cause the
least practicable harm to the area in agricultural, recreation, landscape,
nature conservation and archaeological terms and wherever possible with benefits
to these interests, and
</P>
<P>c. in the case of proposals affecting the National Parks and Areas of
Outstanding National Beauty, all reasonable alternatives have been explored and
found to be less acceptable.&quot;
</P>
<P>5.20 The policy of principal relevance in the Adopted Local Plan is
considered to be Policy 6C. This deals specifically with the issue of research
to identify and develop a site for the disposal of radioactive waste. In the
reasoned justification for Policy 6C Copeland Borough Council highlight the link
between the storage of intermediate level waste at Sellafield and the absence of
disposal facilities.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;6.8 Intermediate level waste is stored at Sellafield in various
forms, none of which are very suitable for disposal. The Council has recently
approved two encapsulation plants now under construction which drum the waste in
a concrete matrix ready for disposal. The responsibility for disposal rests with
the Nuclear Industry Radioactive Waste Executive (NIREX) which is currently
investigating various alternative sites and methods of disposal for both ILW and
LLW. The apparent lack of political will to inject urgency into this
investigation and the long lead up time needed to develop a facility make it
unlikely that any provision will be made within the plan period to dispose of
ILW from Sellafield.
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Table5.1"></A></P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
