Archaeological Sites</TD></TR></TABLE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> 6.9 In the absence of a disposal route the Council has approved an ILW
store for the encapsulated waste. The capacity of the store has been limited to
5,500 m3 as a condition of the planning permission although on the basis of
anticipated arisings this store will be full by 1992. By the turn of the century
BNF estimate that 33,000 m3 of encapsulated waste will have been produced.
Notwithstanding this, the Council is opposed to any further encapsulated ILW
storage until a disposal route is clearly established. Without such a route
there is the possibility that Sellafield will, by default, become an ILW
disposal site. British Nuclear Fuels has recently proposed investigations into
ILW disposal beneath the Irish Sea and it is anticipated that geological
investigation will commence in 1988. It is too early to say, at this stage,
whether this is a technically feasible option.&quot; [COR/305](40)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.21 Policy 6C states:
</P>
<P><B>Policy 6C:</B> the Council urges Government and Nirex to identify and
develop a site for the disposal of intermediate waste as a matter of urgency and
will continue to resist applications to increase ILW storage capacity while
there is a lack of a clear commitment to such a site.
</P>
<P> <B>Emerging Development Plans
</B></P>
<P>5.22 The emerging development policies and proposals for the area of the RCF
at the time of the Appeal were contained in:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The Replacement Cumbria and Lake District Structure Plan 1991-2006 (The
Replacement Structure Plan). [COR/303](41)
</LI>
<LI>The Deposit Draft Copeland Local Plan (Deposit Draft Local Plan).
[COR/306](42)
</LI>
<LI>Recently Cumbria County Council have issued a Consultation Draft Minerals
and Waste Local Plan. A short supplementary proof will deal with any policies
and proposals of relevance to the RCF.
</LI></UL>
<P>The Replacement Structure Plan
</P>
<P>5.23 The Replacement Structure Plan will be adopted on 30th July 1995 and
the implications of this adoption will be dealt with in a short supplementary
proof of evidence. The Replacement Structure Plan seeks to apply the principle
of sustainable development to the strategic planning of Cumbria. It aims to
present a clear strategy for Cumbria and the Lake District National Park
embodying a vision for the County's environment and communities into the next
century. The strategy is built around ten key policies which seek to underpin
the vision and provide a framework for the more specific policies. Where there
is ambiguity or uncertainty about the interpretation and balancing of subsequent
policies, the strategy is intended to provide guidance.
</P>
<P>5.24 Those elements of the strategy which are of most direct relevant to the
RCF proposal at Longlands Farm are as follows:
</P>
<P><B>Policy 1. Development and the Environment
</B></P>
<P>This general policy emphasises that development and economic growth should
be pursued, but in a sustainable manner. The Replacement Structure Plan is
founded on the principle of ensuring that all development is sustainable in the
long term and does not diminish the quality of the environment within the County
or beyond or for future generations.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 2. Conserving the National and Built Environment
</B></P>
<P>The Plan gives particular emphasis to conserving the County's fine
landscapes and areas of valuable natural and built heritage, especially areas
designated as being of international or national conservation importance.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 5. Conserving the National Parks</B>
</P>
<P>Particular emphasis is given in the Plan to protecting the intrinsic
qualities of the National Parks, meeting the needs of local communities and
providing for visitor's enjoyment. Where there is a conflict between these
needs, the long term perspective and the protection of the Park's natural
environment will be paramount.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 8. Furness and West Cumbria
</B></P>
<P>The Plan recognises the particular economic difficulties facing Furness and
West Cumbria. In the latter case, particular reference is made to the shedding
of jobs at Sellafield and the difficulty of attracting alternative employment,
partly as a result of remoteness. The need to safeguard the long term future of
these communities is seen as a high priority.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 9. Inter Urban Transport
</B></P>
<P>Upgrading road communications between Barrow and West Cumbria and the M6 is
identified as an urgent requirement, although there is a need to balance new
road building with environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>5.25 Taken together these policies provide an overall framework for
development within the County with greater emphasis on achieving sustainable
development for the long term.
</P>
<P>Deposit Draft Local Plan
</P>
<P>5.26 The Deposit Draft Local Plan sets out a development strategy which
provides a set of guiding principles for the future planning and development of
the Borough based on the concepts of environmental sustainability. It aims to
develop an integrated approach to the overall shaping of development patterns
which acknowledge land as a finite resource, recognises the essential
characteristics of the natural and built environment and seeks to minimise
public dangers and waste, particularly the cumulative effects of dependence on
the motor car. At the same time, however, the Plan recognises the need for
policies which foster economic growth.
</P>
<P>5.27 In discussing its strategy for Mid Copeland, the Plan describes
Sellafield as the lynch pin of the Borough's economy and of national and
international significance to the nuclear industry. It goes on to argue that the
very nature of the activities carried out particularly at the end stages of
reprocessing require very careful consideration as regards the principles of
sustainability. Accordingly it requires that proposals for the processing and
storage of wastes will need to be shown to be in accordance with long term
management plans which minimise any harmful effects. The Plan acknowledges
Nirex's exploratory work in the area, and the fact that any proposal for an
underground repository would be subject to a Planning Inquiry. [COR/306](43)
</P>
<P>Relevant Emerging Development Plan Policies
</P>
<P>5.28 <A HREF="#Table5.2">Table 5.2</A> lists the emerging development plan
policies which were considered by Nirex at the time of the RCF planning
application. It is based on Table 3.1.2 of the Environmental Statement which
incorporated an assessment of the degree to which the RCF proposal is in
accordance or in conflict with these emerging policies.
</P>
<P>5.29 The policies considered to be of principal relevance are Policies 2, 5,
11, 13 and 54 of the Replacement Structure Plan and Policies DEV1 and ENV33 of
the Deposit Draft Local Plan. These are set out below, although it should be
noted that policies DEV1 and ENV33 remain subject to modification. The wording
quoted is that proposed by Copeland Borough Council at the Local Plan Inquiry.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 2:</B> the County's scenic beauty, natural resources and quality
of its built environment will be protected from inappropriate development,
especially those areas and features of international or national conservation
importance where harmful development will not be permitted.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 5:</B> the scenic beauty, natural resources and quality of the
built environment of the Lake District and Yorkshire Dales National Parks will
be firmly protected and enhanced, whilst fostering the quiet enjoyment and
understanding of the Parks and the social and economic wellbeing of their
communities in a manner which does not conflict with the conservation
objectives.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 11:</B> development and other land use changes detrimental to the
present characteristics and qualities of the landscape of the National Parks,
AONB and the Heritage Coast will not normally be permitted. Particular regard
will be paid to the protection and enhancement of undeveloped open countryside
and coast, the lakes and other sensitive locations and in addition in National
Parks the character of land identified on Section 3 Conservation Maps.
Development required to meet local infrastructure needs which cannot be located
elsewhere, will normally be permitted provided it is sited to minimise
environmental impacts and meets high standards of design.
</P>
<P><B>Policy 13:</B> in the areas not covered by Policies 11 and 12,
development will normally be permitted which in its use, siting, scale and
design is well related to existing developed areas of the countryside and does
not harm distinctive features of local landscape significance. In the
undeveloped open countryside development will not normally be permitted except
when it is required to meet local infrastructure needs which cannot be located
elsewhere and provided it is sited to minimise environmental impacts and meets
high standards of design.
</P>
