<P><B>Policy 54:</B> major developments which are more national than local in
character and have significant environmental effects will only be permitted
where:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>the sum of national, regional and local benefits is shown to clearly
outweigh any harm or risks to the local or wider environment
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>the scheme will be carried out in such manner as to cause the least
practicable harm
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>direct and indirect adverse impacts during construction and operation
(including those from the mining and working of construction materials, the
disposal of waste and their transportation) are minimised
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv.</TD>
<TD>they do not harm areas or features of international or national
conservation importance except where it can be demonstrated that the value of
the benefits that would arise clearly outweigh the international or national
conservation value of the interest affected and in addition:</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v.</TD>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>in National Parks a case can be made in the national interest and all
reasonable alternative locations and methods of satisfying the need have been
explored and shown to be unacceptable;</LI></UL></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>in AONBs a case can be made in the national interest and all reasonable
alternative locations have been explored and shown to be unacceptable.</LI></UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>DEV 1:</B> limits to development around each town and village in the
Settlement Classification have been defined as shown on the Proposals Map.
Development will not normally be permitted beyond these limits unless the
proposals are in accordance with other local plan policies. These policies are:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">1)</TD>
<TD>essential agricultural or forestry development (HSG 5-6 and ENV56-60)
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>2)</TD>
<TD>local housing needs (HSG24 and 25)
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>3)</TD>
<TD>replacement housing, house extensions and alterations on building
conversion (HSG28, 31, 32, 34 and EMP17)
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>4)</TD>
<TD>leisure and tourism related development (ENV10, SVC19 and 20 and TSM3-9)
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>5)</TD>
<TD>development within existing non-settlement based employment sites (EMP11)
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>6)</TD>
<TD>development for energy or in relation to the nuclear industry (EGY3, ENV32
and 33).
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>ENV33:</B> the Council will support the proposal for an RCF at Longlands
Farm, Gosforth so long as the following criteria are satisfied:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">1)</TD>
<TD>the proposal is framed by reference to a national radioactive waste
management strategy and alternative options in relation to the nuclear fuel
cycle, taking into account best international practice, and justified in
relation to the need to establish the geology and groundwater flows in the
vicinity of the proposed repository site, bearing in mind the Council's
fundamental requirement that safety is paramount
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>2)</TD>
<TD>the proposal demonstrates at this stage, on the basis of the investigations
that have already been undertaken, and having regard to due consideration of
alternative locations that further investigations of the suitability of the
Sellafield site for an ultimate repository via an RCF are justified.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>3)</TD>
<TD>the application demonstrates how the RCF fits into the overall research
programme and contributes to the development of the safety case, how the
programme will continue during the planning, design, construction of the
repository (if approved) and during its operation for such period of time as may
be approved, and demonstrates in particular that this programme will address:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>(i) the extent and validity of research into the near field and engineering
barriers and how this influences the issue of monitoring and any consequent need
for retrievability<BR> (ii) research on return times of radionuclides to the
surface as they are influenced by geology, hydrogeology and gas generation and
migration<BR> (iii) the effect of the construction of the RCF itself on the
safety case for the repository.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>4)</TD>
<TD>provision is made for third party review of research at key stages
including independent peer review of all borehole information.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>5)</TD>
<TD>the Council is satisfied that the non-nuclear environmental impact is
acceptable including impacts in relation to landscape, nature conservation and
traffic generation.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>6)</TD>
<TD>the developer has taken into account the full socio-economic impact of the
proposal and is prepared to enter into a Section 106 Agreement to address those
issues identified in Policy IMP 1, so that no adverse impact occurs on the
social and economic well being of West Cumbria.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>7)</TD>
<TD>there is provision for the site of the RCF to be eventually restored to
agriculture subject to any safety requirements dictated by the operation of the
repository (if approved).</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.30 My views as to the policies of principal relevance accord closely with
those of the County Planning Officer. However, Policy 25 is cited in the County
Council's grounds of refusal. For the reasons which I explain in Section 8, I do
not believe that this policy has been appropriately applied to the RCF by the
County Council.
</P>
<P>5.31 Other policies, highlighted in <A HREF="#Table5.1">Tables 5.1</A> and
<A HREF="#Table5.2">5.2</A> are of some relevance to consideration of this
appeal. I will refer to these, as appropriate, in Section 8 of my evidence,
noting, as appropriate, changes in the assessment of the RCF against the
policies listed in the Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P><B>Weight to be Attached to Emerging Policies
</B></P>
<P>5.32 In considering the weight to be attached to emerging policies regard
should be had to the advice contained in PPG 1. [GOV/101](44) This indicates
that the weight to be attached to emerging plans depends upon their stage of
preparation and the degree of any conflict with the existing plans. If no
objections have been lodged to relevant policies in a deposit plan, then
considerable weight may be attached to those policies because of the strong
possibility that they will be adopted and replace those in the existing plan.
</P>
<P>5.33 At the time of finalising this Proof of Evidence the Replacement
Structure Plan has progressed through all stages of the Statutory Plan making
process and is about to be adopted. The outstanding direction from the
Department of the Environment to modify Policy 57 which deals with Nuclear Waste
Reprocessing and Disposal has been complied with. The policies which are
material to the determination of this application are settled and not subject to
the Secretary of State's direction. When the Replacement Structure Plan is
adopted, it will become part of the Statutory Development Plan. During the short
period that remains until adoption, policies should be afforded the greatest
weight as a material consideration.
</P>
<P>5.34 The Deposit Draft Local Plan was published in July 1994. This has been
the subject of a number of objections heard by a Local Plan Inquiry in June and
July 1995. Copeland Borough Council have proposed a number of pre-inquiry
proposed changes.
</P>
<P>5.35 Policies DEV1 and ENV33 which are of particular relevance to this
appeal, introduce matters which are not covered by the Adopted Local Plan. They
should therefore be given more weight than those policies in the draft plan
which relate to matters already covered in the Adopted Local Plan. In addition,
account should be taken of the changes proposed by the Borough Council,
including the change to Policy ENV33 which indicates that Copeland now wish to
support the RCF subject to confirmation with specific criteria. Indeed, the Plan
identifies the RCF as a development which can take place in the open
countryside. However, there remain certain outstanding objections by Nirex and
others to Policy ENV33.
<BR>
</P>
<P>Conclusion
</P>
<P>5.36 This section has examined the development plan context which provides
the starting point from which the RCF proposal should be judged. The key
features of planning policy which can be identified are:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The existence of a statutory development plan which in the case of the
former Structure Plan is about to be formally replaced;
</LI>
<LI>Strategic planning policies aimed at protecting the environment of Cumbria
from inappropriate development. These focus in particular upon areas designated
as being of special landscape or conservation importance;
</LI>
<LI>Provision for major development to take place in the countryside, subject
to meeting certain criteria; and
</LI>
<LI>Specific provision within the Deposit Draft Local Plan for an RCF to be
constructed in the countryside, subject to meeting certain criteria.</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="EffectOnLandUse"></A><B>6. THE EFFECTS OF THE RCF ON LAND USE
</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction
</B></P>
<P>6.1 Mr Smith has described in his evidence the land requirements of the RCF
at different stages in its development. Mr Short has presented evidence on
agricultural land quality and the degree to which it will be possible to restore
the site to productive use. In this section of my evidence I consider the
significance of the resultant land use impacts in planning terms.
</P>
<P><B>Land Use Impacts
</B></P>
<P>6.2 The land use impacts considered in the Environmental Statement are as
follows:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Land take;
</LI>
<LI>Agricultural severance;
</LI>
<LI>Temporary disruption to agricultural land;
</LI>
<LI>Sterilisation of mineral resources;
</LI>
<LI>Secondary land use effects[COR/101](45)
</LI></UL>
<P>6.3 With the exception of land take, which would involve the progressive,
although temporary, removal of up to 24.9 hectares of Grade 3b agricultural land
from production, land use impacts would be of minor significance.
</P>
<P>Agricultural Severance
</P>
<P>6.4 There will be no agricultural severance arising from the construction,
operation and restoration of the RCF. Longlands Farm will not be operated as an
agricultural unit for the duration of the development. Those areas of land which
remain available for agriculture will be let under licence to surrounding
farmers, compensating for the temporary loss of a small number of fields which
lie on the edge of Town End and Low Boonwood farm holdings, as shown in Figure
3.3.1 of the Environmental Statement. [COR/101](46)</P>
<P>Temporary Disruption
</P>
<P>6.5 The establishment of the service routes within the Services Corridors
will result in temporary disruption of agricultural land. This will affect a
maximum of 20 fields, the majority of which are under grass, for a period of up
to 6 months. Along the route of Services Corridor A, access will be required for
material supply and hole boring and, if appropriate, for the installation of
overhead power lines. If the power lines are overhead they may be installed by a
statutory undertaker under the General Development Order. Land will be affected
along the route of Services Corridor B by the laying of pipelines in trenches.
</P>
<P>Sterilisation of Mineral Resources
</P>
<P>6.6 The development being investigatory and temporary in nature will not
sterilise any mineral resources on or under the site. Any sand and gravel
deposits within the minerals consultation area to the south of Sides Lane will
not be affected by the development.
</P>
<P><B>Secondary Land Use Effects
</B></P>
<P>6.7 The RCF development will not give rise to significant secondary land use
effects. The development has been designed to be self contained. Professor
MacKay's evidence demonstrates that the RCF will not give rise to any demands
for labour and public services which cannot be accommodated within the existing
capacity of the local area.
</P>
<P>Agricultural Land Take
</P>
<P>6.8 Potentially the most significant land use impact arising from the RCF is
the progressive removal of up to 24.9 hectares of land from agricultural use.
The maximum duration of this loss will be some 12 years after which time the
land will be restored. However, there will be a permanent loss of 4.6 hectares
of agricultural land as a consequence of retaining areas of landscape planting.
</P>
<P>6.9 In judging the significance of the landtake associated with the RCF at
Longlands Farm, account need to be taken of:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Development plan policies;
</LI>
<LI>Government guidance covering the protection of agricultural land; and</LI>
<LI>The results of consultations and representations made on the application.
</LI></UL>
<P>6.10 Policy A1 of the former Structure Plan sought to prevent the
development of Grade 2 and 3 agricultural land for non-agricultural purposes
other than in compelling circumstances. The loss of Grade 3b land might be
considered contrary to this policy, although the temporary nature of the loss
and the national significance of the RCF could be taken as providing compelling
circumstances. However, revised Government guidance, and emerging development
plan policy, remove the potential for conflict.
</P>
<P>6.11 PPG 7 recognises that the increasing efficiency of agricultural
producers and changes in agricultural policy means that retaining as much land
as possible in agricultural use no longer has the priority it formerly had. It
states that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;Land of moderate or poor quality (Grades 3b, 4 and 5) is the
least significant in terms of the national agricultural interest... Little
weight need normally be given to the loss of such land, except in areas where
particular agricultural practices themselves contribute to the quality of the
environment, or to the rural economy in some special way.&quot; [GOV/102](47)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>6.12 Neither case applies to land at Longlands Farm which is predominantly
Grade 3B, forming part of the West Cumbrian coastal strip which is not farmed by
special or distinctive agricultural practices which contribute to the character
or quality of the local environment.
</P>
<P>6.13 Reflecting the revised guidance set out in PPG 7, Policy 19 of the
Replacement Structure Plan states that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The best and most versatile agricultural land will normally be
protected from development.&quot;[COR/303](48)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The reference to `best and most versatile' agricultural land is a direct
quotation from PPG 7 which defines this as Grade 1, 2 and 3a land. Accordingly,
one may conclude that the loss of agricultural land associated with development
of the RCF is not in conflict with relevant strategic planning policy.
</P>
<P>6.14 This conclusion is confirmed by the absence of objection from MAFF to
the loss of agricultural land for a temporary period. Indeed, no objections have
been made concerning the loss of agricultural land.
</P>
<P><B>Restoration
</B></P>
<P>6.15 Restoration of the site is covered by Policy M6 of the former Structure
Plan which indicates that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;Future consents for mineral development will impose strict
conditions to provide for the restoration of the sites to agriculture or another
acceptable after-use including a use which is of benefit to the landscape.&quot;[COR/302](49)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>6.16 Policy 62 of the Replacement Structure Plan states that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Strict conditions will be imposed on all permissions for mineral
extraction and waste disposal to ensure their full restoration to an acceptable
use. A progressive scheme to restore land at the earliest opportunity will be
required whenever practicable. The creation of diverse land attractive
landscapes, including water areas and woodland to enhance nature conservation
and recreation interest, will be favourably considered.&quot;[COR/303](50)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>6.17 In their consultation response, MAFF made a number of comments
regarding the treatment of stripped soils and proposals for securing a
satisfactory standard of restoration. Of particular concern were the proposals
for landscaping a number of soil mounds. This issue has been the subject of
detailed discussions between MAFF and Nirex. These are reported in Mr Short's
Proof of Evidence.
</P>
<P>6.18 I believe that an acceptable compromise has now been reached between
the needs of agricultural restoration and landscaping and that subject to
appropriate conditions the RCF proposal meets the requirements of both statutory
and emerging planning policy.
</P>
<P><B>Conclusion
</B></P>
<P>6.19 While the RCF will result in the loss of agricultural land for a period
of about 12 years, and will lead to temporary disruption during construction of
the Services Corridors, these effects do not provide the basis for an objection
to the proposal. Insofar as concerns exist these can be adequately dealt with by
means of conditions.</P>
<P><A NAME="EffectOnRecreation"></A><B>7. THE EFFECTS OF THE RCF ON
RECREATION
</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction
</B></P>
<P>7.1 In this section of my evidence I examine the effects of the RCF on
recreational use in and around the Surface Site and consider their significance
in planning terms. In doing this I draw upon information included in the
Environmental Statement. [COR/101](51)
</P>
<P><B>Recreational Impacts
</B></P>
<P>7.2 The potential impacts of the RCF on recreation considered in the
Environmental Statement are as follows:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Displacement of existing recreational activities from Longlands Farm; and
</LI>
<LI>Temporary disruption to public rights of way.
</LI></UL>
<P>Displacement of Activities
</P>
<P>7.3 Development of the RCF will result in the loss of recreational shooting
at Longlands Farm for the duration of the development. Following restoration it
will be possible to allow shooting rights to resume.
</P>
<P>7.4 Longlands Farm is only part of the area that a local syndicate shoots
over two or three times a year. The development will not affect the use of land
at Fleming Hall, Seascale Hall, Calder Hall and Newton Manor for shooting.
</P>
<P>7.5 Longlands Farm is used by the Cumbria Riding Club for local events. Part
of this area has been affected by the RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole development, and the
RCF will further affect land currently used by the Riding Club. BNFL as
landowner will discuss an offer of an alternative site with the Riding Club.
</P>
<P><B>Disruption to Rights of Way
</B></P>
<P>7.6 There will be some temporary disruption to the following public rights
of way during the establishment of the Services Corridors. These are shown on
Figure 3.12.1 of the Environmental Statement. [COR/101](52)
</P>
<P>Services Corridor A
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Calder Town End to Ponsonby Tarn bridleway (421010);
</LI>
<LI>Fleming Hall to Calder Town End bridleway (421010); and
</LI>
<LI>Calder Farm to Lady Wood bridleway (421016).
</LI></UL>
<P>Services Corridor B
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Fleming Hall to Calder Town End bridleway (409019); and
</LI>
<LI>Cross Lanes, Seascale to Calder Farm byway (421016).
</LI></UL>
<P>7.7 The establishment of the electricity service route along Services
Corridor A will take a maximum of four months. The erection of overhead power
lines will have a very limited effect upon the three bridleways it crosses.
</P>
<P>7.8 The provision of underground services along Services Corridor B will
involve the construction of trenches across one byway and one bridleway. While
the total period envisaged for the construction of this Services Corridor is
seven months, the period during which use of these rights of way will be
affected will be much less.
</P>
<P>7.9 Work will be programmed and designed to ensure the minimum period of
disruption to the use of these public rights of way. Full consultation will take
place with the local authorities, parish council and local users, whose
interests will be protected by the statutory powers vested in the County
Council.
</P>
<P><B>Significance of Effects on Recreation
</B></P>
<P>7.10 In considering the significance of the effects of the RCF development
on recreation account needs to be take of:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The present level and nature of uses affected;
</LI>
<LI>The existence of relevant statutory and emerging development plan policies;
and
</LI>
<LI>The results of consultations and representations made on the application.
</LI></UL>
<P>7.11 Currently, informal recreational use in and around the application site
is low key, reflecting the nature and character of the local area.
</P>
<P>7.12 The former and Replacement Structure Plans do not contain policies
dealing with the protection of public rights of way. However, relevant policies
are to be found in the Adopted and Deposit Draft Local Plans.
</P>
<P>Policy 4F of the Adopted Local Plan states:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;The Council supports the development and promotion of the rights
of way network particularly the Cumbria Coastal footpath and of shorter walks
along rights of way associated with it. The Council also supports the
development of cycle routes away from the main road network.&quot;[COR/305](53)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Policy ENV14 of the Deposit Draft Local Plan states:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;The Council will protect existing rights of way from development
at the planning stage and will support proposals for the improvement and
promotion of local circular routes and long distance paths including the Cumbria
Coastal Way where possible served by sensitively designed and landscaped car
parking.&quot; [COR/306](54)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.13 The RCF does not conflict with either of these policies.
</P>
<P>7.14 The result of consultations on the RCF application reveals an
understandable concern on the part of Gosforth Parish Council and the Ramblers
Association that disruption to rights of way should be minimised and that proper
consultation should take place. In his report, the County Planning Officer
concludes that the disruption of rights of way would only be short term and
would require alternative routes to be provided and a satisfactory period of
notice given to the County Council who would consult with local interest. In
this regard the statutory powers available to the County Council provide
adequate safeguards. [COR/104](55). I therefore agree with the County Council
that there are no grounds for objection to the RCF arising from its effect on
recreation and public rights of way.
</P>
<P><B>Conclusion
</B></P>
<P>7.15 The RCF would displace shooting from Longlands Farm for the duration of
the development. Horse riding presently using land at Longlands Farm may be
relocated to an alternative site.
</P>
<P>7.16 Temporary disruption to public rights of way will be of short duration.
Adequate safeguards exist to ensure that the effect on local users will be
minimised.
</P>
<P>7.17 Overall, the effect of the RCF on recreation will be very limited and
of no significance in planning terms.</P>
<P><A NAME="Assessment"></A><B>8. PLANNING ASSESSMENT
</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction
</B></P>
<P>8.1 In this section of my evidence I set out my assessment of the RCF
proposal taking into account those considerations which I believe are material
to the determination of this appeal. This builds upon the assessment contained
within the Environmental Statement, taking into account the County Council's own
assessment and the consultation responses and representations made. The planning
assessment must take account of considerations which fairly and reasonably
relate to the application for the construction of an RCF which will enable Nirex
to decide whether or not to make a planning application to develop a repository
at Sellafield and to produce a full assessment of post closure safety.
</P>
<P><B>Statutory Development Plan Policies
</B></P>
<P>8.2 The starting point for any planning assessment must be the statutory
development plan. In Section 4 I set out the policies which I believe are
particularly relevant to the Surface Site which lies in an area of open
countryside which is not covered by any statutory planning designations, but is
close to the western edge of the Lake District National Park. This is emphasised
by Figure 3.10.1 and 3.11.1 of the Environmental Statement [COR/101](56)
</P>
<P>8.3 Policy C1 of the former Structure Plan sought to prevent development in
the countryside outside the National Parks unless essential in the interests of
agriculture or forestry or where the social or economic benefits clearly
outweigh the environmental costs. Here the key objective of policy was to
protect the countryside from undesirable changes by protecting it from
development which is not essential in a particular place.
</P>
<P>8.4 Given its location in open countryside, development of the RCF would run
counter to this policy unless the social or economic benefits which it produces
outweigh the environmental costs.
</P>
<P>8.5 The evidence presented by Nirex demonstrates that the RCF forms part of
a programme of investigations which has the clear support of Government policy.
The investigations form an essential part of a Science Programme which will
enable Nirex to decide whether or not to make a planning application to develop
a deep repository at Sellafield and to produce a full assessment of post closure
safety. The RCF will therefore make an important contribution to decisions
regarding the safe, long term disposal of the UK's radioactive wastes. This will
be of significant benefit to society, nationally and locally, given the
important role the nuclear industry plays the economy of West Cumbria.<BR>
</P>
<P>8.6 More immediately, Professor MacKay's evidence has demonstrated that the
employment which the RCF will produce will have an unambiguously positive impact
on a local economy where local employment prospects are not promising.
</P>
<P>8.7 More are therefore very clear social and economic benefits to be derived
from the development of the RCF which need to be weighed against any harm which
the RCF development may cause to the environment. In my view I do not believe
that the harm which could be caused by the RCF is significantly different in
nature, extent and duration from that associated with the regional borehole
programme and the RCF/RCM/PRZ borehole development which have previously been
judged acceptable in planning terms. I therefore believe that the RCF proposal
meets the requirements of Policy C1. It should be noted that the Environmental
Statement indicated that the RCF was in minor conflict with Policy C1.
</P>
<P>8.8 Policy C6 of the former Structure Plan dealt specifically with proposals
for major developments in the countryside which would be resisted unless:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">a)</TD>
<TD>Any environmental harm was clearly outweighed by the need for the proposal;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>b)</TD>
<TD>The proposed scheme would be carried out in such a manner as to cause the
least practicable harm to the area in agricultural, recreation, landscape,
nature conservation and archaeological terms and wherever possible with benefits
to these interests; and
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>c)</TD>
<TD>In the case of proposals affecting the National Parks and Areas of
Outstanding National Beauty, all reasonable alternatives have been explored and
found to be less acceptable.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>8.9 Criteria a) of this policy applies a broader test to that used in Policy
C1 in that there needs to be clear justification or need for development to
offset any harm it may cause to the countryside. I believe that Nirex have
clearly demonstrated the case for continuing with their programme of
investigations by means of an RCF and that, following precedent, this outweighs
any environmental harm caused.
</P>
<P>8.10 In relation to criteria b) the County Planning Officer has accepted
that Nirex have gone as far as practicable in minimising impacts. In relation to
the specific concerns covered by this criteria it has been shown that:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The area of agricultural land taken reflects an agreed approach to
environmental design which has sought to minimise the overall impact of the
development. With the exception of slightly more than four and a half hectares
of land retained as landscape planting, the site will be fully restored to
agriculture use of a similar quality to that which currently exists. There are
no objections to the development on agricultural grounds;
</LI>
<LI>The impact of the development on recreation will be minimal involving
temporary loss of shooting and short term disruption to public rights of way
during installation of the Services Corridors. Adequate safeguards exist to
ensure that inconvenience to local users will be minimised. There are no
objections to the development on recreational grounds;
</LI>
<LI>While concerns exist over the impact of the RCF on the landscape, the
County Planning Officer has concluded that Nirex has gone as far as practicable
in minimising the impact of the development on the landscape;
</LI>
<LI>The RCF has been designed in such a way as to meet the requirements of the
National Rivers Authority with respect to discharges into the Newmill Beck. This
will ensure the protection of the Natterjack toad breeding colony some 2 kms
downstream of the site. The development also incorporates proposals to minimise
the impact of the development on the local badger population. Subject to strict
monitoring and enforcement the County Planning Officer concludes that the
development is not in conflict with nature conservation policies;
</LI>
<LI>The development will involve the removal of one feature which is evaluated
as being of very minor archaeological significance. Provision will be made for
recording archaeological features uncovered during site preparation, and subject
to appropriate conditions there is no objection to the development on
archaeological grounds; and
</LI>
<LI>The proposals for restoration will lead to a long term enhancement of both
the landscape and nature conservation value of the site.
</LI></UL>
<P>In the light of these considerations I conclude that the RCF meets the
requirements of criteria b).
</P>
<P>8.11 Criteria c) applies 'the Silkin Test' to all major development
proposals affecting National Parks. While Mrs Wilson's evidence indicates that
the RCF will be visible from a number of locations she concludes that the change
in visual amenity brought about by the intrusion of the RCF into views to and
from the National Park will be limited. Mrs Wilson does not consider that the
RCF will have an effect on the character or landscape quality of the National
Park. I would therefore question whether it is appropriate to seek to apply this
test. I believe that this is supported by previous decisions which provide a
useful guide to the approach to be adopted in the case of development occurring
outside, but close to the National Park.
</P>
<P>8.12 In his report on the RCF/RCM/PRZ borehole development at Longlands Farm
the County Planning Officer acknowledged that less stringent conditions apply to
the consideration of the development at Longlands Farm than within the National
Park. [COR/201](57) 
</P>
<P>8.13 In reaching his decision on an appeal concerning the construction of 15
wind turbines on Kirkby Moor and Lowick High Common, Furness on the edge of the
National Park, the Secretary of State had to deal with a similar question:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;The case against the wind farm therefore rests essentially on its
likely visual impact and the effect this would have on the appearance and
character of the site and the surrounding landscape. In considering the weight
which should be given to these matters, it is considered necessary to bear in
mind that although the site is close to the National Park and in similar
countryside, it is not situated in a nationally designated area of landscape
importance. The windfarm would be readily seen from part of the Park, but will
not directly affect the Park's appearance or character. It is appropriate to
consider the proposal therefore only as one situated in a area designated by the
County Structure Plan as one of Great Landscape Value. Whilst such an area
should be protected from inappropriate development, the evidence points to the
suitability of such areas in general, and the appeal site in particular, for the
purposes of wind energy generation and the conclusion is reached that this form
of development should not be regarded as being, by its nature, one which is
necessarily inappropriate&quot;. [NRX/11/5](58)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.14 From this decision it is clear that in applying planning policy to
development outside, but close to the edge of the National Park, the following
approach needs to be applied:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>In considering the significance of these effects account should only be
taken of National Park policy if the proposal has a direct effect on the
appearance and character of the Park. It is not enough that a development can be
seen from part of the Park; and
</LI>
<LI>Attention should be paid primarily to the policy designation of the area
within which the development lies and which it will directly affect.
</LI></UL>
<P>I believe that this approach is recognised by the guidance set out in PPG7.
</P>
<P>8.15 In any event the purpose of the RCF is to undertake in-situ
measurements to reduce uncertainties and gaps in knowledge of the PRZ at
Sellafield. The RCF provides the only practicable means by which the required
information can be obtained. There are therefore no alternatives to an RCF at
Longlands Farm, indeed none have been suggested. I therefore conclude that the
proposal meets the requirements of criteria c).
</P>
<P>8.16 Policy 6C of the Adopted Local Plan lends support to Nirex's programme
of investigations.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;The Council urges Government and Nirex to identify and develop a
site for the disposal of intermediate waste as a matter of urgency and will
continue to resist applications to increase ILW storage capacity while there is
a lack of clear commitment to such a site.&quot;
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.17 While circumstances have clearly developed since this policy was
approved, it is clear that the local planning authority recognised the need for
investigations to be undertaken to overcome the absence of a disposal route for
the intermediate level waste generated and stored at Sellafield. Indeed, as
explained at para 5.20 of my proof the written justification stressed the
urgency underlying the need for site investigations and the possibility that
these might take place in the Sellafield area. In this regard, I believe that it
is in accordance with and draws support from the Adopted Local Plan.
</P>
<P>8.18 In relation to the key policies of the former Structure Plan I conclude
that:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The RCF meets the requirements of Policy C1. It offers clear social and
economic benefits, nationally and locally, which outweigh the temporary
environmental harm caused. In this regard the RCF is an essential development
which is justified in the open countryside;
</LI>
<LI>The RCF similarly meets the requirements of Policy C6 in that there is
clear justification and need for the development which outweighs any temporary
environmental harm caused; the proposal seeks as far as practicable to minimise
adverse impacts and produce longer term benefits; and that the development will
not directly affect the appearance or character of the National Park and that
there are no reasonable alternatives to the RCF to obtain in situ information to
reduce uncertainties and gaps in knowledge about the PRZ at Sellafield; and
</LI>
<LI>The RCF, as part of the programme of investigations to identify and develop
a site for the disposal of intermediate level radioactive waste, is in general
accordance with Policy 6C of the Adopted Local Plan.
</LI></UL>
<P>I therefore believe that the RCF proposal satisfies the requirements of and
generally accords with the former Structure Plan and Adopted Local Plan.
</P>
<P>8.19 The application for the development must be determined in accordance
with the requirements of the policies of the Replacement Structure Plan, as from
the 30th July 1995, unless material considerations indicate otherwise. These
policies were discussed in Section 5 of my evidence, and were specifically
addressed in the County Council's assessment of the RCF application. I will deal
with each of these in turn.
</P>
<P>Policy 2
</P>
<P>8.20 Policy 2 of the Replacement Structure Plan sets out a general policy
aimed at conserving the natural and built environment of Cumbria.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;The scenic beauty, natural resources and quality of the built
environment will be protected from inappropriate development, especially those
areas and features of international or national conservation importance where
harmful development will not be permitted.&quot;
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.21 The County Planning Officer concluded that the RCF is in conflict with
Policy 2 because it is a:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;major development, industrial in character, in the open
countryside, and would undoubtedly have an adverse visual impact on the
surrounding area including the National Park&quot;. [COR/104](59)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.22 However, in assessing whether or not a proposal is in conflict with
this policy, the key tests are whether the development is inappropriate and if
so, what effect it has on scenic beauty, natural resources or the quality of the
built environment. The key issue is whether a proposal is harmful to interests
of acknowledged importance, in particular features of international or national
conservation significance in the context of a Structure Plan strategy aimed at
ensuring that all development is sustainable in the long term.
</P>
<P>8.23 The information provided in the Environmental Statement and the
evidence submitted by Nirex to this Inquiry demonstrates that the RCF forms part
of a coherent science programme which will enable Nirex to decide whether or not
to make a planning application to develop a deep repository at Sellafield and to
produce a full assessment of post closure safety. The investigatory nature of
the development is confirmed by the White Paper. [GOV/208](60). Indeed, Mr
Folger's evidence explains the support which Nirex's programme draws from the
statements of Government Policy. In addition, he demonstrates that independent
bodies such as the Radioactive Waste Management Advisory Committee, (`the
RWMAC', and the Royal Society support the RCF as an appropriate means of
reducing uncertainties and gaps in knowledge. In these circumstances I do not
believe that the RCF should be regarded as an inappropriate development.
</P>
<P>8.24 While parts of the RCF, in particular the taller structures, may be
seen from limited parts of the National Park, the majority of the development
will be screened from view. The effect of the development on visual amenity will
therefore be slight and, after about 12 years, the site will be restored to
agriculture and will be enhanced by landscaping proposals. Mrs Wilson's evidence
concludes that the development will have no direct physical effect on the
appearance or character of the nearby Lake District National Park. Indeed a
variety of structures already exist in the local landscape and others have been
accepted as part of Nirex's programme of investigations in the Sellafield area.
The RCF will not harm the scenic quality of the Lake District National Park, and
its purposes accord with the principles of sustainable development set out in
the Replacement Structure Plan.
</P>
<P>8.25 Similarly, the RCF will not have a significant effect on natural
resources or the quality of the built environment given the absence of any
special designations covering the site and its immediate surroundings, and the
proposals for full restoration.
</P>
<P>8.26 I would therefore conclude that the RCF is not in conflict with Policy
2 for the following reasons:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>It is not an inappropriate form of development given its clear
investigatory purpose which has been fully explained both in the context of
Government policy and Nirex's science programme;
</LI>
<LI>The effect of the RCF on the visual amenity of those living in and visiting
the local area will be slight given that most of the development will be
screened from view. Visual intrusion will largely arise from a small number of
taller elements which will be seen from a limited number of viewpoints against
the background of structures which are already present in the landscape;
</LI>
<LI>The RCF will have no direct physical effect on the appearance or character
of the nearby Lake District; and
</LI>
<LI>The RCF will not harm scenic beauty or natural resources, or the quality of
the built environment nor areas or features of international or national
conservation importance, particularly when one takes into account the long term
objectives of sustainability which the RCF will assist.
</LI></UL>
<P>Policies 5 and 11
</P>
<P>8.27 The County Planning Officer concludes that the RCF development is in
conflict with Policies 5 and 11 which state respectively that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The scenic beauty, natural resources and quality of the built
environment of the Lake District and Yorkshire Dales National Park will be
firmly protected and enhanced while fostering the quiet enjoyment and
understanding of the parks, and the social and economic wellbeing of their
communities in a manner which does not conflict with the conservation objectives&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Development and other land use changes detrimental to the present
characteristics and quality of the landscape of the National Parks, AONB and the
Heritage Coast will not normally be permitted. Particular regard will be paid to
the protection and enhancement of undeveloped open countryside and coast, the
lakes and other sensitive locations and in addition in National Parks the
character of land identified on Section 3 Conservation Maps. Development
required to meet local infrastructure needs which cannot be located elsewhere,
will normally be permitted provided it is sited to minimise environmental
impacts and meets high standards of design&quot;.
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.28 Both policies which are respectively entitled `Conserving the National
Parks' and &quot;Landscapes of National Importance&quot; are aimed at the long
term protection of designated landscapes. However, the site of the RCF is not
covered by any landscape designation of national or county importance.
</P>
<P>8.29 Examination of the written justification for Policies 5 and 11,
indicate that the overriding concern is with the control of development within
National Parks and other designated areas. Indeed, the Plan provides no guidance
as to the approach to be taken in the case of development lying outside the
boundary of the National Park. However, the Plan does give additional protection
to certain landscapes on the fringe of the National Park through their
designation as &quot;County Landscapes&quot;. The RCF site is not covered by
such a designation.
</P>
<P>8.30 In these circumstances it is, I believe, necessary to undertake the
planning assessment on a pragmatic basis, as follows:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>What effect does the development have upon the landscape of National Park?
</LI>
<LI>How does this affect the underlying objectives of National Park policy?
</LI>
<LI>What approach has been adopted in similar circumstances in the past?
</LI></UL>
<P>8.31 Mrs Wilson addresses the effect of the RCF on present characteristics
and qualities of the Lake District National Park. While the development will be
visible from a limited number of areas within the Park, she considers that the
visual effect of the proposals on the National Park would be insignificant.
Indeed it will have no direct affect on the appearance or character of the Park.
</P>
<P>8.32 In the case of views from properties and routes on the westernmost edge
of the Park, visual intrusion takes place in the context of the A595(T) which
forms the Park boundary. For more distant views, the RCF would appear as a
medium sized element within a wide landscape panorama which includes similar
elements, and is dominated by the presence of the Sellafield complex.</P>
<P>8.33 The RCF will also be visible from a restricted number of areas outside
the National Park but in which the National Park appears as a backdrop to the
view. In these cases, only the upper portion of the development would be visible
and would be relatively insignificant when seen against the dramatic panorama of
the Higher Fells. The change in visual amenity would therefore be slight.
</P>
<P>8.34 When considering the significance of these effects it must be
remembered that they are temporary, about 12 years, and reversible. Indeed, in
the longer term the planting proposals will enhance the landscape quality of the
local area.
</P>
<P>8.35 I therefore believe that the RCF poses no threat to the statutory
purposes of the National Park which are the conservation of its natural beauty
and the promotion of its public enjoyment. The RCF will have no long term effect
on the natural beauty of the Lake District National Park, although it will be
visible from certain viewpoints.
</P>
<P>8.36 Indeed, the introduction of similar temporary and permanent structures
into the landscape on the edge of the National Park has been accepted in the
past. Directly relevant examples include:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Individual borehole applications; and
</LI>
<LI>The RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole development (which the County Planning Officer
accepted would have a greater impact on the environment, in the short term, than
the RCF).
</LI></UL>
<P>8.37 More significantly, highly visible structures have been permitted
elsewhere on the fringes of the Lake District National Park. These include:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The 15 wind turbines on Kirkby Moor and Lowick High Common, Furness (for a
period of 25 years); and
</LI>
<LI>Major quarrying operations at Shap on the eastern boundary of the Park.
</LI></UL>
<P>8.38 I would therefore conclude:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>That while some elements of the RCF will be visible for a temporary period
from limited parts of the National Park, it will have no affect on the scenic
beauty and landscape qualities of the National Park;
</LI>
<LI>The RCF will therefore not harm the landscape qualities nor will it affect
people's enjoyment of the Lake District National Park; and
</LI>
<LI>In the absence of such harm precedent indicates that the RCF should be
judged in terms of the policies which apply to the area within which it lies. It
is simply not enough to claim that because it can be seen from the National
Park, then it is in conflict with Policies 5 and 11.
</LI></UL>
<P>In view of this I conclude that the RCF is not conflict with Policies 5 and
11 of the Replacement Structure Plan.
</P>
<P>Policy 13
</P>
<P>8.39 Policy 13 deals with development in those parts of the countryside not
covered by landscape designations. It is therefore of direct relevance to the
RCF proposal at Longlands Farm. It states:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;In the areas not covered by Policies 11 and 12, development will
normally be permitted which in its use, siting, scale and design is well related
to existing developed areas of the countryside and does not harm distinctive
features of local landscape significance. In the undeveloped open countryside,
development will not be permitted except when, it is required to meet local
infrastructure needs which cannot be located elsewhere, and provide it is sited
to minimise environmental impacts and meets high standards of design.&quot;
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.40 The first part of the policy is aimed at steering appropriate
development alongside existing settlements, while the second half is concerned
with preventing non essential development in the open countryside.
</P>
<P>8.41 The explanatory paragraphs accompanying the policy recognises that
certain types of development cannot avoid being located in the open countryside
and may need to be permitted subject to measures to minimise impact if it can be
demonstrated that benefits clearly outweigh the environmental costs. Mineral
workings are cited as examples of such development suggesting a broad definition
of `local infrastructure'. [COR/303](61).
</P>
<P>8.42 It might be argued that the RCF does not strictly fit the terms of
Policy 13 which only envisages permitting development required to meet local
infrastructure needs in the open countryside. However, the RCF is identified in
policies DEV1 and ENV 33 of the emerging local plan as a development which can
take place outside defined settlement boundaries. This reflects a recognition of
the reasons for locating the RCF at Longlands Farm. These are related to the
requirement to undertake in situ tests, observation and measurements of the
potential repository zone. It therefore meets an important need which cannot be
met other than in a countryside location. I therefore believe that the proposal
meets the general intention of Policy 13.
</P>
<P>Policy 25
</P>
<P> 8.43 The County Planning Officer has sought to argue that the RCF is in
conflict with Policy 25. This states:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The siting, appearance and landscaping of all new development and
alterations should aim to enhance the quality of the existing environment. It
should be in keeping with the local character of townscape or landscape and,
where appropriate, with the local vernacular tradition.&quot;
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.44 I do not believe that this policy has been appropriately applied in the
County Council's fifth reason for refusal.
</P>
<P>8.45 In explaining the policy which is aimed at improving the built
environment of Cumbria, the written statement says:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;Wherever possible new development and its associated landscaping
should not be bland or neutral, but should contribute positively towards the
conservation and enhancement of Cumbria's character, while respecting local
tradition.&quot;[COR/303](62)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This adds an important qualification, indeed if this qualification did not
exist, the effect of this policy would be to impose a more stringent requirement
on new development than that applied in Conservation Areas.
</P>
<P>8.46 It must be accepted that certain forms of development, such as mineral
workings involve structures and materials which cannot be designed in such a way
as to enhance the built environment or respect local traditions. In this regard
they are almost bound to be in conflict with the aim of Policy 25 as noted in
Table 3.1.2 of the Environmental Statement. I believe that this is properly a
matter for conditions covering the detailed design of structures, materials and
use of colour rather than a ground for refusal.
</P>
<P>8.47 However, the evidence produced by Nirex demonstrates that as far as
possible an approach has been taken with the design which seeks to minimise the
extent to which the RCF intrudes into the local area. For example, both in
relation to the siting (84.5m aOD) and appearance, and in relation to
landscaping every effort has been made to blend in with local landform and
vegetation; an approach which was agreed in advance with the County Council.
Indeed in the longer term, site restoration and planting will result in an
enhanced landscape.
</P>
<P>8.48 Given the nature of the development involving temporary buildings and
structures typical of a minerals operation and the agreed approach to landscape,
I remain of the view that it is inappropriate to cite such a policy in the
reasons for refusal, particularly as the County Council accept that Nirex have
gone as far as practicable in minimising the impact on the landscape.
</P>
<P>Policy 54
</P>
<P>8.49 Policy 54 deals specifically with major projects.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;Major developments which are more national than local in
character and have significant environmental effects will only be permitted
where:
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>i) the sum of national, regional and local benefits is shown to clearly
outweigh any harm or risks to the local or wider environment
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>ii) the proposed scheme will be carried out in such a manner as to cause
the least practicable harm, and
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>iii) direct and indirect adverse impacts during construction and during
operation (including those from the mining and working of construction
materials, the disposal of waste and their transportation) are minimised
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>iv) they do not harm areas or features of international or national
conservation importance except where it can be demonstrated that the value of
the benefits that would arise clearly outweigh the international or national
conservation value of the interest affected, and in addition:
</I></P>
<UL>
<LI>in National Parks a case can be made in the national interest and all
reasonable alternative locations and methods of satisfying the need have been
explored and shown to be unacceptable;
</LI>
<LI>in AONBs a case can be made in the national interest and all reasonable
alternative locations have been explored and shown to be unacceptable.&quot;
</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.50 The County Council have argued that the RCF proposal fails to meet the
requirements of Criteria i) because Nirex has failed to produce convincing
reasons why the development should be permitted while national policy
uncertainties remain. This is dealt with by other witnesses and I refer again to
the matter later in my evidence. The County Council also considers that the
development is contrary to criteria iv) by virtue of its adverse visual impact
on the local area, including the National Park. In this regard the report of the
Director of Economy and Environment focused almost entirely upon the visibility
of the RCF rather than its effect on the appearance and character of the
National Park. However, the County Council accepts that the development fulfils
the requirements of Criteria ii) and iii). The last two sub clauses of criteria
iv) are not applicable.
</P>
<P>8.51 In the information provided with the application, including the
Environmental Statement, responses to requests from the County Council, and in
evidence presented to this Inquiry, Nirex has demonstrated a clear justification
in policy and technical terms for the further investigation of Sellafield as a
potential location for a deep repository through construction of an RCF.
</P>
<P>8.52 The benefits which will be produced by the RCF relate principally to
the information which it will provide to allow a future decision to be made
about the long term disposal of the nation's radioactive waste. This is
something which Policy 6C of the Adopted Local Plan requires. This is
particularly important locally given the significance of Sellafield to the
economy of West Cumbria. Indeed, the RCF development will itself produce local
benefits in terms of income and employment.
</P>
<P>8.53 I believe that there is a convincing case, nationally and locally, for
putting aside any limited and temporary harm which the RCF development will
cause to the environment. I would conclude that the requirements of Criteria i)
of Policy 54 are therefore satisfied. Indeed the Director of Economy and
Environment concluded in his report that if the policy basis suggested in the
Review documents was affirmed the ability of Nirex to produce convincing reasons
to override planning objections would be significantly changed.
</P>
<P>8.54 With the publication of the recent White Paper there can now be no
doubt that important national interests will be served by continuing to
investigate and establish the safety of a potential long term disposal option
for low and intermediate wastes, particularly given the significance of
Sellafield to the economy of West Cumbria. Indeed, the RCF development will
itself produce local benefits in terms of income and employment.
</P>
<P>8.55 Set against the harm which the development may cause visually to the
local environment, I believe that there is a clear justification for the RCF,
which meets the requirements of Criteria i) of Policy 54.
</P>
<P>8.56 In considering Criteria iv) I have already demonstrated, drawing on the
evidence of Mrs Wilson, that the RCF will have no direct physical effect on the
appearance and character of the National Park either in the short or long term,
and that the development is acceptable in planning terms when one takes account
of the benefits to be gained. Indeed I believe that the County Council have been
inconsistent in the way in which they have applied this criteria to the RCF as
opposed to the RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole development.
</P>
<P>8.57 I therefore conclude that the RCF proposal does not conflict with
Policy 54 as it meets all the relevant criteria.
</P>
<P>8.58 In relation to Replacement Structure Plan policy I would therefore
conclude that:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The RCF is not an inappropriate form of development and will not affect the
scenic beauty, natural resources or quality of the built environment of areas of
key conservation interest. It is therefore not in conflict with Policy 2.
</LI>
<LI>The RCF does not physically affect the scenic beauty and landscape quality
of the Lake District National Park. It is not in conflict with Policies 5 and
11.
</LI>
<LI>The RCF meets a important need which cannot be met other than in a
countryside location. It will produce clear benefits which outweigh any
temporary visual intrusion which may result. It therefore meets the general
intention of Policy 13 and is in accordance with DEV1 and ENV 33 of the emerging
Local Plan.
</LI>
<LI>Given the nature of the development and the agreed approach to landscaping
the RCF does not conflict with Policy 25, which is inappropriately cited in the
Council's reasons for refusal; and
</LI>
<LI>There is a convincing case nationally and locally for pursuing
investigations. It is acknowledged that the development will be carried out in
such a manner as to cause the least practical harm, with direct and indirect
adverse impacts being minimised; there will be no significant effect on the
appearance and character of the National Park. The proposal therefore meets the
requirements of Policy 54.
</LI></UL>
<P>8.59 In reaching this conclusion it is clearly necessary to take account of
other material considerations, which I will deal with below. However, it is not
relevant for the reasons set out in Section 5 of my evidence, to take account of
matters which would arise in the event of a repository application. I therefore
do not believe that Policy 57 of the Replacement Structure Plan should be taken
into account by the Inquiry into a RCF development, as it clearly is not
concerned with the reprocessing, storage or final disposal of nuclear waste.
Indeed given the investigatory nature of the RCF, such considerations remain
hypothetical.
</P>
<P><B>Other Material Considerations
</B></P>
<P><B>Draft Deposit Local Plan
</B></P>
<P>8.60 In assessing the RCF proposal against the emerging local plan two key
policies can be highlighted. Both refer specifically to the RCF and must
therefore be considered highly relevant.
</P>
<P>8.61 Policy DEV 1 states:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;Limits to development around each town and village in the
Settlement Classification have been defined, as shown on the Proposals Map.
Development will not normally be permitted beyond these limits unless the
proposals are in accordance with other local planning policies. These policies
are:
</I></P>
<P><I>1. essential agricultural or forestry development (HSG 5-6 and TNV
56-60)
</I></P>
<P><I>2. local needs housing (HSG 24 and 25)
</I></P>
<P><I>3. replacement housing, house extensions and alternations or building
conversions (HSE 28, 31, 34 and EMP 17)
</I></P>
<P><I>4. leisure or tourism-related development (ENV 10, SVC 19 and 20 and TSM
3-9)
</I></P>
<P><I>5. development within existing non-settlement based employment sites
(EMP 11)
</I></P>
<P><I>6. development for emerging or in relation to the nuclear industry (EGY
3, ENV 32 and 33).
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.62 Policy ENV 33 deals specifically with the RCF. This means that subject
to meeting the requirements of ENV 33, the RCF is in accordance with emerging
Local Plan policy. No objections have been made to Clause 6 of this policy which
should therefore be accorded some weight particularly as it deals with an issue
which is not covered or contradicted by the Adopted Local Plan.
</P>
<P>8.63 Policy ENV 33 has been the subject of a number of objections which have
resulted in the Borough Council proposing changes to the wording of the policy.
This indicates that the Council will support the RCF subject to a number of
criteria being fulfilled. It is contended that the development accords with this
policy when other material considerations are taken into account while
recognising that Policy ENV33 is yet to be finally settled. I believe that the
existence of a policy which indicates that the local planning authority will
support the development of an RCF should be accorded significant weight.
</P>
<P>8.64 An assessment of the RCF against relevant policies contained in Cumbria
County council's Consultation Draft Minerals and Waste Local Plan will be
covered in a short supplementary proof.</P>
<P>Government Policy
</P>
<P>8.65 Mr Folger in his evidence has demonstrated that Nirex's investigations
in the Sellafield area have the support of Government as expressed in the
Secretary of State's statement to the House of Commons on the 21st March 1989.
This statement provided the basis on which Nirex established the need for its
successful appeals for investigatory boreholes in the Lake District National
Park.
</P>
<P>8.66 The RCF is able to rely upon this statement of Government policy for
support as it does not commit the Government or Nirex to proceed beyond
investigation. Indeed, the application before this Inquiry is expressly for the
purposes set out within that statement, namely:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;detailed geological studies in the vicinity of Sellafield to
enable Nirex to decide on suitability for construction of a repository, or
whether it will be necessary to evaluate other sites&quot; [GOV/210(63)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.67 Critically it remains the case that should Nirex decide to pursue the
development of a deep repository at Sellafield it will have to submit a planning
application and seek the necessary approvals.
</P>
<P>8.68 Significantly, not only does the RCF development derive support from
this statement of Government policy, but is also endorsed in the Department of
the Environment's Consultation Document `Review of Radioactive Waste Management
Policy - Preliminary Conclusions' (August 1994). This states that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;The Government continues to favour a policy of disposal rather
than indefinite storage for ILW and high and emitting wastes. It considers it
appropriate that Nirex should continue with its current site investigations
programme, including its application for planning permission for a rock
characterisation facility at Sellafield.&quot; [GOV/306](64)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.69 This position has been confirmed by the White Paper published in July
1995, which states:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> <I>&quot;The present site selection programme began in 1987, when the
Government accepted Nirex's conclusion that it would be preferable to develop a
multi-purpose deep site for LLW and ILW rather than proceed with the
investigations for a near-surface facility. In 1987, Nirex published a public
consultation document, The Way Forward. Some 30% of the British mainland was
initially considered to offer geological and hydrogeological potential for
repository development. By 1989, Nirex had prepared a short-list of 12 sites.
Following advice from RWMAC, the Government accepted Nirex's recommendation that
a deep repository should be developed under the land rather than the sea and
that the next steps should be to carry out detailed geological studies in the
vicinity of Sellafield and Dounreay. In arriving at these recommendations, Nirex
had concluded that it would be best to explore first those sites where there was
some measure of local support for civil nuclear activities, Further evaluation
of the geology of those two areas would enable it to decide on their suitability
for construction of a repository, or whether it would be necessary to evaluate
other sites. The Government made clear that it was for Nirex to obtain the
necessary planning permissions for its exploratory work through the normal
procedures.
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>In 1991, Nirex announced that results of initial borehole drilling and
other investigations at the two sites suggested that either could potentially
support the safety case necessary for a deep disposal site, but that it proposed
to concentrate its investigations on Sellafield because of the advantages it
offered in terms of transport, with the majority of ILW for disposal arising
from BNFL's operations at Sellafield. The RCF would form part of those
investigations.
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>The matters about which the Secretary of State has said he specifically
wishes to be informed by the public inquiry into the RCF concern the local
impact of the facility's construction. The Government has already promised to
hold a full public inquiry into an applications for the repository itself,
wherever it may be situated. The Government sees no reason to depart from this
procedure. In view of the importance which the RWMAC/ACSNI report attached to
transparency of decision making, Nirex has indicated to the Government that it
is formulating proposals to enhance and put onto a regular cycle the publication
of information about its scientific work and development of the repository
programme. The Government welcomes this initiative and will seek the advice of
RWMAC on the company's proposals.&quot; [GOV/208](65)
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.70 Thus, far from the uncertainty which the Director of Economy and
Environment presented in his report to the County Council of the 20th December
1994, it is clear that the continuation of Nirex's investigation programme and
the concept of an RCF has the support of Government policy and its advisors.
</P>
<P>Form and Siting of the RCF
</P>
<P>8.71 Mr Smith has explained the factors which have been taken into account
in designing and siting the RCF. This has been significantly influenced by the
need for in situ investigations of the potential repository zone, as well as the
depth of the host geology and area of surface and mineral rights ownership.
Within these constraints detailed siting and design has sought to take account
of:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Site access;
</LI>
<LI>Proximity to the A595(T) and National Park boundary;
</LI>
<LI>Proximity of inhabited property; and
</LI>
<LI>Local landscape features.
</LI></UL>
<P>It is relevant to note that no alternative form or siting of the RCF has
been suggested.
</P>
<P><B>Environmental Impact
</B></P>
<P>8.72 In terms of environmental impact the Environmental Statement and
evidence presented to this Inquiry, it has been shown that:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The RCF can be accommodated into the landscape without significant adverse
effect. It does not directly affect the National Park and will not be
detrimental to its present character and qualities;
</LI>
<LI>Beyond short term disruption to a number of rights of way during the
establishment of Services Corridors and temporary loss of shooting rights and
relocation of the Riding Club, the RCF will not have any effect on public access
and recreation;
</LI>
<LI>The agricultural land affected by the development is Grade 3B and not
subject to special protection. Restoration proposals will allow the site to be
returned to productive agriculture, save for the loss of a small area to
landscape planting;
</LI>
<LI>The proposal will not directly affect designated nature conservation sites.
Indeed the area is of no special ecological interest. Measures to control
effluent and limit drainage will give adequate protection to a population of
Natterjack toads some kilometres from the site. Measures will be adopted to
mitigate the effect of loss of, and reduced accessibility to, ground used by
badgers for foraging;
</LI>
<LI>The loss of one minor archaeological feature will be of low significance;
and
</LI>
<LI>Air quality, water quality and noise and vibration levels in the vicinity
of the site will be well below established standards. The local residents at
nearby premises will not experience a nuisance due to these factors during site
construction or operation.
</LI></UL>
<P>Highway Impact
</P>
<P>8.73 Mr Purcell's evidence indicates that the increase in traffic flows as a
result of the development will be within the increase that can be expected due
to national growth on surrounding roads over the planned life of the
development. Adequate highway and junction capacity exists to serve the site.
This is confirmed in the absence of objections from either the Department of
Transport or the County Highways Department. The proposal may therefore be
judged to meet the requirements of relevant transport and highways policies in
the statutory and emerging development plans.
</P>
<P>Socio-Economic Impacts
</P>
<P>8.74 Professor MacKay's evidence points to the positive contribution which
the development will make to a local economy where local employment prospects
are not promising. It is estimated that nearly 1,690 man years of employment
will result from the project to the benefit of the local area.
</P>
<P>8.75 The development is not expected to result in significant additional
demands for accommodation or public services which cannot be met in the
locality.
</P>
<P>8.76 There is no evidence that the nuclear industry or the RCF has or will
prevent new activities from developing by deterring inward investment and
tourism. Accordingly, it is concluded that the socio- economic impact of the RCF
will be unambiguously positive.
</P>
<P> Overall Planning Assessment
</P>
<P>8.77 I have considered the requirements of the relevant policies in both the
statutory and emerging development plans and for the reasons I have given, I
conclude that the RCF accords with them. The Government stated in July 1995 that
Nirex should continue with its programme to identify a suitable site for a deep
repository and that the RCF forms part of these investigations. There are no
other material considerations which outweigh the presumption in favour of
granting planning permission for this development. I therefore conclude that
this planning appeal should be allowed.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>9. CONCLUSION
</B></P>
<P>9.1 Overall, the RCF will provide very clear benefits. It will help:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>To secure a long term solution to the safe disposal of the nation's low and
intermediate level radioactive waste. In this regard the RCF is fundamental to
one of the principles of sustainable development in that it will provide the
information necessary for this and future generations to take decisions about
the long term protection of the environment;
</LI>
<LI>Nirex to decide whether or not to make a planning application for a deep
repository in the Sellafield area and to produce a full assessment of post
closure safety; and
</LI>
<LI>To support local employment and income for the duration of the development.
</LI></UL>
<P>9.2 The development is in general accordance with the provisions of both
statutory and emerging development plans. The national and local benefits
arising from the development clearly outweigh the limited and temporary
environmental harm which may arise.
</P>
<P>9.3 In my opinion there is a clear case for planning consent to be granted.</P>
