<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">SUPPLEMENTARY</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">PROOF OF EVIDENCE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">OF</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">Mr C H BALCH</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="4">MA, MPHIL, MRTPI, ARICS</FONT><BR><BR></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">THE IMPLICATIONS OF THE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">ADOPTION OF REPLACEMENT</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">CUMBRIA AND LAKE DISTRICT</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">STRUCTURE PLAN 1991-2006</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD><A HREF="../nrx11ix.htm">Back to NRX11 Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../poe.htm">Back to POE Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>1. INTRODUCTION 
</B>
</P>
<P>1.1. On the 3Oth July 1995 Cumbria County Council formally adopted the
Cumbria and Lake District Structure Plan 1991-2006, referred to in my main proof
as the 'Replacement Structure Plan' (C0R/303). This document, as amended in
accordance with the direction of the Secretary of State for the Environment,
replaces the Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan 1988 (referred to as
the 'Former Structure Plan') (COR/302) as part of the statutory development
plan. This decision remains open to legal challenge for a period of six weeks
following adoption. 
</P>
<P>1.2. This short supplementary proof deals with the implications of this
adoption for consideration of this appeal. 
</P>
<P><B>2. STATUTORY DEVELOPMENT PLAN</B>
</P>
<P>2.1. As indicated at paragraph 8.2 of my proof of evidence, the starting
point for the assessment of the RCF Appeal must be the statutory development
plan. This is now as follows:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>the Cumbria and Lake District Structure Plan 1991-2001 (C0R/303) and
</LI>
<LI>the Mid Copeland Local Plan 1990. (COR/305)
</LI></UL>
<P>Emerging development plan policies are contained in:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The Copeland Local Plan Deposit Draft, July 1994, (COR 306) and
</LI>
<LI>Cumbria Minerals and Waste Local Plan, Draft for Public Consultation(COR
311).
</LI></UL>
<P><B>3. IMPLICATIONS</B>
</P>
<P>3.1. The Former Structure Plan, which was in force at the time at which the
Application was determined and this Appeal made, is now of little significance
in planning terms.
</P>
<P>3.2. Insofar as the Former Structure Plan is of significance, this relates
primarily to the indication it provides of whether planning policy has become
more or less restrictive over time.  
</P>
<P>3.3. Comparison of the policies in the Former and Replacement Structure
Plans, for example Policy C1 with Policy 13 and Policy C6 with Policy 54, does
not indicate any significant shift in policy emphasis. Rather the approach has
been to elaborate and clarify the policy framework which seeks: 
</P>
<UL>
<LI> to protect the character and appearance of specially designated areas in
Cumbria
</LI>
<LI>to ensure that the rest of the countryside is protected from inappropriate
development;  and
</LI>
<LI>to ensure that decisions in relation to major developments are taken on the
basis of a  balanced assessment of environment, economic and social costs and
benefits.</LI></UL>
<P>3.4. The planning assessment contained in Section 8 of my main proof
examines the Appeal proposals against key policies contained in the Former and
the Replacement Structure Plan. In both cases, I conclude that the development
is in accordance with these policies. In this regard the formal adoption of the
Replacement Structure Plan makes no difference to my conclusion that the Appeal
should be allowed. 
</P>
<P><B>4. CONCLUSIONS
</B>
</P>
<P>4.1 The Cumbria and Lake District Structure Plan 1991-2006 was formally
adopted on 30th July 1995. It now forms part of the statutory development plan.</P>
<P>4.2. The Former Structure Plan is now only of significance insofar as it
indicates whether or not there has been a change in policy of relevance to the
Appeal proposals. No such shift has occurred. 
</P>
<P>4.3. The Appeal proposal is in accordance with the provisions of the
statutory development plan and should be allowed. 
</P>
<P></P>
