<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>1. INTRODUCTION 
</B>
</P>
<P>1.1. On 14th July 1995, Cumbria County Council issued a Consultation Draft
Minerals and Waste Local Plan (COR/311) for comment by the 8th September 1995.
</P>
<P>1.2. The Plan is intended to replace the deposit Cumbria and Lake District
Joint Minerals Plan and the adopted Coal Local Plan. 
</P>
<P>1.3. Ultimately it will form part of the Statutory Development Plan
alongside the Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan 1991-2006 (COR/303)
and adopted Local Plans. However, it has to pass through a number of stages with
the result that it should be accorded only limited weight in line with the
advice contained in PPG 1. (GOV/1O1) 
</P>
<P><B>2. PLAN CONTENT
</B>
</P>
<P>2.1. The Plan sets out a set of guiding principles which govern the County
Council's approach to minerals and waste planning in Cumbria.  These include the
following:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Adequate provision should be made for the handling, processing and
treatment of waste arising in the County and where unavoidable/necessary, its
disposal. In this regard the Plan points out that Cumbria should take
responsibility for the waste it produces.
</LI>
<LI>In making provision for minerals and waste sites consideration should be
given in minimising traffic. Provision should be made, where possible, close to
the areas of demand the areas of demand (the proximity principle).</LI>
<LI> Cumbria is generously enclosed with fine landscapes and areas of natural
and built heritage, many of which are of national or international importance.
These areas should be protected and enhanced for the benefit of present and
future generations.  Proposals which have an unacceptable effect on local
communities will be resisted.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.2 The Plan notes that minerals and waste disposal sites normally have to
be located in<B> </B>the countryside, but they will be directed away from
sensitive areas. In this regard the Plan explains that Policy 13 of the
Replacement Structure Plan aims to allow necessary rural change to be
accommodated in the countryside whilst protecting the undeveloped open
countryside from non-essential development.
</P>
<P>2.3 The Plan indicates that the County Council supports mineral exploration
as it increases the knowledge and understanding of the mineral resources.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Policy 43 states that:<BR>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Planning permission will be granted for mineral exploration
provided there are no significant adverse effects on local communities or the
environment.&quot;</I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>However, the Plan points out that the grant of planning permission for
exploratory boreholes will not commit the County Council to approve subsequent
applications for appraisal and production development.</P>
<P>2.4 In setting out its policies for the management of wastes, the Plan does
not provide specific policies dealing with radioactive waste, and indicates that
any such proposals will be considered against Structure Plan policies.
</P>
<P>2.5 The Plan includes an Appendix which provides a statement on the County
Council's position with respect to radioactive waste. This does not take into
account the Government's recent White Paper.  In this regard, the Cumbria
Minerals and Waste Local Plan Consultation Draft does little to clarify issues
facing the RCF Inquiry. 
</P>
<P>2.6 The Plan does, however, make provision for inert wastes arising from
construction projects. Policy 51 states that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Planning permission will be granted for landfill sites for the
disposal of men waste arising from major construction projects provided the site
is adjacent  to the project and there are not environmental economic and social
benefits compromised with disposing of the waste at existing sites.&quot;
</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The spoil disposal arrangements associated wit the RCF proposal are fully in
accordance with this policy.
</P>
<P><B>3. CONCLUSIONS 
</B>
</P>
<P>3.1 The Cumbria Minerals and Waste Local Plan Draft for Public Consultation
is at an early state in the plan preparation process and should therefore be
accorded only limited weight. 
</P>
<P>3.2 The Plan provides a clear policy basis against which to consider
applications for mineral exploration based upon local consideration of impact on
local communities and the environment without prejudice to any future
development. 
</P>
<P>3.3 The Plan contains no specific policies dealing with radioactive waste.
It simply refers to the policies of the Replacement Structure Plan. 
</P>
<P>3.4 The Plan contains a policy providing for landfill sites for the disposal
of inert waste arising from major construction projects. The RCF is in
accordance with this policy.
</P>
<P></P>
