<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>1. SUMMARY
</B>
</P>
<P><B> Scope of Evidence
</B>
</P>
<P>1.1 Evidence is presented, additional to <A HREF="nrx12.htm"><B>PE/NRX/12</B></A>,
in respect of:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI>volumes of waste for deep disposal;
</LI>
<LI>a new timetable scenario and updated cost projections;
</LI>
<LI>the Board's consideration of the outcome of the MADA process which led the
Company to investigate sites at Dounreay and Sellafield to establish their
suitability;
</LI>
<LI>policy matters raised in Proofs of Evidence by Cumbria County Council and
in cross-examination of Mr Balch;
</LI>
<LI>RWMAC's September 1995 report on the RCF; and,
</LI>
<LI>Nirex policy on publication.
</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B> Repository Capacity
</B>
</P>
<P>1.2 <A HREF="nrx12.htm"><B>PE/NRX/12</B></A> indicated that Nirex was
planning for the disposal of 400,000m<SUP>3</SUP> of waste.  In the light of
updated indications from customers, a new planning basis of a range of volumes
of between 200,000-275,000m<SUP>3</SUP><B> </B> has recently been adopted. 
Estimates of the radioactivity in terms of key radionuclides have reduced by a
generally smaller proportion than the volume. The reductions have no significant
effect on the need for the RCF. 
</P>
<P><B> Planning Timetable and Projected Expenditure
</B>
</P>
<P>1.3 In view of an expected longer duration for the inquiry and an indication
of the timing of submission of the Inspector's report to the Secretary of State,
new assumptions have been adopted for the Company's forward programme. These
indicate that, if development of the RCF commenced in July 1997, the earliest
date for first waste emplacement in a deep repository would be the first half of
2012.  However, Nirex will be declaring no new target date for first waste
emplacement until the Secretary of State's decision on the RCF appeal is known.

</P>
<P>1.4 An update of the Company's projected expenditure up to the point of
first waste emplacement in a DWR at Sellafield indicates an overall net
reduction of &#163;64 million to &#163;1820 million at 1995 prices.  Projected
outlays on the RCF are unchanged.
</P>
<P>1.5 Projections are presented of the Company's Sellafield-specific
expenditure up to a decision about submission of a DWR planning application
taken at various times.  A decision taken at the end of Phase 1 of the RCF
science programme would imply, from 1 April 1995, Sellafield-specific outlays
estimated at &#163;238 million. 
</P>
<P><B> MADA and the 1989 Company Decision
</B>
</P>
<P>1.6 In late 1988 and early 1989 the Board gave careful consideration to the
MADA recommendations and the results of public consultation undertaken between
1987 and 1988 in choosing, from amongst a shortlist of outstanding sites, sites
at which geological investigations would commence.
</P>
<P><B> Policy Matters
</B>
</P>
<P>1.7 There could well be sites amongst the shortlist of 12 considered in 1989
which would enable a repository to offer an even lower level of post-closure
radiological risk to an individual than that which, in the Company's view, could
be offered by the Sellafield site. However, Government policy does not require a
repository site to be chosen so as to provide an annual level of individual risk
even lower than the 10<SUP>-6</SUP> target. 
</P>
<P>1.8 Consideration of provisions of <I>the Green Book,</I> <I>the 1986
White Paper</I> and <I>the 1995 HMIP Consultation Draft</I> shows that the RCF
proposal is not in conflict with these.  The RCF approach was aimed at meeting
key requirements.
</P>
<P>1.9  Other matters arising in Inquiry evidence and in cross-examination are
reviewed.  It is noted that the suitability of any site is properly based on the
assessment of the performance of the complete repository system, not individual
features of the geology or hydrogeology.  Also, the Company has taken no view on
the weight which the regulatory authorities could or should accord to the
resources committed at Sellafield in the event that individual risk performance
were assessed to lie above the 10<SUP>-6</SUP> target. 
</P>
<P><B> The September 1995 RWMAC Report
</B>
</P>
<P>1.10 This report concludes that the RCF is an integral part of the Company's
science programme. It comments upon the use of the RCF for construction of the
DWR and on the timing of a decision on whether to apply for planning permission
to develop a DWR.  On these matters, the Company's forward programme is planned
on a flexible and provisional basis. As the Committee's report points out,
results from investigations in Phases 2 or 3 of the RCF programme may be
required before a decision can be made about submission of a planning
application to develop a DWR.
</P>
<P><B> Policy on Publication
</B>
</P>
<P>1.11 In order to promote public confidence, Nirex policy is to make
available high quality information, appropriately peer-reviewed, to a wide
audience.  The Company has recently put forward proposals to Government designed
to enhance and put onto a regular cycle the publication of information about its
scientific work and continuing development of the deep repository programme.
</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>2. SCOPE OF EVIDENCE
</B>
</P>
<P>2.1 This Supplementary Proof presents evidence, additional to my
<A HREF="nrx12.htm"><B>PE/NRX/12</B></A>, under five headings:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI>the Company's latest assumptions about waste volumes for deep disposal in
the Nirex repository;
</LI>
<LI>a new timetable scenario and revised cost projections, consistent with
latest indications about the planning inquiry timetable and reflecting budgeting
work done since August 1995;
</LI>
<LI>the procedure by which the Board decided in 1989, as a first step, to limit
the Company's further investigations to Dounreay and Sellafield from amongst the
shortlist of 12 sites and the relationship of certain estimates of radiation
dose given in <I>PERA</I> [COR/501] to estimates used during the  MADA process;
</LI>
<LI>various policy matters raised in evidence in the proofs PE/CCC/1, PE/CCC/6
and PE/CCC/7, by Mr Richardson, Mr Parker and Mr Hetherington respectively, and
in cross-examination of Mr Balch in Part A of the inquiry;
</LI>
<LI>the RWMAC report entitled  <I>Review of aspects of the scientific mission
and role of the Nirex Rock Characterisation Facility at Sellafield</I> published
on 1 September 1995 (&quot;<I>the September 1995 RWMAC Report</I>&quot;)
[GOV/414]; and,
</LI>
<LI>Nirex policy on publication, including its initiative welcomed by the
Government in paragraph 110 of <I>the July 1995 White Paper</I> [GOV/208].
</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.2 In respect of the third matter listed above, my supplementary evidence
complements a Proof of Evidence, <A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18.htm"><B>PE/NRX/18</B></A>,
by Dr Lawrence Phillips.  That Proof  amplifies previous evidence about the MADA
process used by the Company to assist in its 1989 decision on selection of sites
for further investigation to determine their suitability for construction of a
repository.
</P>
<P><A NAME="RepositoryCapacity"></A><B>3. REPOSITORY CAPACITY
</B>
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para3.1"></A>3.1 Paragraph <A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para4.3">4.3</A> of
my Proof of Evidence
<B>PE/NRX/12</B> explained that the Company was planning for 400,000m<SUP>3
</SUP>of radioactive waste to be disposed of in an underground repository up to
2060.  In late September 1995, in the light of updated indications of customer
requirements which have been provided for conceptual design work, the Company
adopted a new waste volume for its future work.  The new planning basis to 2060
is a range of 200,000m<SUP>3</SUP> to 275,000m<SUP>3</SUP>, including 15,000m<SUP>3</SUP>
of LLW. 
</P>
<P>3.2 Updated indications of the current waste inventory by volume for deep
disposal, and the projection to 2010, are as follows: 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>  equivalent conditioned ILW for deep disposal, m<SUP>3
</SUP>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>  in storage at 1 January 1995  60,000
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>  further arisings to 2010  60,000
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Para3.3"></A>3.3 The reductions in waste volumes reflect revised
projections of future waste-generating activities, improved waste management
practices by Nirex customers, and confirmation that for the foreseeable future
customers expect to meet the bulk of their LLW requirements by disposals to the
Drigg surface facility operated by BNFL.  A forthcoming Supplementary Proof,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15s1.htm"><B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B></A> by Dr Hooper, comments
on the radioactivity content of the reduced volume.  Dr Hooper will explain
that, for radionuclides of chief importance for the performance of a repository
at Sellafield, estimates of radioactivity have generally reduced but by a
smaller proportion than the total waste volume.
</P>
<P>3.4 The reduction in the volume of waste for disposal in a repository will
have no significant effect on the role and nature of the RCF development and the
need for that development.</P>
<P><A NAME="ForwardProgramme"></A><B>4. FORWARD PROGRAMME AND PROJECTED
EXPENDITURE
</B>
</P>
<P>4.1 The  local planning inquiry into the RCF is not now expected to close
until 26 January 1996 or thereabouts, and the Inspector has recently stated the
end of October 1996 as the indicative date for submitting his report to the
Department of the Environment.  Accordingly, the Company has adopted new timing
assumptions for its forward programme and for budgeting purposes.  As part of
its annual budgeting cycle, Nirex has also recosted its contingent forward
programme and a provisional adjustment has been made in respect of the reduction
in expected waste volume.  An updated programme and revised budget projections
are described below.  They do not affect the conclusions drawn in paragraphs
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para9.16">9.16</A> and <A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para9.32">9.32</A>
of <B>PE/NRX/12</B>.
</P>
<P><B> Forward Programme
</B>
</P>
<P>4.2 Assuming the Inspector's Report is presented by the end of October 1996,
the Company would hope that the Secretary of State would be able to give his
decision in the Spring of 1997.  However, for the purposes of the inquiry, and
conservatively, I set out below the implications of a scenario, examined in the
course of the Company's recent budgeting work, in which it is assumed that
development of the RCF would begin at Longlands Farm on 1 July 1997.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.3"></A>4.3 Within such a scenario, the planning dates given
in paragraphs
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para9.22">9.22</A> to 9.25  of <B>PE/NRX/12</B> are revised
to the following:
</P>
