<P>Note that the Sellafield-specific sunk costs to 31 March 1995 have been
reassessed at &#163;187 million, rather than the &#163;252 million quoted in
paragraph <A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para9.28">9.28</A> of <B>PE/NRX/12</B>, which
misclassified certain modelling development work as Sellafield-specific.
</P>
<P>4.11 Expenditure on RCF construction and the RCF Science Programme has been
tailored specifically to the need to investigate the BVG rock at Sellafield. 
All expenditure on those items is thus properly classified as
Sellafield-specific.  However, if the Company decided not to propose development
of a DWR at Sellafield, the experience gained from the Sellafield RCF programme
would be of value in the investigation of another site.  The expenditures would
not be a deadweight loss.
</P>
<P><A NAME="MADA"></A><B>5. MADA AND THE 1989 COMPANY DECISION
</B>
</P>
<P>5.1 In his Proof of Evidence <A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18.htm"><B>PE/NRX/18</B></A>
Dr Phillips explains the process of multi-attribute decision analysis (&quot;MADA&quot;)
which he facilitated between September and November 1988 as a means of bringing
together data and judgments about the 12 short-listed potential repository
sites.  The drawing up of that shortlist was explained in Chapter 6 of <I>PERA</I>
[COR/501] and in paragraphs <A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para9.22">9.22</A> to 6.39 of
<B>PE/NRX/12</B>.
</P>
<P>5.2 The input data for the 30 attributes considered, in respect of each site
reviewed in the MADA process, is shown at
<A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18fig.htm#Table2">Table 2</A> of Dr Phillips' Proof of
Evidence.  Dr Phillips sets out in paragraph
<A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18.htm#Para6.8">6.8</A> of his evidence the
recommendations of the MADA group that at least three and up to five sites be
investigated from amongst Sites 1, 2, 3, 6, 7 and 10.
</P>
<P>5.3 Through late 1988 and early 1989, the Nirex Board considered which sites
should be nominated for further investigation.  The Board took account of:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI>the results of the MADA process, including the recommendations summarised
above;
</LI>
<LI>the outcome of the public consultation process, as reflected in responses
to <I>The Way Forward</I> [COR/203]; and,
</LI>
<LI>the technical, practical, time and resource constraints on the exploration
of several sites simultaneously.
</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.4 The Board weighed these considerations on the basis that the Nirex site
selection approach - beginning with the identification of some 500 sites and the
sequential sieving of them - had been based on a thorough methodology.  It had
been set up with the assistance of external advice and consultation and taking
account of safety, environmental and societal considerations recognised by the
IAEA through a process recommended by that organisation.  The MADA process
itself, in which appropriate specialists and professionals scored each option
against defined attributes, had produced convergence on a small number of
outstanding potential sites.  When the MADA results were presented to them, the
Board posed questions relating to the processes and documentation and confirmed
their general satisfaction with the methodologies employed and the integrity of
the documentation.
</P>
<P>5.5 Some results from the public consultation exercise had been available
for the MADA work and were taken into account in selecting the attributes on
which the 12 sites were scored, as noted by Dr Phillips at paragraph
<A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18.htm#Para5.4">5.4</A> of
<B>PE/NRX/18</B>.  For the Board's decision,
<I>the UEA Study</I> [COR/204], published in November 1988, was available.  
</P>
<P>5.6 The<I> UEA Study </I>[COR/204] explained at paragraphs 1.3.6 and 1.3.16
that the public consultation had revealed that only in West Cumbria and
Caithness  - areas already familiar with the nuclear industry developments at
Sellafield and Dounreay - was there a measure of local authority support for
deep disposal of radioactive waste.  It had also shown that &quot;<I>safety</I>&quot;
was judged to be &quot;<I>the paramount factor for all consultees</I>&quot;,
with the &quot;<I>safe transport of wastes</I>&quot; being &quot;<I>the next
major area of concern</I>&quot; (Executive Summary of COR/204). 
</P>
<P>5.7 The Board considered next steps between December 1988 and February 1989.
 It regarded the outcome of the public consultation process, which had run in
parallel with the site identification work and  the subsequent MADA process, as
particularly important. Public controversy - as mentioned at paragraphs
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para5.3">5.3</A> and 5.4 of <B>PE/NRX/12</B> - had severely
hampered the investigations undertaken between 1983 and 1987 in pursuit of
shallow disposal, in four areas without a measure of support for nuclear
activities.  Against a background where radioactive waste disposal had become
the focus of public alarm, there was doubt within the Board whether it would
prove possible to pursue to a successful conclusion a site where there was no
measure of support in the local community, no matter how good its technical
features.
</P>
<P>5.8 The Board gave particularly close attention to the case for
investigating Site 6.  But its decision was not to commence investigations there
or at Sites 3 or 7.  This was because in the areas in which those sites were
situated the public consultation had revealed no measure of local authority
support. As a first step, choosing from amongst the shortlist of outstanding
sites, the Board decided to limit investigations to three Sites - 1, 2 and 10 -
in Caithness and West Cumbria.  This was on the basis that, if investigations at
 those sites  did not lead to the identification of a satisfactory site for a
repository, it would be necessary to turn to Sites 3, 6 or 7 or to others
reviewed in MADA.  <I>PERA</I> [COR/501] subsequently stated, therefore, that
Nirex did &quot;<I>not rule out the possibility of investigating other
locations at a later stage</I>&quot; (paragraph 6.7.11).
</P>
<P>5.9 Site 2, like Dounreay, was in the Caithness area.  In mid-March 1989 the
Company was informed of the proposed designation of that site by the Nature
Conservancy Council as a Site of Special Scientific Interest.  Nirex decided
that this prospective designation, although not presenting an absolute bar to
any future interest in Site 2, raised questions about the availability of
planning consent for investigations there.  Accordingly, the site was dropped as
a location for early investigation with a recognition that, like others, it
could come back into consideration if both Dounreay (the other Caithness site)
and the Sellafield Basement site in West Cumbria proved unsuitable.  On 21 March
1989 the Company nominated Dounreay (Site 1) and Sellafield (Site 10) for
investigation. 
</P>
<P><B>Individual and collective dose estimates: MADA and <I>PERA 
</I></B>
</P>
<P>5.10  The scoring of the post-closure safety attributes assessed in the MADA
meetings was based on the best available information from the preliminary
post-closure performance assessment work undertaken for the various repository
concepts.  The relevant individual and collective doses are set out in
<A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18fig.htm#Table2">Table 2</A> of Dr Phillips' Proof of
Evidence <B>PE/NRX/18</B>.
</P>
<P>5.11 Subsequent to the MADA recommendations, further post-closure risk
assessment calculations became available.  These incorporated concept-specific
assessments for the small island and &quot;offshore hard rock deep&quot;
options.  Risk estimates for other options were revised, together with the
estimates of collective doses.  The results of these risk calculations were
reflected in Table 5.2 of  <I>PERA </I>[COR/501].  The revised data, site by
site, are shown <A HREF="#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A> of this Proof of Evidence;
<A HREF="#Table5.2">Table 5.2</A> shows the corresponding preference scores for
the same attributes.  The implications of these changes have been modelled using
the HIVIEW software described in Dr Phillips' <A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18.htm"><B>PE/NRX/18</B></A>
and the results are shown in <A HREF="#Table5.3">Table 5.3</A> of this Proof of
Evidence.  Although some individual site preference scores are changed, the
overall MADA site preferences are unaffected.</P>
<P><A NAME="PolicyMatters"></A><B>6.  POLICY MATTERS
</B>
</P>
<P><B> Other locations and limiting radiological risk
</B>
</P>
<P> <U>Site offering lower post-closure risks</U>
</P>
<P>6.1 A recurring theme in Proofs of Evidence from Cumbria County Council is,
with reference to the Sellafield PRZ and in the words of Mr Richardson at
paragraph 9.3.7 of PE/CCC/1:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>... the likely availability of alternatives offering
significantly lower potential levels of risk and more readily determinable
geologies.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> At paragraph 2.5 of PE/CCC/7 Mr Hetherington argues that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>... Nirex, rather than proceeding with the RCF now, should take
time to revisit and re-evaluate a site or sites which are likely to lower
radiological risk and provide greater levels of confidence in their assessment</I>.&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>6.2 These statements are somewhat ambiguous as it is not clear whether &quot;<I>lower
risk</I>&quot; is seen as desirable in itself or as essential because of a
County Council view that the preliminary risk evaluation for Sellafield, as
reported in Dr Hooper's Proof <A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm"><B>PE/NRX/15</B></A>,
suggest that the site will not meet regulatory requirements.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.3"></A>6.3 Any view that it would be appropriate to require
selection of a site providing a level of post-closure radiological risk even
lower that the 10<SUP>-6</SUP> repository design would not appear to be
consistent with Government policy.  Paragraph 78 of <I>the July 1995 White
Paper </I>[GOV/208] stated:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>... The Government therefore confirms the preliminary conclusion
of the review that it is inappropriate to rely on a specified risk limit or risk
constraint as the criterion for determining the acceptability of a disposal
facility.  A risk target, however, should be used as an objective in the design
process and this should be a risk of 10<SUP>-6</SUP>/y of developing either a
fatal cancer or a serious hereditary defect.  Where the regulators are satisfied
that best practicable means have been adopted by the operator to limit risks and
the estimated risks to the public are below this target, then no further
reductions in risk should be sought ...</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> Paragraph 6.17 of <I>the 1995 HMIP Consultation Draft</I> [HMP/1/1] states
that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;... <I>where the Inspectorates can be satisfied that the safety case
has a sound scientific and technical basis, that good engineering principles are
being applied in facility design, construction, operation and closure, and that
the risk to the public is below the target, then no further reductions in risk
need be sought</I>.&quot; 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Para6.4"></A>6.4 For the avoidance of doubt I should state that
the Company's view in 1989, and its view now, is that there could well be sites
amongst the shortlist of 12 which would enable the repository system to offer an
even lower level of post-closure radiological risk to an individual that that
which, in the Company's view, could be offered by the Sellafield Basement.  The
results of preliminary post-closure safety evaluations presented in Table 5.2 of
<I>PERA</I> [COR/501] showed that other geological settings - BUSC and the
Offshore Hard Rock, Deep Water (&quot;OHRDW&quot;) option - could potentially
give a lower level of individual post-closure dose (and hence lower risk) than
the Sellafield Basement.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.5"></A>6.5 The RWMAC advice to Government in 1989,
confirming that the Nirex decision to investigate first at Dounreay and
Sellafield was in line with its previous advice, specifically recognised the
existence of &quot;<I>sites associated with better geological conditions and
which are more robust in radiological terms</I>&quot; (Appendix C of GOV/402). 
That advice was provided prior to the Government's accepting in 1989, in the
terms of <I>the 1989 Parliamentary Statement</I> [GOV/211], Nirex's report
recommending the further investigation of Dounreay and Sellafield.
</P>
<P> <U>Post-closure Collective Dose Estimates</U>
</P>
<P>6.6 Mr Parker, at paragraph 4.9.7 of PE/CCC/6 draws conclusions based on
estimates of post-closure collective dose which were presented in Table 5.2 of
COR/501.  He notes that the estimates for BUSC and OHRDW were less than those
given for the Sellafield Basement.  He points to cost and transport
disadvantages of OHRDW which offset its prospective radiological advantages. 
(This is in line with the Company's conclusion about that option, as reported at
paragraph 6.6.10 of <I>PERA</I> and further explained at paragraph
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para6.50">6.50</A> of
<B>PE/NRX/12</B>.)  Mr Parker therefore proposes that Nirex turn its attention
to &quot;<I>the generic BUSC option instead of Sellafield</I>&quot;. 
</P>
<P>6.7 <I>The 1995 HMIP Consultation Draft </I>[HMP/1/1] indicates, at
paragraph 8.21, that in presenting a safety case a developer should provide
indicators of collective radiological impact &quot;<I>to answer the question as
to how widespread any significant elevation of risk may be as a result of
radioactivity from the disposal facility</I>&quot;.  This is in the context of
the provision of &quot;<I>a wide range of information</I>&quot; to inform the
Inspectorates' view of the proposal.  The quantitative objective for design is
an individual risk target of 10<SUP>-6</SUP> as stated in paragraph 78 of <I>the</I>
<I>July 1995 White Paper </I>[GOV/208] and set down as &quot;<I>Radiological
Requirement R2</I>&quot; at paragraph 6.7 of HMP/1/1.  The calculated collective
dose is therefore not a primary consideration for deciding the acceptability of
a proposed repository.  The Company's view (as expressed in its 1994 response to
<I>the HMIP Consultation Document </I>[GOV/307] and reproduced in NRX/12/5) is
that problems associated with calculating doses to large numbers of people over
very long periods of time can make the results misleading.  Collective dose
estimates based on declared population and behaviour assumptions over limited
timeframes may be a useful comparative indicator of design options, but will
only be supportive to the main arguments advanced in the safety case.
</P>
<P>6.8 RWMAC concluded in their <I>8th Annual Report</I> (paragraph 2.20(ii)
of GOV/411) and confirmed in their <I>14th Annual Report</I> (GOV/406 at page
51) that collective dose is a useful comparative measure of the global scale of
a radiation source.  The figures given in Table 5.2 of <I>PERA</I> [COR/501]
were themselves calculated for a global population.  The estimated collective
doses through the first 100,000 years after repository closure, as tabulated at
paragraph 4.9.4 of PE/CCC/6, include estimates of 2 man Sv for &quot;<I>BUSC</I>&quot;
and 40 man Sv for the<I> </I>&quot;<I>Sellafield BUSC variant</I>&quot;<I>.</I>
 As RWMAC pointed out, such estimates can be usefully compared with estimated
collective dose to the world population from natural background radiation.  Over
100,000 years that is of order 10<SUP>12 </SUP>man Sv (annual collective dose
to the world population from natural background radiation taken as 13 million
man Sv, as stated by the RWMAC at page 50 of GOV/406, multiplied by 10<SUP>5</SUP>
years).
</P>
<P>6.9 Table 5.2 of <I>PERA</I> [COR/501] also included estimates of
post-closure collective dose over 10<SUP>8</SUP> years for various geological
settings.  At paragraph 4.9.4 of PE/CCC/6 Mr Parker comments on the rank order
of these.  For BUSC the estimate was 30,000 man Sv and for Sellafield Basement
200,000 man Sv.  Again it is useful to put such estimates and the difference
between them in the context of an estimated collective dose over the same period
from natural background radiation.  That estimate would notionally be of order
10<SUP>15</SUP> man Sv.  Over 10<SUP>8</SUP> years, however, the significance
of any dose or risk calculations is questionable.  Paragraph 6.14 of <I>the</I>
<I>1995 HMIP Consultation Draft</I> [HMP/1/1] states that at times longer than
those for which conditions can be modelled scoping calculations or qualitative
arguments may be used.
</P>
<P> <U>Radiological Risks during Repository Operation</U>
</P>
<P>6.10 Section 5.4 of <I>the Green Book</I> [GOV/302] stated that the
authorising Departments would &quot;<I>require to be satisfied that in
selecting his preferred site, the developer has not ignored a clearly better
option for limiting radiological risks</I>&quot;.  Section 5.3 of explained,
additionally, that in presenting his safety case for a repository a developer:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;... <I>will not be expected to show that this proposals represent
the best choice from all conceivably possible sites.  Where factors other than
radiological ones have influenced the choice of site, this must be brought out
clearly</I>.&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>6.11 Any assessment of radiological risks from a repository must obviously
take account of risks during both the period before control is withdrawn and the
period thereafter.  Chapter 6 of
<I>the 1995 HMIP Consultation Draft </I>[HMIP/1/1] explains this, maintaining
the requirement previously set down in Sections 3.5 to 3.9 of <I>the Green Book</I>
that the radiological protection principles apply throughout the period of
institutional control and after the withdrawal of institutional controls.
Accordingly, alongside estimates of peak individual doses, and of collective
doses to the public after repository closure, the MADA process also took account
of collective doses to repository workers and the public during the repository's
50 year operating period.  (<I>cf</I>. attributes 19, 20, 14, 16 described at
pages 116-117 of COR/104).
</P>
<P>6.12 As stated in paragraph 5.3.7 of <I>PERA</I> [COR/501], a component (up
to 60 man Sv) of the collective dose to the public during a 50 year operating
period for the repository was projected to arise from waste transport. 
<A HREF="../nrx18/nrx18fig.htm#Table2">Table 2</A> of Dr Phillips' Proof of
Evidence [<B>PE/NRX/18</B>] shows that for the MADA work the Sellafield
Basement option, which minimised the ILW to be transported, was assessed as
minimising the collective dose to the public during the operating period.  For
Sellafield that dose was estimated at 71 man Sv.  This is 37 man Sv less that
the 108 man Sv which was the lowest estimate for any of the other sites.  In
terms of collective dose to the public, this estimated difference during the
operating period almost exactly offset the post-closure advantage over 10<SUP>5
</SUP>years of &quot;<I>the generic BUSC option</I>&quot; evident from Table
5.2 of <I>PERA</I>, to which Mr Parker referred at paragraph 4.9.7 of PE/CCC/6.
 In practice, for inhabitants of the British Isles, for many thousands of years
the net collective dose position tended to favour the Sellafield option.  This
is because the reduction it was estimated to offer in collective dose from
transport during the 50 year operating period arises mainly in Great Britain.
</P>
<P><U><I>The Green Book</I></U>
</P>
<P>6.13 At paragraphs <A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para6.49">6.49</A> and
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para6.50">6.50</A> of <B>PE/NRX/12</B>, I described how the
Company's procedures in its site identification and site selection work through
1988 and into 1989 kept open a wide range of geological options.  The shortlist
of 12 sites included at least the leading two candidates from each of the four
defined rock environments, as well as offshore concepts in hard rock and
sedimentary rock.  The subsequent MADA process to define a subset of the most
promising sites for investigation took account of differing estimated levels of
performance in terms of limiting radiological risks.  The options which
potentially offered lower estimated risks were not ignored. 
</P>
<P>6.14 As explained in Section 5 of this Supplementary Proof, the Company
regards its 1989 decision in respect of Sellafield and Dounreay as rational,
having been based on reasoning related to a range of safety, environmental and
societal considerations recognised in <I>IAEA Safety Series No. 59</I>
[GOV/208] and to basic requirements of Nirex's task.  
</P>
<P>6.15 I conclude that <I>the Green Book</I> requirements to follow a &quot;<I>rational
procedure for site identification</I>&quot; (Section 5.3 of GOV/302) and not to
ignore a &quot;<I>clearly better</I> <I>option for limited radiological risks</I>&quot;
(Section 5.4)<I> </I>were observed in 1989.  Also, nothing in the estimated
collective dose performance of the Sellafield Basement as estimated in 1989
compared with other of the 12 options undermines the rationality of selecting it
as the site at which further investigations are now concentrated.
</P>
<P> <B>A free-standing RCF and Government Policy
</B>
</P>
<P> <U><I>The Green Book</I></U>
</P>
<P>6.16 Mr Hetherington in his Proof PE/CCC/7 comments at paragraph 1.6 that &quot;<I>Nirex's
approach</I>&quot; of, in his words, &quot;<I>seeking to defer any discussion
of site selection</I>&quot; &quot;<I>undermined</I>&quot; a &quot;<I>clearly
defined approach in the</I> [Government] <I>policy applying to Nirex throughout
its programme to date</I>&quot;.  He also asserts there a somewhat different
proposition that: &quot;<I>By splitting out the RCF, Nirex have not followed
the clear assumptions of Government policy</I> ...&quot; as set out in <I>the
Green Book</I>.
</P>
<P>6.17 For the avoidance of doubt, I note that - as explained in paragraphs
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para7.4">7.4</A> to 7.6 of <B>PE/NRX/12</B> - the decision
to propose development of the RCF was based solely on practicability.  The
Company judged that a meaningful &quot;<I>provisional view</I>&quot; from the
regulatory authorities on whether a proposed repository &quot;<I>would be
suitable for authorisation</I>&quot; (paragraph 1.3 of <I>the Green Book)</I>
required confirmatory information from exploratory excavation.  <I>The 1995
HMIP Consultation Draft</I> [HMIP/1/1] (at paragraph 4.11) continues to provide
for such a view to be given to the planning authority, or to the Inspector at an
inquiry, following any application to develop a DWR.  The Company's decision to
adopt an RCF stage - taken in the light of three years of experience from
initial investigations at a candidate repository site - was driven by the need
to provide the regulatory authorities with firmer interpretations of the
hydrogeology, in particular, so that they could provide a view as envisaged in
the Green Book.  The RCF approach was aimed at helping to meet a key provision
of <I>the Green Book</I>, not at &quot;<I>undermining</I>&quot; it.
</P>
<P><I> <U>The 1986 White Paper</U></I>
</P>
<P>6.18 At paragraph 3.16 of PE/CCC/7, Mr Hetherington comments on the
Government's response to a recommendation made by the Environment Committee in
1986.  That recommendation had been that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;... <I>research on a fully constructed deep geological site in this
country is urgently needed and should be implemented</I>&quot; and that &quot;<I>such
a site should be designated as an experimental facility <B>explicitly excluded
from being a potential operational facility</B></I>.&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>(paragraph 115 of GOV/304, my emphasis).
</P>
<P>6.19 The Government's response, stated in paragraph 55 of <I>the 1986 White
Paper </I>[GOV/202], is set out at paragraph 3.15 of PE/CCC/7.  From reading it
as a whole, including the last two sentences, alongside the Environment
Committee recommendation, it is clear that in stating there will &quot;<I>be no
need for a separate experimental facility</I>&quot; the response was addressed
to the specific proposal for  a facility which would have been
<U>geographically</U> &quot;<I>separate</I>&quot; from any potential 
repository site.  It was only in that sense that, in the words of paragraph 3.16
of PE/CCC/7, &quot;<I>freestanding URLs</I> [underground rock laboratories],
<I>as a concept, thus had no place in UK radioactive waste management
procedures</I>.&quot;  The possibility of an RCF - a rock laboratory constructed
at a potential repository site to provide information to enable a decision to be
taken on whether or not to propose repository development there - had simply not
been raised by the Environment Committee. 
</P>
<P><B> Commitment of resources
</B>
</P>
<P>6.20 Mr Hetherington, at paragraphs 3.63 and 3.64 of PE/CCC/7, comments on
the scale of Nirex Sellafield-specific expenditures to date and the commitment
of fresh resources through the RCF programme.  At paragraph 4.10 above I note
that from 1 April 1995 the additional Sellafield-specific resources which would
be expected to be committed by the end of Phase 1 of the RCF amount to some &#163;238
million.  
</P>
<P>6.21 In cross-examination on 19th September, Mr Balch was asked whether
Nirex would regard the extent of such commitment as material to the
determination of any planning application for a DWR at Sellafield.  Questions
have also been asked about whether Nirex would regard the expenditure committed
at Sellafield as a matter to which the regulatory authorities should give weight
in deciding the acceptability of the safety case which Nirex may in due course
present in support of an application made under the Radioactive Substances Act
1993 for authorisation of waste disposal in a repository at Sellafield.  In
particular, views were sought on whether the committed expenditure should be a
factor weighed by the regulatory authorities in deciding the acceptability of
any safety case embodying a calculation of individual risk somewhat above 10<SUP>-6</SUP>.

</P>
<P>6.22  These matters could involve questions of law on which I would not be
competent to express views.  As regards the &quot;planning&quot; context, the
Company has taken no view on the materiality of, and any weight to be given to,
the investigatory expenditures undertaken at a potential repository site in
determining any subsequent application for a substantive development there.
</P>
<P>6.23  Any decision about whether to authorise radioactive waste disposal at
a repository if the calculated post-closure risk exceeded 10<SUP>-6</SUP>, and
what, if any, weight to give in such circumstances to investigatory expenditures
incurred, is for the regulators to decide.  I note in that context that in
paragraph 4 of PE/HMP/1 HMIP have stated:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>Whatever site were selected, the performance requirements which
HMIP would require to be met would be the same.&quot;
</I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> </I>The Company has submitted the RCF planning application in the
expectation that, subject to information from the RCF programme, the Sellafield
site is promising as it will offer a post-closure risk performance meeting the
10<SUP>-6</SUP> target.  The Board has accordingly not addressed the
hypothetical question of what position it would adopt with the regulatory
authorities regarding the committed expenditures if the calculated risk were
above 10<SUP>-6</SUP>. 
</P>
<P> <B>&quot;Geological criteria&quot;
</B>
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.24"></A>6.24 At paragraph 9.3.7 of PE/CCC/1, Mr Richardson
mentions the concept of &quot;<I>a 'poor site' in geological terms</I>&quot;. 
Mr Parker refers, at paragraph 1.4 of PE/CCC/6, to &quot;<I>Nirex criteria</I>&quot;
for geological and hydrogeological properties of candidate repository sites
which would determine their suitability  for a  ILW disposal.
</P>
<P>6.25  In fact Nirex has had and has no policy of fixing geological or
hydrogeological &quot;<I>criteria</I>&quot;  - in the sense of numerical tests
to be satisfied by particular site attributes.  The RWMAC recognised at
paragraph 4.23 of its <I>Thirteenth Annual Report</I> [GOV/405] that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>Nirex has not published any quantitative hydrogeological criteria
by which the potential suitability of a proposed deep repository can be
assessed.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Para6.26"></A>6.26  The Company's view is that the suitability of
any particular site must be based on a safety assessment of the predicted
performance of the complete repository system at that site.
</P>
<P>6.27  I described in paragraph <A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para6.10">6.10</A> of
<B>PE/NRX/12</B>, features and indicators, expressed in qualitative terms,
which the Company used to help to identify generic geological environments which
were the starting point in 1987 for the &quot;<I>Regional Evaluation</I>&quot;
stage of site selection.  These features were recapitulated at paragraph 6.3.2
of <I>PERA</I> [COR/501].  It was recognised, as explained at paragraph 3.2.6
of <I>PERA,</I> that it was unlikely that any one location would prove superior
to all others in terms of all the physical properties offered by the host
environment.  Paragraph 6.5.8 of
<I>PERA</I> explained that, with the 500 sites reduced to 39 candidates, it was
generic post-closure radiological safety assessments which were applied in
judgements about the suitability of promising sites.  In assessing the promise
of Sellafield, or any other specific site on the shortlist which was
subsequently established , the task now, through site investigations and
modelling, is to build a sufficient understanding of conditions which affect
long-term radiological safety performance of a repository system in that
particular setting.  It is the total geological and hydrogeological picture
which is relevant, as it bears on risk performance and the safety case, rather
than site performance on individual attributes. 
</P>
<P>6.28  This Company view is consistent with the provisions of <I>the 1995
HMIP Consultation Draft</I> [HMP/1/1] which in respect of geology states:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>7.6</I> <I>As part of</I> <I>this demonstration</I> [of the
adequacy of the site] <I>the developer will have to show that the geological
environment is adequately characterised, understood and capable of analysis
necessary to support the safety case.  This will involve consideration of the
lithology, the stratigraphy, the geochemistry, the local and regional
hydrogeology, and the resource potential of the area.  The developer will also
need to assess the potential for, and effects of, dynamic processes such as
seismic events and ground subsidence, see Ref. 24.  Knowledge of the
characteristics of the site will increase progressively through the site
investigation and the facility development phases. 
</I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> 7.7 The physico-chemical and geochemical characteristics of the
geological environment combined with the materials of construction of the
facility should be shown to limit the migration of radionuclides.  It should be
shown that the hydrogeological characteristics of the region and the site under
present and possible future conditions are such as to allow the safety case for
the facility to be made.  This should include consideration of  features and
properties of the site related to release and transport of radionuclides in the
gas phase.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> HMP/1/1 highlights no specific geological or hydrogeological attribute as
being crucial in themselves and consequently lays down no quantitative criteria
for site performance in relation to particular attributes.
</P>
<P><B> Site Confirmation
</B>
</P>
<P>6.29 At paragraph 3.17 of PE/CCC/7 Mr Hetherington  contrasts Nirex
statements about Sellafield not having been selected as the site for the
repository with the explanation in my Proof of Evidence <B>PE/NRX/12</B> (at
paragraph <A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para2.1">2.1</A>) that the RCF sits within a site
confirmation stage of the  Company's programme to provide a deep waste
repository.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.30"></A>6.30  My styling of the RCF as part of &quot;<I>site
confirmation</I>&quot; marks no change of view and is consistent with the fact
that Sellafield has not been selected as the repository site.  As noted at
paragraph
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para6.3">6.3</A> of <B>PE/NRX/12</B>, site confirmation is
the last of the three stages of the site selection process set out by the IAEA
in <I>IAEA Safety Series No. 59 </I>[GOV/501], which is the guidance followed
by the Company.  Table 6.1 of GOV/501 shows &quot;<I>SITE CONFIRMATION</I>&quot;
commencing as the last of the three stages of the &quot;<I>SITE SELECTION
PROCESS</I>&quot;, to give a basis for &quot;<I>Final Site Selection</I>&quot;.
 &quot;<I>Site confirmation studies</I>&quot; begin before, and continue after,
that site selection to inform the &quot;<I>licensing</I>&quot; process and
ongoing &quot;<I>safety analysis</I>&quot;.
</P>
<P>6.31  In the specific UK context, as I explained in paragraph
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para7.9">7.9</A> of
<B>PE/NRX/12</B>: 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>... Final Site Selection ... is a matter for the developer who,
having selected the site, will submit a planning application for development of
the DWR ...</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> This is &quot;<I>the repository 'go/no go' decision</I>&quot; to which Mr
Hetherington refers at Paragraph 3.32 of PE/CCC/7. 
</P>
<P>6.32 Nirex would  select Sellafield as the site for repository development
only as, when and if it makes a planning application for DWR development. 
Information from the RCF will be required to validate hydrogeological models and
for other scientific purposes before the Company can make that decision.  This
was explained in my letter of 11 March 1994 to the Chief Executive of Cumbria
County Council (COR/202, page 455).  As explained in paragraph
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para9.11">9.11</A> of
<B>PE/NRX/12</B>, selection of Sellafield or any other location would need  to
be founded on Company satisfaction that the proposed repository at the site:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI>would meet the regulators' safety requirements;
</LI>
<LI>could be constructed safely; and,
</LI>
<LI>could be constructed at acceptable cost.
</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> In addition the Company would need to be confident that the proposal would
receive planning permission.
</P>
<P>6.33  In the language of <I>the 1989 Parliamentary Statement</I> [GOV/211],
up to the point where with the help of results from the RCF programme, the
Company makes, or decides against, a planning application for DWR development at
Sellafield, Nirex will not be able <I>&quot;to decide on&quot; </I>the <I>&quot;suitability&quot;</I>
of the site.</P>
<P><A NAME="RWMACReport"></A><B>7. THE SEPTEMBER 1995 RWMAC REPORT
</B>
</P>
<P>7.1 On 1 September 1995 the RWMAC published <I>the</I> <I>September 1995
RWMAC Report</I> [GOV/414].
</P>
<P><B> Origins of the Report</B>
</P>
<P>7.2 Paragraphs 1 to 3 of  GOV/414 state that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>1. This report is concerned with a review of certain aspects of
the Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF) which UK Nirex Ltd. proposes to
construct as a part of the investigation of the potential of the Sellafield Site
for the development of a deep underground repository for the disposal of
intermediate level radioactive waste.  Nirex invited the RWMAC in March 1994 to
carry out a review of the Scientific Mission for the RCF which is described in
the memorandum &quot;Update on the Scientific Mission of the RCF&quot; (Annex
2).  A RWMAC Working Group discussed that document with Nirex in June 1994 and,
subsequently, Nirex has provided additional information.
</I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> 2. At the same time as the approach from Nirex, Cumbria County Council
invited comment from the RWMAC on the role of the RCF in the short-term as a
research facility, and its relationship in the longer term to the construction
and operation of the eventual repository if one were to be built, together with
any post-closure implications.  The RWMAC was also asked to comment on the
appropriateness of the RCF science programme, at the current state of
development of the project, the minimum level of experimentation required to
substantiate the safety case for any planning application for the repository,
and the types of experiments which could be left until construction was under
way, if approved.
</I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> 3. The RWMAC decided, in the light of the overlap between these two
requests, to write a single response.  There have been significant developments
with regard to the RCF in the intervening months between these approaches by
Nirex and Cumbria County Council.  A planning application for the construction
of the RCF was submitted by Nirex in July 1994, and in December 1994, the
application was rejected by Cumbria County Council.  A planning inquiry into the
RCF is to commence on 5 September 1995.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.3 The Nirex memorandum to which reference is made in paragraph 1 of
GOV/414 was submitted to the Committee in March 1994 and is reproduced as ANNEX
2 of its report.  It describes the scientific mission of the RCF and relates it
to the RCF design which was later embodied in the RCF planning application
submitted on 29th July 1994.
</P>
<P>7.4 Paragraph 6 of <I>the September 1995 RWMAC Report </I>[GOV/414] states
in part:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>The Nirex proposal for a RCF is, of course, on the site of a
potential deep repository and could, at the out-turn, have four separate
functions:
</I>
</P>
<UL>
<LI><I>an underground research laboratory constructed on the same basis as
those developed primarily for generic purposes elsewhere in the world;</I>
</LI>
<LI><I>a site specific underground investigation of actual ground conditions
at the site of a possible deep repository in order to assist in the development
of the safety case for, and design and construction of, this repository;</I>
</LI>
<LI><I>a means of access for construction, in part or all, of the repository
in due course once the appropriate assessments have been carried out, and
approvals given;</I>
</LI>
<LI><I>a component part of the repository during operation being used, for
example, for ventilation or emergency access.</I>&quot;
</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Para7.5"></A>7.5 At paragraph 32, GOV/414 suggests a number of
technical matters to which the Company should give particular attention in its
planning and execution of the project.  In the period since March 1994 a number
of these issues have been addressed as part of the continuing development of the
programme.  Other Nirex Proofs of Evidence comment on all the matters concerned.
</P>
<P>7.6 The Committee's &quot;<I>Conclusion</I>&quot; given at paragraph 45 of
<I> the September 1995 RWMAC Report </I>[GOV/414] is:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>The RCF is an integral and necessary part of the overall Nirex
science programme forming an essential step in establishing the post-closure
safety case for the repository ahead of construction.  The timing of the RCF, in
relation to the current overall Nirex programme, is such that only limited data
will be available at the time that a planning application would be made for the
repository.  It is, however, important that the results of the RCF programme be
available in time for that inquiry.  For Nirex to have assurance of achieving
the planned date for commissioning of the repository of by around 2010, then it
would be necessary to use the RCF shafts for construction purposes.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B> Comment
</B>
</P>
<P>7.7 The purpose of the RCF, as explained in paragraph 9.1 of the Supporting
Statement for the Planning Application [COR/102], aligns closely with the second
function identified at paragraph 6 of GOV/414.  The purpose of the development
is site specific, although some of what is learnt may be of generic application.
 If at any time the Company decided that the Sellafield site were unsuitable for
repository development then its intention would be to withdraw and implement the
restoration programme for the site.
</P>
<P>7.8 If results from the RCF confirm the suitability of the Sellafield site
in terms of the considerations explained in paragraph
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para7.8">7.8</A> of <B>PE/NRX/12</B>, the Company will
submit a planning application to develop a DWR there.  The Company has taken no
decisions about the extent to which it might, in that event, propose use of the
RCF shafts in constructing any DWR at Sellafield or within its design.  Such
reuse of some of the RCF workings would be within the scope of the latter two
functions listed in paragraph 6 of GOV/414.  On current thinking, however, Nirex
would probably propose reuse of the shafts for ventilation of a DWR and for
emergency access, though the shaft dimensions have not been determined by such
potential reuse.  Both radiological safety - the avoidance of unnecessary
penetrations through the rock - and cost considerations would favour that
approach.  For the same reasons and subject to the priorities of the RCF Science
Programme, some galleries constructed in Phases 2 and 3 of the RCF would be
considered for incorporation in the DWR.  
</P>
<P>7.9 As explained to the RWMAC, the Company has also considered options which
&quot;<I>would require the RCF shafts to be used for access and spoil removal</I>&quot;
(paragraph 41 of GOV/414).  One approach would be to use such access, subject to
the requirements of the RCF Science Programme, to support the driving of the DWR
access tunnels partly from the RCF horizon.  Reliance on driving the access
tunnels solely from the surface risks delay if tunnelling conditions prove
difficult in the overlying sandstones.  
</P>
<P>7.10 The Company has acknowledged this position publicly whilst emphasising
two points:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI>the specification and design of a DWR at Sellafield, and the appropriate
methods and programming for its construction, are only developed in outline and
it is too early to take any decisions on use of the RCF shafts or other parts of
the RCF workings; and,
</LI>
<LI>as stated in 1992 in paragraph 1.9 of <I>Nirex Report 327</I> [COR/504]:&quot;</LI></UL>
<P><I>None of the RCF workings could become part of a repository, at any time,
unless regulatory licences and authorisations were received and entirely
separate planning approval were given.  That approval would be granted only
after a full Public Inquiry into a repository development application, which the
Secretary of State has undertaken to &quot;call in&quot; for his own
determination.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.11 Paragraph 40 of <I>the September 1995 RWMAC Report</I> [GOV/414]
states that: &quot;<I>At the time of the publication of the revised design of
the Sellafield Repository in 1991 it was made clear that the shafts near
Gosforth would not be used for construction purposes.</I>&quot;  The Company is
unaware of any such statement by it at that time.  Only with the subsequent
proposal for an investigatory RCF development has there arisen the potential to
modify the construction programme for any DWR by using the RCF shafts, as
pre-existing underground access, to reduce the DWR construction period and/or
make the programme more robust.  The fourth and fifth sentences of paragraph 40
of GOV/414 appear consistent with that perspective on the matter.
</P>
<P><B> Timing
</B>
</P>
<P>7.12 Paragraph 35 of GOV/414 states in part:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>According to the current schedule much of the data obtained from
the RCF will be obtained after the planning application </I>[for the DWR]<I>has
been made.  The Royal Society Study Group has also commented on the same point
indicating that the RCF &quot;will need to operate for several years&quot; in
order to make a substantial contribution to the post-closure performance
assessment.  This would mean that the repository planning application should not
be made much before 2005.  Nirex's published programme is thus extremely tight
and may have to be extended.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.13 <A HREF="../nrx16/nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A> of Dr
Mellor's Proof of Evidence <B>PE/NRX/16</B> shows that the planned duration of
the RCF Science Programme - Phases 1, 2 and 3 - approaches ten years, to support
possible preparation of a final safety case for a repository at Sellafield.  As
noted in paragraph 4.10 of this Supplementary Proof, the end of Phase 3 is now
indicated as March 2007.  However, the Company believes it reasonable to assume
that, by the end of Phase 1, sufficient information may be available to enable
the regulatory authorities to &quot;...
<I>comment on whether or not there appears to be any impediment, in the light
of the information available to them ...  to an authorisation which would
eventually permit disposal of waste ...</I>&quot; (paragraph 4.11 of <I>the
1995 HMIP Consultation Draft</I> [HMP/1/1]).  At paragraph
<A HREF="../nrx13/nrx13.htm#Para6.26">6.26</A> of <B>PE/NRX/13</B>, Dr Holmes
summarises the basis for this view.
</P>
<P>7.14 However, the Company has long emphasised, as explained in paragraphs
<A HREF="nrx12.htm#Para6.19">6.19</A> and 9.20 of <B>PE/NRX/12</B>, that its
forward programme can only be planned on a flexible and provisional basis and
that results from investigations in Phase 2 and possibly Phase 3 could be
necessary before a decision is made on repository development.  <I>The
September 1995 RWMAC Report</I> [GOV/414] recognises this position in paragraph
34, which states in part:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> </I>&quot;<I>Nirex assures the Committee that planning permission will
not be applied for until a sufficient level of confidence in the safety
assessment has been achieved.</I>&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Publication"></A><B>8. POLICY ON PUBLICATION
</B>
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para8.1"></A>8.1 In order to promote public confidence in the
repository programme, Nirex has a policy of making available to the regulating
bodies, interested groups and the public at large, a wide range of information
on its programme, and in particular its scientific activities.  So far, Nirex
has published more than 500 scientific reports and papers and has made a further
1600 reports available for reference.  The Company's record in open reporting of
scientific results compares well with the practice of radioactive waste disposal
agencies overseas.  Nirex's practice also extends far beyond any statutory
requirement.
</P>
<P>8.2 The Company's policy is also that its published reports must be of high
quality.  Our reporting is intended to provide a balanced and objective account
of the work, conclusions arising and remaining uncertainties, and it includes
referencing of underlying material which is also available.  Both the RWMAC and
the Royal Society Study Group have praised Nirex for the quality of its
information.  For example, the RWMAC's <I>Fifteenth Annual Report</I> [GOV/407]
states at paragraph 4.6:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>The Committee would record, again, its view that the field work,
and the interpretation of site data, being carried out by Nirex staff and by
Nirex's contractors is of the highest quality</I>.&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> The Royal Society Study Group stated at Section 1.9 on page 9 of COR/605:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>We have been impressed by the quality of individual items of
scientific work undertaken and commissioned by Nirex, which command high respect
from others engaged in parallel work world-wide.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> and stated at Section 6.8 on page 110:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> &quot;<I>Nirex site characterisation work at Sellafield has been of very
high quality.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.3 In order to achieve high quality in its published reports, the Company
ensures that data are thoroughly checked, and interpretations and modelling
results are properly debated and, if appropriate, further developed prior to
publication.  Some interim reporting, which is not published, is associated with
this process and is a necessary precursor to the production of reports of the
standard necessary for review by the academic community and the public at large.
</P>
<P>8.4 Nirex procedures provide for proper independent review of all work
critical to radiological safety, as required by BS 5882, which the Company
follows in its work.  That review is conducted by experts who have not been
directly involved with the piece of work concerned.  Frequently those experts
have no direct involvement in any aspect of the Nirex programme.  This approach
is analogous to, but generally goes into more detail than, the refereeing
process for published papers in academic journals.  The result of this process
is the release of high quality information which Nirex, as the organisation
responsible for the development of a repository, stands behind as the current
position on the relevant aspects of its programme.  The reports are also
provided to the regulators for information although, in due course, the
acceptability of any proposed repository will be decided on the basis of the
application that Nirex will make for authorisation under the Radioactive
Substances Act 1993.
</P>
<P>8.5 Nirex information is also available for review by the scientific
community at large and by the local communities within which Nirex operates. 
Such review is important, particularly in promoting public understanding and
confidence.  It is complementary to, but not in the final analysis part of, the
peer review process required for a nuclear safety case.  Just like the developer
of a nuclear power station or a spent fuel reprocessing plant, Nirex is engaged
in a practical engineering task to meet an identified objective, which is
provision of a deep repository for safe disposal of radioactive waste.  As with
the safety case for any nuclear facility in the UK, it is for the developer of a
repository to ensure that regulatory principles and requirements are met (see
paragraph 1.12 of <I>the 1995 HMIP Consultation Draft</I>, HMP/1/1).  Nirex
peer review is structured appropriately to that task and not to sustain academic
debate for its own sake.
</P>
<P>8.6 Paragraph 110 of <I>the July 1995 White Paper</I> [GOV/208] explains
that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> </I>&quot;<I>In view of the importance which the RWMAC/ACSNI report
attached to transparency of decision making, Nirex has indicated to the
Government that it is formulating proposals to enhance and put onto a regular
cycle the publication of information about its scientific work and development
of the repository programme.  The Government welcomes this initiative and will
seek the advice of RWMAC on the company's proposals.</I>&quot;
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> On 13 July 1995 the Chairman of Nirex wrote to the Department of the
Environment explaining the Company's proposals.  A copy of his letter is
provided as NRX/12/6.  A copy of a bibliography, Nirex Report S/95/001 which
accompanied his letter, is provided as NRX/12/7.
</P>
