<P><A NAME="TA4"></A><B>Table A.4:  Core Characterisation and Description -
Activities and Component Tests</B></P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
<TR ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD ALIGN="Center" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1"><B>Activity</B></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Center" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1"><B>Objective of testing</B></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Center" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1"><B>Component Tests</B></FONT>

</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">Lithostratigraphical Core
Logging</FONT> 
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">To supplement the geological
information on the rock cores.</FONT> 
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">Core Orientation and Depth
Correction 
</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">Using the wireline log data, to
provide absolute orientations of fractures in the core and to provide accurate
depths of core samples. 
</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">Hydrogeological Core Analysis 
</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">To determine hydrogeological
properties of core samples. 
</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">Gas permeability<BR>Permeability
to brine or water<BR>Porosimetry<BR>Pore Volume Compressibility</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">Bulk Rock Petrography and
Geochemistry 
</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">To assist in the detailed
characterisation and identification of the rock types encountered in the cores.
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="Left" VALIGN="Top"><FONT SIZE="-1">Thin section optical petrography<BR>Reflected
light microscopy<BR>Cathodoluminescence microscopy<BR>Scanning electron
microscopy<BR>Dispersive x-ray microanalysis<BR>Electron microprobe analysis<BR>X-ray
diffraction<BR>Thermal analysis<BR>Heavy mineral analysis<BR>Whole rock
chemical analysis<BR>Rare Earth Element Analysis</FONT>    
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">Fracture Petrography and Geochemistry 
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">To provide detailed information on the characteristics of
the minerals which occur within the fractures in the rock. 
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">Thin section optical petrography<BR>Reflected light
microscopy<BR>Cathodoluminescence microscopy<BR>Scanning electron microscopy<BR>Dispersive
x-ray microanalysis<BR>Electron microprobe analysis<BR>Fluid inclusion studies<BR>Stable
isotopes (Carbon, Oxygen, Sulphur and Strontium)<BR>Fracture logging</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">Geotechnical and Geophysical Testing 
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">To characterise the mechanical properties of the rocks. 
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">Saturated density<BR>Dry density<BR>Grain density<BR>Saturated
water content<BR>Effective porosity<BR>Slake durability<BR>Swelling index<BR>Uniaxial
compressive strength<BR>Indirect tensile strength - Brazilian method<BR>Strength
under triaxial compression<BR>Elastic constants under triaxial confinement<BR>Thermal
conductivity<BR>Specific heat<BR>Thermal expansion coefficient<BR>Compressional
and shear wave seismic velocity<BR>Magnetic susceptibility<BR>Remnant
magnetism<BR>Resistivity</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">Core Pore Fluid Extraction and Analysis 
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1">Fluids are extracted from the pores in the rock for
subsequent chemical analysis in order to supplement the hydrochemical data
obtained from analysis of water samples obtained from the boreholes. 
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
