<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>1. SUMMARY</B></P>
<P>1.1 In this Supplementary Proof of Evidence I comment on the Proofs of
Evidence which oppose the planning application for the RCF on the grounds that
aspects of safety assessment research and modelling have not been adequately
addressed by Nirex. I include comments on the Proofs and the Evidence led by:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>Dr Starmer (PE/CCC/5 for Cumbria County Council); </TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>Dr Salmon (PE/FOE/5 for Friends of the Earth) (paragraphs 4.20 to 4.26);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>Dr Hencher (PE/FOE/6 for Friends of the Earth);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv.</TD>
<TD>Dr Allison (PE/FOE/7 for Friends of the Earth);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v.</TD>
<TD>Dr Wogelius (PE/FOE/8 for Friends of the Earth);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>vi.</TD>
<TD>Dr Mackay (PE/GNP/2 for Greenpeace Ltd);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>vii.</TD>
<TD>Dr Haszeldine (PE/GNP/3 for Greenpeace Ltd) (Sections 13 and 14); and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>viii.</TD>
<TD>Mr Richardson (PE/GNP/4 for Greenpeace Ltd) (paragraphs 8.4 to 8.7).</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Principal Points of Agreement</B></P>
<P>1.2 There are four main areas in which there appears to be substantial
agreement or, at least, no dispute between all the principal parties, namely:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>the performance of barriers in the repository system must be evaluated
carefully to ensure that radionuclides would be sufficiently contained by the
system to assure safety of the people living at the time of repository closure
and in the future;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>the groundwater pathway for release of radionuclides from the repository is
the most significant pathway against which barrier performance should be
assessed;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>calibration and validation of models is of importance in assessing
repository performance; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv.</TD>
<TD>Nirex is not yet in a position to make a safety case for the disposal of
radioactive wastes, nor yet to give the regulatory authorities a sufficiently
firm view of the suitability of locating a repository at the Sellafield site to
warrant an application for its development.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Principal Points of Disagreement</B></P>
<P>1.3 The assertions made in the Objectors' Proofs of Evidence which form the
principal points of disagreement that I address in this Supplementary Proof of
Evidence fall essentially into three categories:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>Nirex's evaluation of the post-closure performance of a repository at
Sellafield does not properly reflect current knowledge of the site and processes
influencing radionuclide return: the 'true' performance is likely to give a less
favourable comparison against the regulatory target;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>a detailed understanding of all processes potentially influencing
radionuclide return is required: such understanding has not been achieved and
will require substantial further work; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>in both the above regards, the RCF will not take us significantly forward.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>1.4 The various points raised by the Objectors within each of these
categories are addressed by Sections 4 to 10 of this Supplementary Proof of
Evidence as outlined in paragraphs 1.8 to 1.34 below. In summary my response to
each of the three categories is as follows:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>In its evaluation of Sellafield, Nirex takes a balanced approach to
reflecting current knowledge of the repository system. I believe that we have
properly reflected current knowledge in our performance assessment work and that
the processes and features identified by the Objectors are adequately addressed
for the current stage of development in our programme. Given the agreed
significance of the groundwater pathway, I believe our performance assessment
gives a good indication of the system performance and that the site shows good
promise. However, further work is needed to help resolve uncertainties and the
RCF has an essential role to play in this. Resolving these issues to a
satisfactory level will demonstrate the confidence required to reach a decision
on whether to submit a planning application for repository development.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>Nirex does not accept that a complete understanding of all processes is
essential to assessing system performance. Dealing with uncertainty is
recognised by Nirex and HMIP as an integral part of carrying out post-closure
performance assessments. When knowledge is incomplete it is accepted that this
uncertainty is dealt with either explicitly, within a range of models, or
through the use of appropriate parameter distributions in a probabilistic
assessment.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>The RCF will provide an opportunity to gain further information and reduce
uncertainties in the key areas identified in my Proof of Evidence (<A
HREF="nrx15.htm"><B>PE/NRX/15</B></A>).  The factors directly affecting
repository performance include groundwater flow and radionuclide transport and
the engineered sealing system needed at repository closure. In certain key
areas, the RCF is the only route to obtaining this information and to
demonstrating clearly to decision makers and peer reviewers that Nirex is able
to validate its assessment modelling approach.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Repository Capacity (Section 3)</B></P>
<P>1.5 Information is provided in Section 3 of my Supplementary Proof of
Evidence on the content of key radionuclides in respect of the revised
repository capacity advised by Mr Folger in his Supplementary Proof of Evidence
(<B>PE/NRX/12/Sl</B>, <A HREF="../nrx12/nrx12s1.htm#Para3.1">paragraph 3.1</A>)
to be in the range of 200,000m<SUP>3</SUP> to 275,000m<SUP>3</SUP>.</P>
<P>1.6 The radioactivity contents of chlorine-36, iodine-129 and uranium-238
for the 275,000m<SUP>3</SUP> volume are estimated to be the same as those given
previously in my Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15.htm#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A>, page 63) for a repository capacity
of 400,000m<SUP>3</SUP>. The radioactivity contents of these radionuclides for
the low end of the range, 200,000m<SUP>3</SUP>, are given as 11.7 TBq instead
of 16.6 TBq (chlorine-36), 0.51 TBq instead of 0.919 TBq (iodine-129) and 30 TBq
instead of 35.8 TBq (uranium-238). Reductions would result from the potential
elimination of notional future waste arisings that are included in the figures
given for the 275,000 m<SUP>3</SUP> volume.</P>
<P>1.7 In the remaining paragraphs of this summary I describe the technical
contents of my Supplementary Proof of Evidence. The issues raised by the
Objectors have been grouped under seven topical headings:</P>
<UL>
<LI>  treatment of uncertainty;
</LI>
<LI>  using site investigation data to construct safety assessment model;
</LI>
<LI>  the Nirex repository concept;
</LI>
<LI>  effect of geochemistry on radionuclide transport;
</LI>
<LI>  treatment of the biosphere in performance assessments;
</LI>
<LI>  results of groundwater flow modelling; and
</LI>
<LI>  validation of models and the role of the RCF.
</LI></UL>
<P>The points raised under these topical headings are addressed in Sections 4
to 10 respectively of my Supplementary Proof of Evidence. In this summary I
outline the evidence that I present to rebut the points raised by the Objectors.</P>
<P><B>Treatment of Uncertainty (Section 4)</B></P>
<P>1.8 Dr Starmer (PE/CCC/5) attempts a quantification of the <I>&quot;errors
and uncertainties&quot; </I>associated with the preliminary assessment of the
groundwater pathway presented in <I>Nirex 95</I> [COR/522]. Within his
analysis, he draws on cases set out in <I>Nirex 95</I> [COR/522] to develop
<I>&quot;range bars&quot;. </I>These purport to show the uncertainty associated
with the Nirex risk assessment.</P>
<P>1.9 I refer in Section 4 to one example of Dr Starmer's treatment of a
specific case, given in <I>Nirex 95</I> [COR/522] - the treatment of
sub-surface routing in the biosphere, and to examples of Dr Starmer's treatment
of distributions of probabilities. Dr Starmer has based his assertions on the
performance of a repository at Sellafield on segregation of uncertainty from
risk calculations. This approach is contrary to the requirements of <I>the July
1995 white Paper </I>[GOV/208] in respect of the calculation of risk for
comparison with the risk target.</P>
<P>1.10 Dr Starmer's analysis is meaningless as it is inconsistent with a
number of requirements of a properly structured probabilistic analysis as
follows:</P>
<UL>
<LI> failure to reflect the relative probabilities of different cases;
</LI>
<LI> compounding of unconnected cases;
</LI>
<LI> failure to establish a basis for the mathematical meaning or magnitude of
<I>&quot;range bars&quot; </I>as a measure, he says, of <I>&quot;errors and
uncertainties&quot;; </I>and
</LI>
<LI> the selection of outlying cases. having low probability, rather than the
expectation value of risk for comparison with the risk target - in contravention
of regulatory guidelines.
</LI></UL>
<P>1.11   1 conclude that attempted comparison to the regulatory target is not
based on a sound scientific treatment of risk, being essentially a product of
manipulation of random and incorrectly derived values.</P>
<P><B>Using Site Investigation Data to Construct Safety Assessment Models
(Section 5)</B></P>
<P>1.12 Dr Mackay (PE/GNP/2) draws on experience gained from the conduct of a
theoretical exercise for HMIP to raise questions concerning the relationship of
models used in performance assessments to field observations and the conduct of
site investigations.</P>
<P>1.13 The issues raised by Dr Mackay have been recognised by Nirex in its
work programme. There are significant differences between the Nirex programme,
involving the acquisition of real data from a real site, and the theoretical
HMIP exercise.  In the Nirex work programme, priorities for data acquisition are
guided by reference to performance assessment studies as is the selection of
conservative models and associated parameter values.  This approach is designed
to ensure tat the problems encountered in the exercise carried out by Dr Mackay
for HMIP will not arise.</P>
<P>1.14 Dr Mackay raises other concerns with respect to the calibration and
validation of groundwater flow models, in particular the <I>&quot;macroscopic&quot;,
</I>or regional, groundwater flow model, and to the development and assessment
of alternative conceptual models. Each of these concerns is being addressed in
the Nirex programme. Therefore Dr Mackays overall concern (PE/GNP/2, paragraph
11.2) that these matters require resolution before proceeding with the RCF is
unfounded.</P>
<P><B>The Nirex Repository Concept (Section 6)</B></P>
<P>1.15 Dr Allison (PE/FOE/7) and Dr Wogelius (PB/FOE/S) both make a number of
points concerning the Nirex repository concept. the research and development
programme that supports the assessed performance of the concept and the
relationship of the concept to the experimental programme proposed for the RCF.</P>
<P>1.16 Both Dr Allison and Dr Wogelius appear to base their ideas on views of
the requirements of near-surface facilities for radioactive waste disposal.
These views are not relevant to a deep geological repository. Furthermore,
although Dr Allison and Dr Wogelius both provide evidence for Friends of the
Earth, the basic themes of their respective Proofs of Evidence are inconsistent.
Dr Allison argues that physical containment, to be afforded by engineered 
barriers, is essential to repository performance because of the unreliability of
the natural barrier, and of geochemical equilibria in particular. Dr Wogelius
argues that a <I>&quot;geochemical safely case&quot; </I>is essential because
of the unreliability of engineered barriers in providing physical containment.</P>
<P>1.17 1 reject both these themes because they both over-emphasise the
importance of the performance of one component of the multi-barrier containment
system that is required for the safe disposal of the radioactive wastes
identified in the disposal inventory. Several criteria that Dr Allison and Dr
Wogelius seek to establish in respect of barrier performance or of requirements
for scientific research have no relevance to requirements in relation to
affording radiological protection.</P>
<P>1.18 By reference to published information, uncertainties raised by Dr
Allison and Dr Wogelius concerning the performance of the engineered barriers in
the Nirex repository concept are without proper foundation or are irrelevant. In
some instances, the references cited by Dr Allison and Dr Wogelius in evidence
do not lend support for the statements they make.</P>
<P>1.19 The RCF is needed to address many of those residual uncertainties
identified by Dr Allison and Dr Wogelius that are significant. Where there are
criticisms of the proposed experiments in the RCF, these arise from a failure to
appreciate the nature of the experiment and the relationship of the experiment
to work that has been carried out, is being carried out, or is planned. Issues
raised by Dr Salmon (PB/FOE/S, paragraphs 4.20 to 4.26) concerning the impact of
the RCF on repository performance have been addressed.</P>
<P><B>Effect of Geochemistry on Radionuclide Transport (Section 7)</B></P>
<P>1.20 Dr Haszeldine (PE/GNP/3, Sections 13 and 14) and Dr Wogelius (PB/FOE/S,
Sections 5, 6.7.8 and 9) raise points concerning the effect of geochemistry on
radionuclide transport under four main topics as follows:</P>
<UL>
<LI> the presence and effect of oxidising or reducing conditions in groundwater
(PE/GNP/3, Sections  13 and 14),
</LI>
<LI>radionuclide solution chemistry (PB/FOB/8, Section 5);
</LI>
<LI>mineral surface chemistry (PE/FOB/8, Sections 6 and 7); and
</LI>
<LI>sorption measurements and the use of experiments in the RCF (PB/FOE/S,
Sections 8 and 9).
</LI></UL>
<P>1.21 Concerning the presence and effect of oxidising or reducing conditions
in groundwater, Dr Haszeldine asserts that the presence of hematite in the rocks
of the Sellafield region indicates oxidising conditions at depth which are
deleterious to repository performance. Dr Haszeldine claims that there is no
justification for the controls upon reducing conditions that he believes Nirex
is proposing.</P>
<P>1.22 Dr Haszeldine is incorrect in his treatment and apparent understanding
of the thermodynamic data defining the geochemical stability of hematite.  In
particular Dr Haszeldine does not appear to appreciate that hematite is stable
under reducing groundwater conditions that are typified by the presence both of
neutral to alkaline pH and of other iron-bearing minerals, include pyrite, as
found at Sellafield. Dr Haszeldine is also incorrect in his understanding of the
role of groundwater flow into the repository in respect of his cited performance
measures of release of uranium and corrosion of steel waste containers. The
redox conditions in the groundwater Within the repository near field will be
controlled by the contents of the repository and are not dependent on the redox
conditions of inflowing groundwaters within the ranges proposed by Nirex or by
Dr Haszeldine.</P>
<P>1.23 Dr Wogelius raises a range of concerns about the geochemical aspects of
the assessment of repository performance. None of these raises an issue that is
not covered by information provided in my Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>)
or the calculations of risk reported in <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3) [COR/522]
and the references cited therein.
</P>
<P>1.24 My disagreement with Dr Wogelius' evidence in this area is that he
proposes that a more detailed, mechanistic understanding is required for all the
processes which he identifies. In this, Dr Wogelius appears to misunderstand the
philosophy underlying a probabilistic safety assessment. A complete
understanding of all processes is not required.  Rather, the uncertainty in
parameters must be encompassed fully in the probability density function of
parameter values. Nirex is dealing with uncertainties by making conservative
judgements until such time as these uncertainties can be better resolved.</P>
<P><B>Treatment of the Biosphere in Performance Assessments (Section 8)</B></P>
<P>1.25 Dr Starmer (PE/CCC/5, Sections 3, 4, 5 and 7), makes a number of
observations and criticisms regarding Nirex's treatment of the biosphere in
performance assessments. In particular, he asserts that Nirex has omitted to
consider (or at least to present) a number of analyses and scenarios which would
lead to worse risk predictions than the scenarios actually presented in <I>Nirex
95</I> [COR/522] and that Nirex has treated the agricultural well analysis in a
manner that underestimates the resulting risks.</P>
<P>1.26  The additional analyses and scenarios proposed by Dr Starmer will not
lead to calculations of higher risks as he suggests for the reasons that:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the issue that time-dependent simulations of climate change could increase
calculated risks (PE/CCC/5, paragraph 5.1.2) is based on a single incorrect
result in an HMIP report and the result, even if it had been correct, was
obtained for a system that is not relevant to Sellafield;
</LI>
<LI>the issues of <I>&quot;down-cutting&quot;</I> of streams in the Boreal
climate state (PE/CCC/5, paragraph 5.1.8) and <I>&quot;up-welling&quot;
</I>of groundwater offshore (creating contaminated marine sediments) (PB/CCC/5,
paragraph 5.1.7) are shown to be treated adequately by Nirex, in contradiction
of Dr Starmer's assertions; and
</LI>
<LI>the issues of non-treatment of different hydrological conditions due to
climate changes and of non-presentation of calculated risks for a Temperate
climate state for some cases presented in <I>Nirex 95 </I>[COR/522] are shown
to be of little significance to consideration of the performance of a repository
at Sellafield.
</LI></UL>
<P>1.27 Dr Starmer's criticisms of the agricultural well analysis are based on
unjustified assertions concerning his analysis of information presented in <I>Nirex
95</I> [COR/522].   Dr Starmer's assertion that the analysis will underestimate
risk, because the well has been modelled at insufficient depth to realise the
<I>&quot;maximum plume concentration&quot;</I> (PE/CCC/5, paragraph 4.4.1) is
incorrect.  Dr Starmer's analysis of the well scenario is incorrect in not
recognising that the scenario is an alternative biosphere scenario whereby
exposure to contaminated water is modelled conservatively by the assumed
reliance on the well supply for all water resources. Therefore Dr Starmer's
proposals that additional reliance on well water or addition of the well
scenario <I>to &quot;exposure pathways using only biosphere models&quot; </I>
will increase risk are insupportable.  Dr Starmer is not correct in raising
concerns that both the treatment of other identified radionuclides and the use
of a different dilution model in the well analysis would increase risk.  The
other identified radionuclides would decay long before reaching the sandstones
in significant concentrations and the alternative dilution model is not the
correct model for use with the radionuclides chlorine-36 and iodine- 129 that do
require to be considered.</P>
<P><B>Results of Groundwater Flow Modelling (Section 9)</B></P>
<P>1.28 The Proofs of Evidence by Professor Mather (PE/CCC/4, paragraphs
1.30,6.65 and 6.4.11), Dr Starmer (PE/CCC/5, paragraphs 4.2.1 to 4.2.5, 4.3.1,
4.3.2, 4.5.1 to 4.5.5, 4.6.1 to 4.6.3, 5.1.4, 5.1.6, 5.1.9 and 5.3.1 to 5.3.3),
Dr Salmon (PE/FOE/S, paragraphs 3.17, 3.1 8, 3.22, 3.24 and 7.9) and Dr Hencher
(PE/FOE/6, paragraphs 7.9, 7.11, 9.8, 9.9 and 9.11) make a number of
observations on, and criticisms of the results of the groundwater flow and
radionuclide transport modelling performed in<I> Nirex 95</I> [COR/522] and on
the approach to modelling adopted in the analysis. These comments fail into
three groups of points related to:</P>
<UL>
<LI> modelling approach: it is asserted that aspects of the modelling work are
inappropriate or in some way deficient;
</LI>
<LI> specific results of the modelling: it is asserted that the assessment
models do not deal appropriately with aspects of the behaviour of, or structure
of the site; and
</LI>
<LI> features alleged to be excluded from the models: it is asserted that
certain, potentially important, physical processes have not been included in the
models.
</LI></UL>
<P>1.29 In response to these points, I say:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the modelling approach is appropriate and not deficient and the points
raised generally indicate that important aspects of the Nirex approach have not
been recognised by the Objectors;
</LI>
<LI>the models do deal appropriately with the identified aspects of the
behaviour of, or structure of, the site and the criticisms generally indicate
that the basis for the results or the nature of the results has not been
appreciated; and
</LI>
<LI>the features or processes which the Objectors argue should be included
actually are included in the modelling, when they are realistic features or
processes. When this is not the case it is because there are no sound physical
arguments for their inclusion.
</LI></UL>
<P>1.30 The criticisms of the modelling approach are directed at the following
topics:</P>
<UL>
<LI>development of the conceptual model of the groundwater system and the
method of deriving the parameters of the models;
</LI>
<LI>fracture-network modelling; and 
</LI>
<LI>regional flow modelling.
</LI></UL>
<P>In respect of development of the conceptual model and parameter values, the
criticisms are not supported by the references cited by the Objectors; the Nirex
approach involves the considered selection of appropriate modelling and
numerical techniques. In respect of fracture-network modelling, the criticisms
of the status and development of fracture-network modelling techniques are
ill-founded; there is evidence of the successful and relevant applications of
these techniques which are cited in some of the publications referenced by the
Objectors. In respect of regional flow modelling, a criticism that sensitivity
analysis is not carried out is incorrect. Much criticism of the outputs from
Nirex regional flow modelling stems from an inappropriate synthesis in [GOV/406]
of Nirex results, in which features from different geological cross-sections
were superimposed to produce an unrealistic model.</P>
<P>1.31 The criticisms of the specific results of the modelling are that:</P>
<UL>
<LI>a marine discharge of radionuclides has been assumed and that evidence of
terrestrial discharge of groundwater has been neglected; and
</LI>
<LI><I>&quot;up-welling&quot; </I>associated with the Fleming Hall Fault Zone
has not been addressed in the analysis presented in <I>Nirex 95 </I>[COR/522].
</LI></UL>
<P>A marine discharge has not been assumed, rather it is the output of
groundwater flow modelling. Furthermore, this modelling is supported by the
evidence of the Objectors in respect of terrestrial discharges of groundwater,
since the discharge of water from the BVG at depth would be expected to occur
further offshore than that discharged from the much higher flows in the
overlying sedimentary formations. Preferential pathways for upward flow in the
Fleming Hall Zone were incorporated in the modelling used in the calculations of
risk in <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3) [C0R/522]. The figures identified by the
Objectors are outputs of that process rather than ignored potential inputs.
Nirex has used a conservative treatment of flow in the Fleming Hall Fault Zone
and there is no physical reality to the proposals by Dr Starmer that a
preferential pathway, not considered by Nirex, could exist.</P>
<P>1.32 The criticisms that features have been excluded from the models relate
to the following points:</P>
<UL>
<LI>potential short, fast pathways have been neglected and excessive credit has
been taken for the retardation of radionuclide transport by the process of rock
matrix diffusion;</LI>
<LI>processes that could reduce dilution have been neglected;
</LI>
<LI>unreasonable screening of the radionuclide inventory has occurred; and
</LI>
<LI>specified effects of climate change on hydrogeology should be addressed.
</LI></UL>
<P>The proposal that short, fast pathways have been neglected is incorrect
because it is based on an assertion that has no scientific grounds and is not
supported by use of site data. The modelling of rock matrix diffusion by Nirex
is appropriately conservative; the assertion that excessive credit has been
taken is not supported by information supplied by Nirex in <I>Nirex 95
</I>[COR/522]. The criticism that processes that could reduce dilution have been
neglected is groundless since no realistic processes are proposed: in contrast
the Nirex modelling approach is based upon field observations and the
application of physical laws and is likely to underestimate dilution.  The
criticism of unreasonable screening of the radionuclide inventory has not
occurred: no screening has been carried out and the assertion is based upon an
incorrect analysis of Nirex information.  The glaciation mechanism invoked by Dr
Starmer for the effect of climate change on hydrogeology is translated
incorrectly from the reference cited. Furthermore, both the Periglacial and 
Mediterranean climate-driven mechanisms invoked by Starmer would in fact lead to
lower, rather than higher, calculated risks.</P>
<P><B>Validation of Models and the Role of the RCF (Section 10)</B></P>
<P>1.33 Several of the Objectors' Proofs of Evidence raise the issue of
validation. in particular Dr Salmon (PB/FOE/5, paragraphs 3.28 and 4.27 to
4.29), Mr Richardson (PE/GNP/4, paragraphs 8.4 to 8.7), Dr Hencher (PB/FOE/6,
paragraphs 3.6, 8.5 and 9.4) and Dr Mackay (PE/GNP/2. Section 7). There is an
accepted definition and approach to validation in the context of radioactive
waste safety assessment studies and Nirex is addressing the issue. in particular
with respect to the RCF work programme.</P>
<P>1.34 My overall conclusion in respect of the matters raised on validation by
the Objectors is that Nirex has both a well-developed approach to validation and
an extensive programme of validation exercises completed, underway and planned
for the RCF itself. Nirex is involved in international validation exercises and
is committed to ensuring that its validation work is thoroughly peer reviewed.
Conceptual models used to support safety assessments submitted to the regulators
will have to be shown to be acceptable and to be fit for purpose. As a
consequence, the concerns raised by the Objectors are considered to be ill
founded and to be addressed by work which Nirex already has in hand. The RCF is
an essential component of this work.</P>
<P></P>
