<P><A NAME="Introduction"></A><B>1. INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY</B></P>
<P>1.1 In this Supplementary Proof I comment on the Proof of Evidence of Dr
Wallace (PE/GNP/5) dealing with model validation and the role of the RCF.</P>
<P> <B>Principal Points of Agreement</B></P>
<P>1.2 Dr Wallace appears to accept the need to carry out field measurements to
validate key hydrogeological models that underpin repository performance
assessments (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 6.2) and that this is in line with current
regulatory thinking (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 4.2).</P>
<P><B>Principal Points of Disagreement</B></P>
<P>1.3 The assertions made in Dr Wallace's Proof of Evidence which form the
principal points of disagreement that I address in this Supplementary Proof are
as follows:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>For the planned validation of groundwater flow models in Phase 1 of the RCF
to build sufficient confidence to permit a decision of whether to propose
repository development the current range of predictions must be narrowed by
means of the ruling out or rejection of alternative models (PE/GNP/5, paragraphs
3.2, 3.3 and 6.9;);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>Nirex has accepted the need for adoption of a validation procedure, as
proposed in the submission by Dr Mackay for Greenpeace (PE/GNP/2). and that the
use of performance measures in this procedure in a new feature of the Nirex
research programme (PE/GNP/5, paragraphs 5.1 and 5.2);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>Regional-scale models of groundwater flow will not be validated in a
rigorous manner (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 5.14);</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv.</TD>
<TD>RCF shaft sinking would represent the first validation cycle of the
fracture network models to follow rigorously the procedures outlined in my first
Supplementary Proof (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>, <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.10">paragraph
10.10</A>) (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 5.8); and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v.</TD>
<TD>The safe performance of a repository at Sellafield is heavily dependent
upon a low flux of groundwater through the repository and the RCF is unlikely to
build sufficient confidence that the flux will not exceed an acceptable value
(PE/GNP/5, paragraph 6.16).</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>1.4 I deal with these points in Sections 3 to 7 respectively of this
Supplementary Proof but in summary my response is as follows:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>The models that will be subject to validation testing in Phase 1 of the
proposed RCF programme will have been produced as a result of an interative
process of confidence building.  The RCF will afford further building of
confidence because it will allow new and different testing of models, in
particular with respect to:
<UL>
<LI> three-dimensional testing at greater lengthscales; and
</LI>
<LI> simultaneous testing and observations on specific features and on the
larger scale
</LI></UL>Dr Wallace's assertion appears to be based upon a misconception that
validation is a process of ruling out models that are inconsistent with data. 
Nirex has a different objective for validation, with validation being a process
of building confidence in the fitness for purpose of models achieved through the
refinement and development of the models.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>Nirex has followed a validation strategy, including the use of performance
measures, for a number of years in its research programme.  Given the accord
with Dr Mackays views that is now recognised by Dr Wallace, the relevant
sections of Dr Mackays submission are viewed as supportive of the Nirex
approach.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>The regional scale models of groundwater flow have been subject to a
continual process of validation that will be continued through further
investigations from the surface and through Phase 1 of the RCF.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv.</TD>
<TD>The fracture network models used by Nirex have been subject to an
appropriate level of validation to build sufficient confidence in their
application at this stage of the project.  Dr Wallace seeks to impose a
prescriptive approach to model validation that is not appropriate at this stage
and would tend to work against the building of improved models for future
applications.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v.</TD>
<TD>A relatively low flux of groundwater through a repository is a necessary
feature for long-term radiological safety in all repository concepts of which I
am aware.  Dr Wallaces assertions on this point appear to be based upon
misunderstandings concerning the extent to which a range of fluxes, having
different probabilities, is acceptable.  This failure to take account of the
probabilities of different values of flux leads Dr Wallace to make incorrect
statements concerning requirements to narrow the possible range of fluxes
through Phase 1 of the RCF programme.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><A NAME="Planned"></A><B>2. PLANNED VALIDATION IN PHASE 1 OF THE RCF</B></P>
<P>2.1 The basis of Dr Wallaces Proof of Evidence (PE/GNP/5) appears to be
provided by her definition of validation as a process for ruling out or
rejecting models (paragraphs 3.2 and 4.2).  This is not an appropriate
definition of validation.  As I note in my first Supplementary Proof (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.8">paragraphs 10.8</A> and 10.9) the International
Atomic Energy Agency defines validation as [COR/519] (page 11):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I> &quot;... a process carried out by comparison of model predictions with
independent field objections and experimental measurements, a model cannot be
considered validated until sufficient testing has been performed to ensure an
acceptable level of predictive accuracy.  (Note that the acceptable level of
accuracy is judgmental and will vary depending on the specific problem or
question to be addressed by the model).&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This is consistent with my statement that, in radioactive waste safety
assessment, validation is the term applied to the iterative process of building
confidence in the fitness for purpose of models used in developing a performance
assessment for a repository and in the predictions they make.</P>
<P>2.2 This view of validation as positive, confidence-building process (rather
than a negative process of elimination) has been expressed by Nirex specifically
in the context of groundwater flow modelling, for example in <I>Nirex Science
Report S/94/004, Post-closure Performance Assessment.  Modelling of Groundwater
Flow and Radionuclide Transport, January 1995</I> (page 2) [COR/510]:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>The conceptual model evolves through a series of validation cycles
... Within each cycle the conceptual model is developed, and testable
predictions are constructed.  These predictions are then tested in the course of
the site investigation programme in order to build confidence in the model and
to gather data to refine the model&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This statement aligns with the thinking of the regulators subsequently
expressed in <I>HMIP Draft Guidance on Requirements for Authorisation</I>
(paragraph 8.19) [HMIP/1/1]:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Validation is an iterative and progressive process of confidence
building.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.3 The <I>HMIP Draft Guidance</I> (paragraph 8.19) [HMP/1/1] goes on to
list amongst measures that should be included in a validation programme:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Systematic approaches to model building and consideration of
alternative models.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>In <A HREF="nrx15.htm/#Para6.9">paragraphs 6.9</A> to 6.13 of my Proof of
Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>) I describe the requirement to develop the models
used in <I>Nirex 95</I> [COR/522] and to consider alternatives, by building in
the data not yet incorporated.  Also the role of the RCF in achieving this is
discussed.  Most importantly in the context of Dr Wallaces Proof of Evidence, I
point to the treatment of uncertainties in values of parameters (paragraph 6.9)
and the role that judgements have played in building models (paragraph 6.10),
stating:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Some of these alternative models, albeit improbable, could lead to
the prediction of high values for the flow of groundwater into the repository or
low values for its dilution in the overlying rocks that would not be consistent
with meeting regulatory requirements for post-closure safety of a repository.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.4 It may not ever be possible to rule out or reject such alternative
models in an absolute sense as sought by Dr Wallace.  A good outcome of
validation testing of alternative models using information from the RCF would be
increased confidence that the current judgements are correct and that
alternative models, not consistent with meeting regulatory requirements, are of
acceptably low probability.  This approach is consistent with the <I>HMIP Draft
Guidance</I> (paragraphs 8.15 and 8.16) [HMP 1 1].</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>The treatment of uncertainty is central to the establishment of
the post-closure safety case for a radioactive waste disposal system. 
Uncertainties are not of themselves obstacles to establishing the safety case,
but rather matters requiring consideration in a variety of ways and assimilation
into the structure of the case as appropriate.  They arise inter alia from
natural variability, the practical limits on sampling relevant processes and
data, alternative interpretations of data, ...   Some uncertainties may be
quantified and incorporated into numerical assessments of probability or risk...&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.5 The interative process of validation progressively builds confidence in
a modelling approach and enables comparison of alternative models.  In order to
see how well an approach is doing, it is necessary to have a set of measures
against which results can compared.  These are called performance measures, and
I describe those used for the RCF3 Pump Test models in my first Supplementary
Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>, <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#ParaA.2.4">paragraph
A.2.4</A>).  Some models and modelling approaches will give better results when
compared to these measures than will others.  Some will perform better against
one measure than they do against another.  With successive validation cycles,
one or more preferred approaches models will emerge.  Consequently, selection of
a model may not be a straightforward matter of accepting one and rejecting the
rest and, in a final regulatory submission, presentation of the results of
different approaches is likely to be required, together with a commentary on the
confidence attached to each.  At some stage in the validation cycle it may be
reasonable to specify quantitative acceptance criteria allowing the simple
acceptance or rejection of a model.  Given that a degree of expert opinion will
be needed to assess all the results and that these results will inevitably
contain uncertainties, it is not clear that adopting the black and white
approach (as advocated by Dr Wallace) would actually add to clarity.  Rather, it
may hide potentially useful information from decision makers at an early stage
of work.</P>
<P>2.6 At the present stage of the project, before the data which an RCF would
afford become available, it has not been considered useful to reject potentially
useful models as I note in <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#ParaA.2.6">paragraph A.2.6</A>
of my first Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>).  As I note
in paragraph A.3.4 of my first Supplementary Proof of Evidence (bullet iv), it
is Nirexs intention to establish acceptance criteria for aspects of the shaft
drawdown test, but the way in which they may be applied is still being
considered and this issue is unlikely to form part of the future discussions
with the regulatory authorities described by Mr Folger in his Proof of Evidence
(<B>PE/NRX/12</B>, <A HREF="../nrx12/nrx12.htm/#Para9.6">paragraphs 9.6</A> to
9.8).  As indicated in <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.18">paragraph 10.18</A> of
my first Supplementary Proof of Evidence, there may be additional cycles of
validation beyond the immediate shaft drawdown experiment which will start in
Phase 1 of the RCF.  Over the next 12-24 months, once the RCF3 Pump Test data
have been fully analysed, decisions can be made as to how many opportunities for
iterative testing can or need to be created within the shaft drawdown validation
cycle and within Phase 1 of the RCF.  Such iterative testing may need to extend
into Phases 2 and 3 and, as noted by Dr Holmes in his Supplementary Proof of
Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/13/S1</B>, <A HREF="../nrx13/nrx13s1.htm/#PageA1.3">page
A.1.3</A>):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Nevertheless, as supporting documentation for the RCF planning
application makes clear, if after the first phase of the RCF programme the
evaluation of the Sellafield site is not sufficiently confident to underpin a
decision for or against, then more time would be taken to carry out further
studies&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.7 Thus, Nirex will continue to validate its modelling approach until
sufficient confidence is gained.  As Dr Wallace points out, this work has to be
carried out to the eventual satisfaction of the regulator (PE/GNP/5, paragraph
4.2).  The RCF programme allows ample scope to build confidence by responding
flexibility to the outcome of each cycle of model testing.</P>
<P>2.8 Dr Wallace appears to consider it important that (PE/GNP/5, paragraph
5.11):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>the regional models Nirex need to validate in order to obtain
authorisation of a future repository do not appear to exist yet, although Nirex
expect them to require no further development by the end of Phase 1.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The final clause is an oversimplification of the Nirex position in that
further development is bound to occur, but the intention is that Phase 1 of the
RCF Programme will provide sufficient confidence that regional-scale models are
complete in respect of features and processes of importance to repository
post-closure safety.  The earlier part of the statement reflects a
mis-conception concerning the nature of the validation process.  As explained in
paragraphs 3.1 to 3.7, the regional-scale models that will be available for
Phase 1 of the RCF programme are intended to be the products of earlier cycles
of refinement and development.</P>
<P>2.9 By the very process of evolving conceptual models through a series of
validation cycles, as outlined in my first Supplementary Proof (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.8">paragraphs 10.8</A> to 10.20) the models are
bound to change in time.  It would be very unlikely that the models developed in
1994, for application in <I>Nirex 95</I> [COR/522], would not be subject to
refinement or development of alternatives prior to initiation of one or more
validation cycles involving the RCF more than three years later.  The regional
hydrogeological models now available have been developed through several stages
that can be traced back to <I>Nirex Report 268</I> [COR/521] published in
September 1992.  As noted by Dr Chaplow in his Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/14</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx14/nrx14.htm/#Para6.75">paragraph 6.75</A>), a number of key
features have been supported by successive further acquisitions of data and
there is good confidence that a sufficiently firm understanding of the site will
be achieved by refinements to current models, rather than requiring substantial
new developments.</P>
<P>2.10 The important role in confidence building of information from Phase 1
of the RCF is summarised in my first Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.23">paragraphs 10.23</A> to 10.25).  In particular
I note:</P>
<UL>
<LI> the benefits of simultaneous and complementary validation of a variety of
conceptual models relevant to developing the necessary understanding of the
behaviour of the site;
</LI>
<LI> the availability of information to achieve these objectives, as outlined
by Dr Mellor in his Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/16</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx16/nrx16.htm/#Para4.3">paragraphs 4.3</A> to 4.14); and
</LI>
<LI> the further confidence that will be developed from information that is not
obtainable from observations from the surface (including the results of
three-dimensional testing at greater lengthscales, and of simultaneous testing
and observations on specific features and on the larger scale)
</LI></UL>
<P>2.11 Nothing in Dr Wallaces Proof of Evidence thus deflects me from the view
expressed by Dr Holmes in his Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/13</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx13/nrx13.htm/#Para6.26">paragraph 6.26</A>) that the planned
programme of validation in Phase 1 of the RCF could put Nirex in a position to
take a decision on whether to propose repository development.</P>
<P><A NAME="Status"></A><B>3. STATUS OF NIREX VALIDATION PROCEDURE</B></P>
<P>3.1 Dr Wallace (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 5.1) seeks to establish the view that
Nirex has accepted the need for adoption of a validation procedure, as proposed
in the submission by Dr Mackay for Greenpeace (PE/GNP/2), and that the use of
performance measures is a new feature of the Nirex research programme (PE/GNP/5,
paragraph 5.2).  The assertion that the use of performance measures is a new
development is not sustainable.  As I explain in the following paragraphs, there
is documentary evidence that Nirex has had a validation procedure which
incorporates the use of performance measures for a number of years.  This has
been applied in appropriate areas of the research programme as and when
sufficient data have become available.  In the context of validation of fracture
flow models, Nirex considered that there were sufficient hydrogeological data,
which could be combined with the experience gained in the development and
application of hydrogeological models at Sellafield, to apply the procedure in a
formalised manner to the RCF3 Pump Test.</P>
<P>3.2 The presentation of the application of validation cycles for models of
groundwater flow in the <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#APPENDIX:">Appendix</A> to my
first Supplementary Proof (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>) is a summary of a procedure
that has been developed over an extended period.  In particular the reference to
the role of John Lloyd, Professor of Hydrogeology at the University of
Birmingham, in holding results of forward predictions for the RCF3 Pump Test for
comparison with the relevant performance measures (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#ParaA.2.9">paragraph A.2.9</A>) is evidence that Nirex
has worked to this procedure.</P>
<P>3.3 The validation procedure outlined in my first Supplementary Proof of
Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/21</B>, <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.10">paragraph
10.10</A>) represents the same procedure, made more explicit for certain steps,
as first published in detail by Nirex in March 1991 in <I>Nirex Report
NSS/R259.  Validation of Transport Models for use in the Repository Performance
Assessments.  A View Illustrated for INTRAVAL Test Case 1b [NRX/15/39].  </I>In
particular, a formal framework for validation is set out in <I>Nirex Report
NSS/R259</I> (Section 3, pages 4 to 8) which involves the use of measures, then
called goodness-of-fit measures, to assess quantitatively the agreement between
model predictions and experimental data.  The assertions by Dr Wallace on the
timing of the introduction of a validation procedure involving performance
measures by Nirex are not justified.</P>
<P>3.4 Since Dr Wallace confirms that the procedure outlined in my first
Supplementary Proof of Evidence is in accord with the views of Dr Mackay, for
Greenpeace, on validation (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 5.1), the relevant sections of Dr
Mackays submission are viewed as supportive of the long established Nirex
approach.</P>
<P><A NAME="RegionalValidation"></A><B>4. VALIDATION OF REGIONAL-SCALE MODELS
OF GROUNDWATER FLOW</B></P>
<P>4.1 Dr Wallace asserts (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 5.9):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Nirex have not validated their regional models of groundwater flow
to date, nor is validation of such models discussed by Dr Hooper in his
Supplementary Proof of Evidence&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This statement is not correct.  In my Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para5.14">paragraph 5.14</A> and 5.15) I state the
strategy for validation of regional-scale models, specifically in response to
the submission by Dr Mackay.</P>
<P>4.2 Dr Wallace supports her assertion in paragraph 5.10 of her Proof of
Evidence (PE/GNP/5) by pointing to the absence of published performance measures
and blind predictions for the comparisons of calculated and measured groundwater
heads and densities made in<I> Nirex 95</I> [COR/522].  In adopting this
position, Dr Wallace seeks to apply a set of rules without recognising either
the practicalities of testing regional-scale models or the face that there will
necessarily be differences between the approaches to validation of models on
different scales.  Nirexs approaches to building confidence in the
regional-scale groundwater flow model and in particular the hydraulic model of
the BVG in the PRZ are different, reflecting the different character of both the
data and the uncertainties of importance to performance assessment which
underlie each system.  I explain this in the following paragraphs 4.3 to 4.7.</P>
<P>4.3 In the regional sense, there is effectively only one overall description
of the physics of the regional flow system.  This describes large-scale
groundwater flow in a topographically driven, variable density, multiple rock
formation system.  The broad understanding of geological structure, the
processes that drive flow and the general patterns of flow have not changed
since the site was first being studied.  This understanding has been reflected
in the use of a series of models with similar characteristics.  Site
characterisation has provided the data to quantify  and refine these models,
although the gross patterns of water movement are the same as those estimated at
the time of the CASCADE Phase 2 exercise reported in <I>PERA </I>[COR/501]. 
The main uncertainties in the regional context are the local effects of specific
features on flow at the site and the most appropriate treatment of some model
boundaries.  Thus, in the regional sense the validation of alternative models
actually involved the evaluation of alternative assumptions about the nature of
specific features and now the testing of fundamentally different approaches to
modelling regional flow.</P>
<P>4.4 In studying the BVG on a more detailed PRZ-scale, more specific features
of the fracture network system and its role in conducting flow on a small scale
need to be assessed.  As a result, there are distinctly different ways of
describing flow through the fracture system which need to be explored and
compared.  For example, as noted in my first Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#ParaA.2.2">paragraph A2.2</A>), the RCF3 Pump Test is
evaluating six alternative models of bulk water flow through the mass of the
BVG.</P>
<P>4.5 The fact that the approaches to regional-scale modelling of the whole
flow system and PRZ-scale modelling of the BVG are different reflects the
different type of information required by the post-closure performance
assessments.  At the PRZ-scale in the BVG a more detailed understanding and
evaluation is required in order to evaluate the behaviour of the engineered
barrier system and the source term spreading time.  A less detailed
understanding of groundwater flow through the rest of the regional system is
acceptable for evaluating larger-scale geosphere transport.</P>
<P>4.6 As a result, the nature of the validation process at regional- and
PRZ-scale is different.  At PRZ-scale in the BVG, the formal methodology of
testing alternative models described in the Appendix to my first Supplementary
Proof of Evidence is being followed.  At the regional-scale this approach is not
appropriate.  In part, this is because it is not practical, or desirable, to
perform simple but rigorous predict, perturb and monitor tests (such as the RCF3
pump test) which involve disturbing the whole domain of interest, at a regional
scale.  The only sensible approach is to use alternative possible explanations
of the nature of features and processes to explain the pre-observed hydraulic
and hydrochemical properties of the site.  This is why reliance is placed on
interpreting different observations of the natural system, as I note from the
quotation in <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para5.14">paragraph 5.14</A> of my first
Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>), and why it is important
to observe several different variables.  Confidence building in this context
comes from the effort to produce an overall consistent picture that accounts for
the different observations.</P>
<P>4.7 As noted in Dr Chaplows Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/14/S1</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx14/nrx14s1.htm/#Para10.37">paragraph 10.37</A>), an important
way of doing this is to be able to explain the palaeohydrogeology (past
groundwater flow) of the system, inferred from geochemical indicators, using
existing models of control on regional flow and how boundary conditions and rock
properties may have evolved.  This approach is thus an interpretative method of
confidence building necessarily quite different in nature to the blind
prediction validation approach to be used in the RCF.</P>
<P>4.8 Wherever possible, comparisons of outputs from the mathematical models
with independent field observations have been used to refine the regional scale
models of groundwater flow.  The comparisons of calculated and observed
groundwater heads and densities published in <I>Nirex 95 </I>(Volume 3, Section
7) [COR/522] are a good example, since these parameters are routinely calculated
as outputs of the models and are not used as data inputs in the formulation of
the relevant models.  However, because an increasing volume of data on hydraulic
heads, groundwater densities, groundwater ages, recharge and discharge locations
has been published, calculations of these parameters as outputs from models
cannot be viewed as blind predictions in these circumstances.  Nevertheless, the
comparisons with newly acquired field data provide a powerful validation test of
the models.</P>
<P>4.9 Quantitative performance measures have been applied to comparisons of
calculated and observed hydraulic heads and densities but this aspect of Nirexs
work on regional-scale groundwater flow modelling has not been published to
date.  In this work, it has been found important to balance a proper reflection
of the relevant uncertainties in comparing the outputs of a regional-scale model
with effectively point measurements, made on the scale of individual borehole
intervals, against allowing very large discrepancies that would devalue the
exercise.  So far it has been found more valuable to make judgements on the
adequacy with which key observations, such as the increase in hydraulic heads
with increasing depth, are reflected in the models and to variation in hydraulic
heads and densities across the region and with depth.  Their investigation in
modelling studies will help to assess their potential significance and thus
build confidence in the resulting models, thereby satisfying the prime objective
of a validation exercise.</P>
<P>4.13 Dr Wallace appears to suggest that the excavation of the RCF and the
drilling of further, planned boreholes will not contribute significantly to the
validation of the regional groundwater flow models (PE/GNP/5, paragraphs 5.13
and 5.14).  The contribution of the RCF in this context was explained by Dr
Chaplow in his supplementary Proof (<B>PE/NRX/14/S1</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx14/nrx14s1.htm/#Para8.85">paragraphs 8.85</A> to 8.88).  Dr
Wallace appears to accept one of the objectives that Dr Chaplow listed, namely
that of building confidence in fracture network models that are used to provide
values of regional-scale effective hydraulic conductives (PE/GNP/5, paragraph
6.4).  The further boreholes that are planned are similarly important to the
validation of regional groundwater flow models.  According to the current Nirex
scientific programme, this will involve the models that will be developed during
1996 and it is considered unlikely that, after that stage in the exercise,
further testing will be required that cannot be satisfied by excavation of the
RCF.</P>
<P><A NAME="FractureValidation"></A><B>5. VALIDATION OF FRACTURE NETWORK
MODELS</B></P>
<P>5.1 With respect to fracture network modelling, Dr Wallace appears to find
it significant that, as stated in my First Supplementary Proof of Evidence, the
Borehole RCF 3 Pump Test did not develop quantitative criteria against which a
model could be accepted or rejected (PE/GNP/5 paragraph 5.6).  This approach
reflected the objective of the Test and should not be construed as a deficiency.
 A major purpose of the RCF 3 Pump Test was to discriminate between alternative
conceptual models and to refine and develop one or more to be carried forward
for use in future safety assessments (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#ParaA.3.1">paragraph A3.1</A>).  The use of performance
measures reflected that purpose.</P>
<P>5.2 A model that appears not to perform very well in the RCF 3 Pump Test
validation cycle is one where the groundwater flow through the volume of BVG
rock considered is dominated by a single, large-scale, transmissive fracture
system.  A useful outcome of the validation cycle might well be a refinement of
this model to enable its further testing in the RCF shaft drawdown experiments,
rather than its outright rejection at this stage.</P>
<P>5.3 Dr Wallace acknowledges that performance measures were specified for the
RCF3 Pump Test (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 5.6) but interprets the wording of my first
Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#ParaA.2.6">paragraph A.2.6</A>) to mean that these were
not the quantitative performance measures that would be required to accept or
reject models.  This is not the case.  The performance measures, the majority of
which were quantitative, would be suitable for such a purpose.  The wording of
my first Supplementary Proof was intended to explain that the exercise that was
not carried out, but could have been if required, was a formal process of
statistical testing whether the model outputs could be considered to represent
the field data at some pre-determined confidence level.</P>
<P>5.4 Dr Wallace also claims (PE GNP 5, paragraph 5.8) that the RCF shaft
drawdown exercise will be the first validation cycle to follow rigorously the
procedure outlined in my first Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.10">paragraph 10.10</A>).  This claim is based on
the use of revised Class B predictions as well as Class A, blind predictions in
the RCF3 Pump Test.  There is no justification for this claim.  The use of
`Class B predictions  is entirely consistent with the Nirex validation strategy
as I note in my First Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.12">paragraph 10.12</A>):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Predictions may be made prior to, during or after independent data
are gathered.  If made during or after data acquisition then special care must
be taken to ensure that independence is not compromised.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Since the Class B predictions were made when the test was in progress but
before there was any knowledge of the data that would result, the independence
of the predictions was not compromised.</P>
<P>5.5 In <A HREF="nrx15s1.htm/#Para10.12">paragraph 10.12</A> of my First
Supplementary Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15/S1</B>) I state:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>The most powerful technique in terms of building confidence is
that of making forward predictions prior to data gathering.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>In that sense the use of Class A predictions must be viewed as the most
rigorous for validation testing.  The need for Class B predictions in the RCF3
Pump Test recognised the fact that, for various practical reasons, the tests
were not run exactly as originally planned.  There would be little point in
trying to compare predictions made for one set of test conditions with test
results obtained in different conditions which would be the logical outcome if
the validation cycle had employed only the Class A predictions.  Such practical
considerations are a necessary aspect of integrated hydrogeological modelling
and testing, particularly on the large scale.</P>
<P>5.6 The purpose of the RCF3 Pump Test validation cycle is to facilitate the
building of the best possible models for use in a detailed safety assessment and
for validation testing in the RCF shaft drawdown experiment.  The success of the
validation cycle will be judged by the peer review process that has been
specified, but which Dr Wallace appears to be prejudging.  The relevant skills
of integrated modelling and testing have been exercised extensively and, in the
nature of the interactive process of validation, the models involved are likely
to be refined as a result.</P>
<P>5.7 The initial validation cycle involving the Borehole 2/4 crosshole
testing programme, to which Dr Wallace refers in her Proof of Evidence
(PE/GNP/5, paragraph 5.4), was viewed as successful in meeting the objectives
which Dr Wallace identifies in a quotation from the <I>European Commission
Workshop Paper</I> [NRX/15/16] and in particular in enabling the construction of
conceptual models for subsequent testing.  Nirex believes that this is a more
meaningful test of the outcomes of a validation process at that stage than
adherence to a prescriptive approach, which Dr Wallace appears to propose as
being necessary.</P>
<P><A NAME="Flux"></A><B>6. FLUX OF GROUNDWATER THROUGH THE REPOSITORY</B></P>
<P>6.1 Dr Wallace asserts that the range of fluxes of groundwater through the
repository allowed by the existence of alternative conceptual models of fracture
flow must be narrowed according to her interpretation of results in <I>Nirex 95</I>
[COR/522] for an application for authorisation to be made (PE/GNP/5, paragraph
6.9).  (I believe that Dr Wallace intends this to mean an application to develop
a repository rather than an authorisation to dispose of wastes since she relates
the statement to Phase 1 of the RCF).</P>
<P>6.2 In connection with this assertion, Dr Wallace makes other points that I
address in this Supplementary Proof of Evidence, namely:</P>
<UL>
<LI> the safety case appears to be heavily dependent on a low flux through the
repository and hence will not meet a requirement of HMIP (PE/GNP/5, paragraph
6.16, point (ii));
</LI>
<LI> the source term spreading times and geosphere spreading times presented in
Nirex 95 (Volume 3, Figure 8.8) [COR/522] may be linked (PE/GNP/5, paragraph
6.13); and
</LI>
<LI> the RCF is unlikely to deliver the required level of confidence to resolve
these difficulties (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 6.16, point (i)).
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Range of Fluxes</B></P>
<P>6.3 Dr Wallace had adopted Figure 8.8 from <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3)
[COR/522] as Figure 1 of her Proof of Evidence (PE/GNP/5).  This Figure shows
the dependence of risk on source term and geosphere spreading times.  The source
term spreading time is inversely proportional to the flux of groundwater through
the repository as shown in <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3, page 8.8, equations 8.15
and 8.16) [COR/522].  In a discussion of uncertainties in the groundwater flux
through the repository Dr Wallace makes use of three lines that she has
superimposed onto the Figure.</P>
<P>6.4 Dr Wallace states (PE/GNP/5, paragraph 6.9) that a way of showing how
conceptual models must be rejected is to investigate how short the lines shown
on Figure 1 of her Proof of Evidence (PE/GNP/5) would have to become to lie
within the risk target.  This suggests that Dr Wallace considers that the range
must be sufficiently small that all models that are considered in the risk
calculation must give results that lie to the low value side of the risk target,
if the final result is to be acceptable.</P>
<P>6.5 Figure 8.8 from<I> Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3) [COR/522] that Dr Wallace
has adapted as Figure 1 in her Proof of Evidence shows that the <I>Nirex 95</I>
base case hydrogeological model has a probability density function for the flux
of groundwater through the repository that extends well beyond the range shown
by her lines.  This is shown by the horizontal spread of individual realisations
from the probabilistic modelling, shown as small dots, corresponding to
different source term spreading times.  Nevertheless the risk calculated for
natural discharge of groundwater using this model is well below the target of 10<SUP>-6</SUP>.
 This is because the probabilities associated with different values of the flux
of groundwater need to be taken into account in calculating risk.  The
probabilities associated with significantly higher values of flux (than the
expectation value) are sufficiently low for the calculated risk to be
acceptable.  Thus, lines 1 and 2 on Dr Wallaces Figure 1 do not have the
significance that she claims.</P>
<P>6.6 The role of the RCF is therefore not as proposed by Dr Wallace, that is
to eliminate any models and associated parameter values which predict fluxes
corresponding to risks exceeding the target, but rather of testing that:</P>
<UL>
<LI> the expectation value of groundwater flux through the repository, derived
from one or more conceptual models, gives an acceptable risk;
</LI>
<LI> the distribution of fluxes considered in the probabilistic calculations is
a proper representation of the uncertainty in that quality; and
</LI>
<LI> the distribution of fluxes is acceptable in the context of regulatory
requirements taking account of the probabilities of their occurrence.
</LI></UL>
<P>As I note in paragraph 3.4 of this Supplementary Proof, a good outcome of
validation testing of alternative models using information from the RCF would be
increased confidence that current judgements on these points are correct.</P>
<P>6.7 Dr Wallace focuses attention on the possibility of alternative
conceptual models which are equivalent to higher values of flux (PE/GNP/5,
paragraph 6.15).  Dr Wallace ignores the possibility that models equivalent to
lower values of flux are currently considered as equally probable, as noted in
my Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>, <A HREF="nrx15.htm/#Para5.51">paragraph
5.51</A>).  When this is borne in mind, it is obvious that on the basis of
current knowledge the information from the RCF must be considered as likely to
give a more favourable result as an unfavourable one.</P>
<P>6.8 The RCF has another potential role to play in providing information
which will allow a reduction in the calculated groundwater flux through the
repository.  The calculated flux is dependent upon the modelled properties of
the &quot;Type II features&quot; in the BVG.  The importance of these features
in current performance assessment models arises because the repository is
assumed to be located with no attempt to avoid or minimise the intersection of
vaults by the Type II features.  As noted in my Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="nrx15.htm/#Para6.2">paragraph 6.2</A>) an important aspect of the work
in the RCF is to explore the possibility that intersections of repository vaults
could be minimised or avoided, which would have the effect of reducing
significantly the flux of groundwater through the repository.</P>
<P><B>Possible HMIP Requirements</B></P>
<P>6.9 Dr Wallace refers to the <I>HMIP Draft Guidance</I> (paragraph 7.3,
page 26) [HMP/1/1] at paragraph 4.5 of her Proof of Evidence, and asserts at
point (ii) of paragraph 6.16 of her Proof of Evidence:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Nirex's safety case appears to be heavily dependent on a low flux
through the repository, and will not be robust to an adverse interpretation of
this aspect of the evidence as required by HMIP&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>6.10 I believe that Dr Wallace is interpreting the <I>HMIP Draft Guidance</I>
incorrectly to mean that a the calculated risk for a repository system should be
sufficiently below the target of 10<SUP>-6</SUP> that it will remain below the
target even when an adverse interpretation is made of any given aspect of the
evidence in a safety case taken in isolation.  Dr Wallace does not quote the
heading that is given in paragraph 7.2 of the <I>HMIP Draft Guidance:</I></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Requirement R5 - Multiple Factor Safety Case.</I></P>
<P><I>The overall safety case for a specialised land disposal facility shall
not depend unduly on any single component of the case&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>In my experience, this should be interpreted as meaning the HMIP would
require sensitivity studies to be carried out to show that a large fraction of
the radiological protection to be afforded by the facility is not dependent upon
a single component of the safety case, and not that the calculated risk remains
below the target despite an adverse interpretation of a component of the safety
case.  The alternative interpretation by Dr Wallace would require over-design of
a system to cope with a potential adverse interpretation of each and every
component of the safety case, and ensure that the calculated risk remained below
target.  This would render meaningless the statements on optimisation given at
paragraph 6.17 of the <I>HMIP Draft Guidance.  </I>[HMP/1/1] which give
guidance on the requirement to consider additional measures to enhance
performance only when the calculated risk is above the target.</P>
<P><B>Source-term and Geosphere Spreading Times</B></P>
<P>6.11 Dr Wallace proposes that Nirex has (incorrectly) deduced an
independence of the source term spreading time and the geosphere spreading time
as an artefact of the use of the probabilistic safety assessment code MASCOT
(PE/GNP/5, paragraph 6.11).  Dr Wallace goes on to propose that a more
reasonable assumption may be that the two spreading times are linked (PE/GNP/5,
paragraph 6.13).  She is incorrect in this.  There are sound scientific reasons
why the two spreading times are not linked and this fact cannot be, and is not,
deduced from the use of MASCOT.</P>
<P>6.12 The flux of groundwater through the repository and the geosphere travel
time, which are the important components of the two spreading times in this
context, are derived from the same internally consistent suite of groundwater
flow models which represent a physical understanding of the system.  The
controls on the flux and the geosphere travel time calculated in <I>Nirex 95</I>
[COR/522] are well understood and are different.</P>
<P>6.13 As discussed in <I>Nirex 95</I> [Volume 3, Sub-section 7.9, pages 7.9
and 7.10) [COR/522], the main controls on flux through the repository are:</P>
<UL>
<LI> the horizontal gradient of the freshwater head in the BVG at repository 
depth; and
</LI>
<LI> the horizontal component of the effective permeability of the deep BVG.
</LI></UL>
<P>Except for the case of release from the small 'downstream' section of a
vault, the travel time in the BVG makes only a small contribution to the overall
geosphere travel time: inspection of <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3, Table 2.3, page
2.23) [COR/522] shows that the geosphere spreading time for water leaving a
repository vault will be dominated by the time spent in the sandstone formations
overlying the BVG.  The main controls on the time spent in the sandstone
formations are:</P>
<UL>
<LI> the vertical gradient of the environmental head and horizontal gradient of
the freshwater head in the sandstone formations; and
</LI>
<LI> the effective permeabilities and porosities of the relevant sandstone
formations.
</LI></UL>
<P>6.14 The controls on the time spent in the sandstone and hence on the
geosphere spreading time are independent of the controls on the flux through the
repository and hence on the source term spreading time.  Therefore the statement
is made in <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3, Sub-section 8.2.3, page 8.12) [COR/522]
referring to the figure reproduced as Figure 1 in Dr Wallaces Proof of Evidence:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>It can be seen that the system is robust to decreases in the
geosphere spreading time, provided that the source-term spreading time remains
similar to its base-case value.  Similarly, the system is robust to reduction of
duration of the source term if the spreading time in the geosphere remains
constant&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This is soundly based and does not ignore a correlation between the two
parameters of interest as proposed by Dr Wallace.  There is no justification for
the line 3 of Figure 1 in Dr Wallaces Proof of Evidence.</P>
<P><B>Contributions from the RCF</B></P>
<P>6.15 Dr Wallace proposes that the RCF will not provide data to address
uncertainties concerning the regional models of groundwater flow (PE/GNP/5
paragraph 6.6).  I disagree with the proposal in paragraph 4.13 above but would
emphasise two very important contributions that would be made to building
confidence in the calculation of the geosphere spreading time.</P>
<P>6.16 The first of these relates to the modelling of the Basal Deep St. Bees
Sandstone.  As shown in <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3, Table 7.6, page 7.17)
[COR/522] if this is modelled as a barrier to flow rather than being intersected
by large-scale sub-vertical fracture systems there is an increase in the overall
travel time in the sandstone units overlying the BVG.  The large scale drawdown
created by shaft excavation would provide a powerful test in assessing whether
or not there is an extensive barrier.  This objective of the RCF was identified
in my Proof of Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>, <A HREF="nrx15.htm/#Para6.31">paragraph
6.31</A> and 6.32).</P>
<P>6.17 The second contribution relates to the modelling of the Type II
features in the BVG.  In <I>Nirex 95</I> (Volume 3, Sub-section 2.4.1 and 2.14
and 2.15) [COR/522] groundwater flow from the repository vaults, except for the
small downstream section, was modelled as passing directly into Type II features
and along these into the overlying sedimentary formations.  This reflected the
representation of Type II features and in particular the lengths of these
features.  The RCF could show that the main channels for groundwater flow in the
BVG of the PRZ should be represented as shorter features that would not extend
from repository depth to the overlying formations and that a significantly
greater time would be taken for groundwater to travel through the single
fractures (Type I features) of the BVG.</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusion"></A><B>7. CONCLUSION</B></P>
<P>7.1 Nirex recognises that the uncertainties about the properties of the BVG
that will control the flux of groundwater through the repository are currently
too great to come to a decision whether to propose development of a repository. 
Dr Wallace proposes an unrealistic formalism for the use of future information
from the RCF to resolve these uncertainties.  Dr Wallace also seeks to establish
a narrow view of the information that the RCF will provide and of its
implications for calculations of risk.  I believe that her positions are not
sustainable and, when these are removed, that Dr Wallaces evidence does not deny
the contribution that is sought from the RCF, despite the conclusions 7.1 and
7.3 in her Proof of Evidence.</P>
