<P><B>DR DAVID WILLIAM MELLOR will say:</B></P>
<P><B>1. <A NAME="PERSONAL">PERSONAL DETAILS</A></B></P>
<P>1.1 I have been the RCF Science Manager in the Science Department of United
Kingdom Nirex Limited ('Nirex') since July 1993. I am responsible for developing
the programme of activities planned in the Rock Characterisation Facility
('RCF') to meet the needs of the site characterisation and research programmes.
I am a member of the Steering Committee of the Joint ANDRA, Nirex and SKB ZEDEX
Project at the Hard Rock Laboratory ('HRL') in &Auml;sp&ouml;, Sweden, which
comprises a series of underground experiments to measure excavation disturbance
effects on the rock mass.</P>
<P>1.2 I hold an upper second class honours degree in Geology from the
University of Manchester. Following postgraduate research I was awarded a Master
of Science degree in Geophysics from the University of Liverpool. I hold a
Doctor of Philosophy degree from the Earth Science department of the Open
University. This degree was sponsored and funded by British Petroleum ('BP') and
deals with the control of structure in a real porous medium over two phase fluid
movement. I am a Chartered Geologist and a Chartered Engineer. I am a Member of
the Institution of Mining Engineers and a Fellow of the Geological Society. I am
an external examiner for the HND, BSc and MSc courses in Environmental
Management at Farnborough College of Technology. I am the author of 18 technical
papers and a named inventor in 27 UK and international patents on measurement
technology used in geology, geophysics and fluid flow in porous media.</P>
<P>1.3 From 1975 until 1981 I was employed by the National Coal Board ('NCB')
as a Mine Geologist. In that capacity I was responsible for providing geological
and geophysical characterisation of underground tunnels, coal faces and access
drifts for mines in Yorkshire, Staffordshire, North Wales and Lancashire. This
included maintaining and operating the National Coal Board's portable
underground wireline geophysical logging unit for logging underground boreholes
in all UK coalfields. I was also responsible for inputs into deep drilling and
geophysical surveys for potential new mine sites in North Wales, Cheshire and
Staffordshire, and am a named inventor in NCB patents for inferring rock
properties from downhole geophysical logs. From 1981 until 1992 I was employed
by BP to manage a range of research and development projects in support of BP's
worldwide exploration and production operations in coal, oil, gas and minerals.
During this period I successively held the posts of Coal Geologist, Petroleum
Engineer, Head of Nuclear Geophysics, Head of Technical Services Group, Head of
Well Completions Group, Manager of Reservoir Appraisal Branch and Manager of
both Reservoir Appraisal and Reservoir Description Branches. From 1992 until
1993 I was a partner in an International Atomic Energy Agency funded consortium
which developed and built a prototype towed seabed spectrometer for monitoring
gamma radiation from nuclear powered vessels abandoned at sea by the Soviet
Union.<BR>
</P>
<P><B>2. <A NAME="SUMMARY">SUMMARY</A></B></P>
<P>2.1<B> </B>It is shown in the evidence of Drs Holmes, Chaplow and Hooper
that the RCF is needed to provide information to address uncertainties in three
main areas:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Groundwater flow and radionuclide transport;
</LI>
<LI>Natural and induced changes to the geological barrier; and
</LI>
<LI>Design and construction of the repository.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.2 My evidence explains how the programmes of scientific activities and the
underground works for the RCF have been designed to deliver the information
which is required. This explanation is provided in four steps in my evidence:</P>
<UL>
<LI>a description of how the activities planned for Phase 1 will deliver
information in the first category, which is required to address the
uncertainties in the three main areas to enable Nirex to make the decision on
whether to propose a repository at Sellafield;
</LI>
<LI>a description of how the activities planned for Phase 2 and Phase 3 will
deliver information in the second category, which is required to address the
uncertainties in the three main areas to inform a decision by the regulatory
authorities on whether to approve the start of disposal operations after
completion of repository construction and commissioning;
</LI>
<LI>the reasons for the design and approach to construction of the below ground
works of the RCF necessary to enable the scientific programme of activities; and
</LI>
<LI>the approach to planning and managing activities in the RCF.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Phase 1 Science Programme</B></P>
<P>2.3 The activities planned for Phase 1 to deliver the information required
to enable Nirex to make the decision on whether to propose a repository at
Sellafield are explained in terms of the three main areas of uncertainties in
the following paragraphs.</P>
<P>Groundwater Flow and Radionuclide Transport</P>
<P>2.4 Mapping will take place as an integral and continuous part of shaft and
gallery construction. This will provide observational information on the
following:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the structural characteristics of the St Bees Sandstone and Brockram
exposed in the shaft walls, including the main features controlling groundwater
flow;
</LI>
<LI>the lengths, orientations, apertures and ways in which fractures forming
flow channels in the BVG are connected together, and the variability of these
characteristics exposed in the shaft walls;
</LI>
<LI>continuity of mapped structural characteristics and flow channels of the St
Bees Sandstone, Brockram and BVG between the North Shaft and South Shaft and
existing boreholes drilled from the surface; and
</LI>
<LI>continuity of mapped structural characteristics and flow channels of the St
Bees Sandstone, Brockram and BVG observed in the shafts and the same features
intersected at a distance in underground boreholes drilled from insets in the
shafts and galleries.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.5 Hydraulic measurements will take place as an integral and continuous
part of shaft and gallery construction. These will provide observational
information on the following:</P>
<UL>
<LI>continuous measurement of the changes in groundwater pressure on the
groundwater pressure monitoring system;
</LI>
<LI>continuous monitoring of the inflows of groundwater to the shafts and
galleries;
</LI>
<LI>acquisition of groundwater samples from flow zones encountered in the
shafts and galleries;
</LI>
<LI>hydraulic testing of fractures intersected in underground boreholes drilled
out from insets in the shafts and galleries;
</LI>
<LI>acquisition of groundwater samples from fractures intersected in
underground boreholes drilled out from insets in the shafts and galleries; and
</LI>
<LI>monitoring during construction for groundwater ahead of the shaft by
testing the shaft sinker's probe holes.
</LI></UL>
<P>Natural and Induced Changes to the Geological Barrier</P>
<P>2.6 The mapping of the shafts during construction will provide access to
enable examination of fractures in the sandstones, Brockram and BVG for evidence
of their evolution and changes that may have occurred to them in the past as a
consequence of natural geological changes. This observational evidence will
include:</P>
<UL>
<LI>fracture intersection and cross-cutting (relative age) relationships; and
</LI>
<LI>sampling of fracture infill for mineralogical analysis and radiometric age
dating.
</LI></UL>
<P>The examination and sampling during mapping will concentrate largely on
groundwater flow channels. This is expected to allow the geological history of
flow patterns established from analysis of cores from surface-drilled boreholes
to be confirmed.</P>
<P>2.7 Construction of the shafts and galleries will create a zone of
disturbance around the excavations within which the mechanical and hydraulic
properties of the rock mass will change. These mechanical and hydraulic changes
within the excavation disturbance zone will be measured in the sandstones,
Brockram and BVG during shaft construction. A further experiment to measure the
mechanical and hydraulic changes within the excavation disturbance zone
surrounding a gallery in the BVG at the preferred repository horizon will be
carried out towards the end of Phase 1. These measurements are a practicable
means of validating that the site characteristics are such that excavation
disturbance will not significantly impair the containment performance of the
natural geological barrier in advance of the decision whether to propose the
development of a repository. Such measurements are based on practical experience
in other underground laboratories, including the ZEDEX Project in the &Auml;sp&ouml;
Hard Rock Laboratory in Sweden.</P>
<P>Design and Construction of the Repository</P>
<P>2.8 The validity of models that will be used to make extrapolations
throughout the BVG rocks in the PRZ of the distribution of networks of connected
fractures will be tested progressively during Phase 1. This will be achieved by
making a series of forward predictions of the expected geological and
hydrogeological characteristics of the BVG, and comparing these predictions with
observational data subsequently obtained from:</P>
<UL>
<LI>mapping the shafts;
</LI>
<LI>mapping the galleries;
</LI>
<LI>underground drilling from insets in the shafts and galleries;
</LI>
<LI>measurements of inflows to the excavations; and
</LI>
<LI>measurements of drawdown on the groundwater pressure monitoring system.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Phase 2 and Phase 3 Science Programme</B></P>
<P>2.9 Completion of the Phase 1 Science programme could put Nirex in a
position to take a decision on whether to propose repository development, and
this is the working assumption for the RCF programme. If, for some reason, the
decision to propose repository development is not taken at the end of Phase 1,
then the nature of the science programme for Phase 2, and possibly Phase 3,
would be reviewed and possibly revised. Under such circumstances the balance of
science activities might be expected to shift from a programme which currently
comprises predominately experimentation on processes within flow channels in the
BVG to one which further emphasises the testing of extrapolations of
distributions of networks of connected fractures within the BVG rocks of the
PRZ. </P>
<P>2.10 The activities currently planned for Phase 2 and Phase 3 are explained
in terms of the three main areas of uncertainties in the following paragraphs:</P>
<P>Groundwater Flow and Radionuclide Transport</P>
<P>2.11 It is expected that it may be necessary to fill out the information
supplied on groundwater flow and spreading in the geosphere in the safety
assessment prepared at the first key decision point. In order to achieve this,
it is envisaged that two large scale experiments may be required:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the SCD experiment which will characterise the flow of groundwater though
connected fractures in a region of BVG unaffected excavation disturbance and
which is approximately one million m<SUP>3</SUP> in volume; and
</LI>
<LI>the Ventilation Tunnel experiment which will measure the hydraulic
conductivity of the BVG including that of the excavation disturbed zone, over a
lengthscale of about 100 metres.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.12 Experiments within single fractures, and within zones of connected
fractures, will be carried out in Phase 2 and Phase 3 to measure rock matrix
diffusion in situ in the BVG. These measurements will be used to determine the
extent to which laboratory measurements of rock matrix diffusion are valid. Such
experiments will be comparable in outline to experiments conducted in
underground laboratories in other countries.</P>
<P>2.13 Groundwater samples from boreholes drilled from insets in the galleries
will be taken for analysis as part of the geochemical sampling programme
throughout Phase 2 and Phase 3. </P>
<P>2.14 Experiments to observe colloid transport within single fractures and
fracture zones will be undertaken for the subsequent development of simple,
empirically based models of colloid transport.</P>
<P>2.15 Experiments to study gas migration will be carried out in Phase 3 to
measure:</P>
<UL>
<LI>gas entry pressure into fractures; and
</LI>
<LI>two phase (i.e. gas and water) flow characteristics within fractures.
</LI></UL>
<P>Natural and Induced Changes to the Geological Barrier</P>
<P>2.16 Experiments to measure the effects of chemical disturbance to networks
of connected fractures arising from highly alkaline fluids will be carried out.
These experiments would be intended to build confidence in the trends of changes
to the rock properties already established in the laboratory.</P>
<P>2.17 Further work in measuring the mechanical and hydraulic changes within
the excavation disturbed zone will be carried out during Phase 2 and Phase 3.
This work will include:</P>
<UL>
<LI>measurement of the extent to which mechanical and hydraulic changes within
the zone of disturbance are sensitive to excavation direction in relation to the
maximum horizontal stress direction; and
</LI>
<LI>measurement of the mechanical and hydraulic changes within the zone of
disturbance when an excavation passes through a significant fault or fracture
zone.
</LI></UL>
<P>Design and Construction of the Repository</P>
<P>2.18 The validity of models that will be used to make extrapolations
throughout the BVG rocks in the PRZ of the distribution of networks of connected
fractures will continue to be tested during Phase 2 and Phase 3 by making
forward predictions of the expected geological and hydrogeological
characteristics of the BVG and comparing these with observational data
subsequently obtained from:</P>
<UL>
<LI>mapping the galleries;
</LI>
<LI>underground drilling from insets in the galleries;
</LI>
<LI>measurements of inflows to the excavations; and
</LI>
<LI>measurements of drawdown on the groundwater pressure monitoring system.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.19 The finalised location of the repository vaults in the rock mass would
be confirmed on the basis of underground drilling from the Phase 3 galleries,
possibly along the line of the vaults.</P>
<P>2.20 A series of experiments and demonstrations is planned to establish that
required properties of seal materials, such as fluidity, durability or
permeability (in set condition) may be achieved in situ for:</P>
<UL>
<LI>seals in shafts;
</LI>
<LI>seals in galleries parallel and perpendicular to the maximum horizontal
stress direction;
</LI>
<LI>seals in boreholes; and
</LI>
<LI>seals to fractures and the excavation disturbance zone.
</LI></UL>
<P>These experiments and demonstrations are comparable in outline to
experiments conducted in underground laboratories in other countries.</P>
<P><B>Design and Construction of the RCF</B></P>
<P>2.21 In order to obtain information on networks of connected fractures,
access to rocks at depth is required. Shaft access has been selected because
shafts are the most economic means of achieving access to rock at depth. In
order to provide a second and separate exit to the surface for safe working, two
shafts are needed for continuation of underground gallery construction and
scientific works beyond the shaft bottom area.</P>
<P>2.22 The method for shaft construction and gallery construction must be such
that it allows regular and routine access to the rock mass for scientific
measurements and observations which are needed. The only practical method of
achieving this is the drill and blast method. This method has also been selected
by other countries with underground research laboratories, including Sweden for
the access drift for the HRL at &Auml;sp&ouml; and Canada for the URL main
shaft.</P>
<P><B>Approach to Planning and Managing Activities in the RCF</B></P>
<P>2.23 There are a number of underground research laboratories in other
countries. Though they are not necessarily directly comparable to the RCF in
many respects, there are some lessons in general which have been learned which
are relevant to the planning and management of the RCF. One of the most
important is that it is essential to retain a degree of flexibility to adapt the
layout of the laboratory, the underground experiments, or both, to the
geological conditions as found underground. This has been incorporated into the
planning for, and management of, the RCF. The current layouts for the
underground excavations are therefore all indicative, rather than prescriptive,
at this stage.</P>
<P><B>3. <A NAME="SCOPE">SCOPE OF THE EVIDENCE</A></B></P>
<P>3.1 The purpose of my evidence is:</P>
<UL>
<LI>to describe the programme of activities planned for Phase 1 of the RCF to
provide information in the first category identified by Dr Hooper (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.5">para 6.5</A>) to enable Nirex to make a
decision on whether to propose a repository at Sellafield (Section 4);
</LI>
<LI>to describe the programme of activities planned for Phase 2 and Phase 3 of
the RCF to provide information in the second category identified by Dr Hooper (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.6">para 6.6</A>) to inform a decision by the
regulatory authorities on whether to approve the start of disposal operations
after completion of repository construction and commissioning (Section  5);
</LI>
<LI>to provide the reasons for the design and approach to construction of the
below ground works of the RCF to enable the scientific programme of activities
(Section 6); and
</LI>
<LI>to present the approach to planning and managing activities in the RCF
(Section 7).
</LI></UL>
<P>3.2 In Section 4, I describe the activities which generate information which
is needed to address the uncertainties. This information is generated
continuously throughout Phase 1, and it is expected that a decision to propose a
repository at Sellafield could be taken at the end of Phase 1.</P>
<P>3.3 Section 5 of my evidence presents the current plans for experimental
activities necessary to address the remaining uncertainties on the assumption
that the decision has been taken to propose a repository at Sellafield at the
end of Phase 1. This section of my evidence also explains that if the decision
to propose repository development is not taken at the end of Phase 1, then the
nature of the science programme for Phase 2 and possibly Phase 3 would be
reviewed and possibly revised, as indicated in Dr Hooper's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.4">para 6.4</A>)</P>
<P><B><A NAME="PHASE1">4. PHASE 1 SCIENCE PROGRAMME</A></B></P>
<P>4.1 The programme of activities planned for Phase 1 will be described under
the following headings:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>groundwater flow and radionuclide transport;
</LI>
<LI>natural and induced changes to the geological barrier; and
</LI>
<LI>design and construction of the repository.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Groundwater Flow and Radionuclide Transport</B></P>
<P>4.2 As identified in Dr Hooper's evidence, information is required from the
RCF to address two uncertainties within the main area of groundwater flow and
radionuclide transport:</P>
<UL>
<LI>calculation of groundwater flow into the repository; and
</LI>
<LI>spreading in the geosphere.
</LI></UL>
<P>The programme of activities to address these two uncertainties will be
explained under these sub-headings in the following paragraphs.</P>
<P><U>Calculation of Groundwater Flow into the Repository</U></P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.3"></A>4.3 The information which is required from Phase 1 of
the RCF includes the lengths, orientations, apertures and ways in which
fractures forming flow channels in the Borrowdale Volcanic Group ('BVG') are
connected together, and the variability of these characteristics. This
information will be generated from two groups of activities carried out during
Phase 1:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">i.
</TD>
<TD>mapping; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">ii.</TD>
<TD>hydraulic measurements.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>These two groups of measurements will be described under these sub-headings
in the following paragraphs.</P>
<P>i. Mapping</P>
<P>4.4 Observations and measurements will be made of geological conditions and
parameters at depth in the potential repository host rock. These will be
conducted within the underground shafts and galleries and boreholes drilled from
them into the surrounding rock mass, as stated in the <I>Rock Characterisation
Facility Environmental Statement, Nirex Report 600 </I>(&quot;<I>Environmental
Statement</I>&quot;) (para 1.54, page 12) [COR/101]. Most of these general
characterisation observations and measurements will be obtained as part of
mapping, carried out by teams of specialist contractors. Mapping of both shafts
will take place as a continuous and integral part of shaft construction. The
method of shaft mapping which will be used in the RCF shafts and galleries has
been developed in conjunction with Atomic Energy of Canada Limited ('AECL'),
based on their experience of mapping the walls of the rectangular shaft and the
circular shaft extension of their Underground Research Laboratory ('URL'). In
the RCF shafts, data collection will be by colour stereo photography of the
shaft walls and in situ mapping of the shaft walls using a photomosaic base, and
recording of geological, geotechnical and hydrogeological parameters on coded
field sheets. These parameters will be substantially the same as those already
in existence and used for core description and characterisation of the surface
based site characterisation programme described in Dr Chaplow's evidence. These
parameters will include the trace lengths, orientations, apertures and ways in
which fractures forming flow channels in the BVG are connected together, and the
variability of these characteristics exposed in the shaft walls. Mapping of the
shaft walls therefore extends established site characterisation methods and
experience and utilises experience and proven mapping techniques developed for
shafts and galleries in other, comparable national programmes of underground
characterisation.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.5"></A>4.5 It may be possible to infer continuity between
connected fractures mapped in the BVG in the South Shaft, and connected
fractures mapped in the North Shaft or flow zones observed in existing boreholes
drilled from the surface. Such continuity, if observed, or confirmed by drilling
short boreholes from the Shafts to intersect the connected fractures, would
provide observational data on a lengthscale of tens or hundreds of metres.</P>
<P>ii. Hydraulic Measurements</P>
<P>4.6 Observation and measurements of groundwater inflows via fractures to the
shaft will be made as a routine part of geological mapping. The three
dimensional nature of the connections between some of these fractures can be
observed and recorded where the shaft intersects and exposes them, as part of
mapping. However, we need to extend our knowledge and understanding of the
hydraulic characteristics of these connections in three dimensions beyond the
limits of the shaft. This will be achieved by piecing together a number of
complementary observations, described in the following paragraphs.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.7"></A>4.7 The most extensive set of hydraulic measurements
during Phase 1 will be that made by the groundwater pressure monitoring system
installed in the existing boreholes which have been drilled previously from the
surface. This monitoring system will be operated continuously throughout the
life of the RCF. The monitoring system will record the groundwater pressure in
fractures present in the existing boreholes. Some of these fractures may be
connected in networks to fractures which the shafts will intersect. Under these
circumstances, the reduction in groundwater pressure (termed drawdown) in the
fractures exposed in the shafts would be evident as a reduction in pressure in
some of the fractures in the existing boreholes. The groundwater pressure
responses to shaft sinking recorded on the monitoring system therefore provide
important information on the hydraulic characteristics of networks of connected
fractures.</P>
<P>4.8 Throughout the construction of the shafts, the volume of effluent water
pumped out of the shaft will be monitored. In order to make estimates of the
amount of effluent water which is groundwater (and not water used for
construction purposes) the volumes of water introduced into the shaft for
construction purposes will also be monitored. To differentiate between
groundwater and water which is introduced for construction purposes in the
effluent water, the introduced water will be marked with a chemical tracer.
Drilling fluids used in the site characterisation programme have been traced
with lithium chloride and with potassium iodide to differentiate between
groundwater and drilling fluid in water samples obtained from the boreholes. The
tracer used in the water which is introduced into the shafts for construction
purposes will use a different tracer to those used in the surface based drilling
programme. These steps are necessary precautions and may be helpful, following
analysis of groundwater samples from the RCF, in identifying sources of
contamination in groundwater samples and pathways taken by groundwater which has
entered the shafts.</P>
<P>4.9 As part of the suite of hydraulic measurements for the RCF there will be
a geochemical sampling programme, the main objective of which will be to provide
high quality groundwater samples from well-characterised locations, as stated in
the <I>Environmental Statement </I>(para 1.62, page 13) [COR/101]. Groundwater
samples will be obtained throughout Phase 1, though the numbers of samples and
frequency of sampling may vary with depth. Groundwater samples will be collected
from flow zones in the shaft and from underground boreholes drilled out from the
shaft.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.10"></A>4.10 As a routine part of construction operations,
the shaft sinker will drill probe holes down and below the shaft, ahead of
construction. These probe holes will be hydraulically tested in order to
identify sources of groundwater beneath the shaft which might constitute
potential inrush hazards to construction operations. Where a probe hole
intersects a network of connected fractures, the hydraulic testing by the shaft
sinker of the probe hole may also cause a tell-tale response on the groundwater
pressure monitoring system. This complementary combination of in situ (i.e. in
the shaft) probe hole hydraulic testing and tell-tale response detected outside
the shaft will help to build the picture of the network of connected fractures.
Depending on which parts of the groundwater pressure monitoring system responded
by tell tale perturbations, this complementary method of interrogating fractures
may give information on the connectivity of fracture systems on lengthscales
over may tens, or even hundreds, of metres.</P>
<P>4.11 The drilling of additional probe boreholes from the shaft to further
characterise flow channels in such areas of interest could extend the
lengthscale of the information obtainable on hydraulic properties of the
fracture system.</P>
<P>4.12 Where the shaft sinker identifies a zone of potential groundwater
inflow beneath the shaft bottom, he will make an operational decision whether or
not to restrict inflows by injecting grout into the zone before sinking the
shaft through the zone. In order to inject grout into an identified zone, the
shaft sinker will drill a number (around 20 or so) of short grout injection
boreholes to intersect the zone. This is illustrated schematically for the South
Shaft in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A>. Grout, coloured with
a dye, would then be forced into each of these grout injection boreholes and
thereby into the network of connected fractures. As the shaft is subsequently
sunk through the grouted section, mapping of the shaft walls will reveal those
connected fractures into which the dyed grout has penetrated. Mapping this
section in detail will provide information in three dimensions about the
connected, hydraulically conductive fractures, including trace lengths,
orientations, apertures and ways in which fractures forming flow channels in the
BVG are connected together as illustrated schematically in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure4.2">Figure 4.2</A>. The three dimensional nature
of these grout filled fractures can be further investigated by drilling cores
out of the shaft wall. This technique of injecting dyed grout and subsequently
mapping and coring grout filled fractures has been used successfully in the
Swedish Hard Rock Laboratory ('HRL') in &Auml;sp&ouml;. The construction
operations of probe hole testing and grouting, therefore, provide further
opportunities to obtain data which is complementary to that obtained from
mapping and drawdown monitoring which is required to quantify the lengths,
orientations, apertures and ways in which fractures forming flow channels in the
BVG are connected together and which cannot be obtained from surface boreholes
alone.</P>
<P>4.13 At any stage in shaft sinking Nirex may decide to suspend shaft sinking
operations to further investigate a particular feature of scientific interest,
such as flow channels. For example, should any particular probe hole give
unexpected or significant hydraulic responses on the groundwater pressure
monitoring system, then suspension of sinking operations would allow further
hydraulic testing and characterisation of the flow channel to be carried out. It
is difficult at this time to prescribe what these might be in any detail, but it
might, for example, be desirable to drill additional underground boreholes from
the shaft to intersect a network of connected fractures in order to characterise
it in more detail further away from the shaft. Alternatively, it may be
desirable under such circumstances to attempt a modified form of cross-hole
testing. Other reasons for temporary suspension of shaft sinking could include
the construction of an inset (short horizontal excavation) from the shaft into
the feature, or to one side of the feature for subsequent access into it by
underground boreholes. This flexibility to stop shaft sinking and concentrate
scientific efforts on features of interest is an important aspect of providing
the required information, and is consistent with the experience of other
national and international underground laboratories, as explained in more detail
in Section 7.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.14"></A>4.14 Further information complementary to that
obtained from geological mapping of the shaft walls, drawdown monitoring,
testing in probe holes and injection of dyed grout is planned to be obtained
from a period of underground diamond drilling termed Peripheral Drilling. This
comprises a programme of drilling of boreholes from the 650 metres bOD gallery
once shaft sinking has been completed. Peripheral Drilling will be carried out
for a period of nine months before the end of Phase 1 in order to further
characterise the lengths, orientations, apertures and ways in which fractures
forming flow channels in the BVG are connected together, and the variability of
these characteristics. These underground boreholes will be cored and
hydrogeologically tested. Geophysical logging and the installation of
instruments to monitor groundwater pressures and obtain groundwater samples will
be undertaken for each borehole. Peripheral Drilling will be used to explore and
characterise hydraulic properties of networks of connected fractures in regions
of the potential repository zone ('PRZ') not directly penetrated by the RCF
shafts. The use of underground diamond drilling and characterisation of
hydraulic properties of fractures is common to other national and international
programmes of site characterisation for deep disposal of radioactive wastes
which have an underground laboratory, and is an important way of testing the
validity of extrapolations throughout the BVG rocks in the PRZ of the
distributions of networks of connected fractures.</P>
<P><U>Spreading in the Geosphere</U></P>
<P>4.15 The information from the RCF on groundwater flow channels in the BVG
required in relation to calculations of groundwater flow through the repository
would also be required to address uncertainties concerning spreading in the
geosphere, for the reasons noted in Dr Hooper's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.30">para 6.30</A>).
</P>
<P>4.16 Information is also required from the St. Bees Sandstone. The
information which is required from the St. Bees Sandstone is the correlation of
the observed large scale geological structures encountered in the shaft with the
hydrogeological responses in monitoring boreholes in order to distinguish
between alternative conceptualisations of connected fracture systems. The
programme of activities planned for the St. Bees Sandstone sections of the shaft
is therefore essentially the same as that which has been described for the BVG
in paragraphs 4.3 to 4.13, including:</P>
<UL>
<LI>geological mapping during sinking;
</LI>
<LI>drawdown monitoring on the groundwater pressure monitoring system;
</LI>
<LI>probe hole testing; and
</LI>
<LI>injection of coloured grouts into networks of fractures in the sandstones
and subsequent mapping and photography of the excavation through the treated
zone.
</LI></UL>
<P>4.17 There are some differences, however, between the information which
would be obtained during sinking the shafts through the sandstones and that
which would be obtained during sinking through the BVG. These differences are
twofold:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the diameter of shaft is greater in the sandstones than the BVG; and
</LI>
<LI>the shaft sinker would have a higher density of probe holes in the
sandstones that the BVG.
</LI></UL>
<P>These two differences are explained in paragraphs 4.18 and 4.19.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.18"></A>4.18 A hydrostatic concrete lining will be
continuously formed during shaft sinking through the sandstones and Brockram.
The purpose of this lining is to reduce the inflows of water into the completed
shaft. The thickness of the concrete lining will be increased with increasing
depth in order to be able to withstand the groundwater pressure which also
increases with increasing depth. This means that the concrete lining is over a
metre thick towards the lower part of the St Bees Sandstone. Because the
internal finished diameter of the shaft is constant at 5 metres, the St Bees
Sandstone has to be excavated to a diameter of up to about 7.4 metres to
accommodate the thickness of the lining. This gives a much greater surface area
of exposure per metre length of shaft compared to an equivalent metre length of
borehole core (more than 70 times). There is therefore greater scope for
observing and recording structural features of the sandstones including the
trace lengths, orientations, apertures and ways in which fractures in the
sandstones are connected in three dimensions and relating these to inflow
characteristics than is possible from boreholes drilled from the surface.</P>
<P>4.19 Because the St Bees Sandstone typically has a higher hydraulic
conductivity than the BVG, the shaft sinker will proceed through them more
cautiously. The shaft sinker will be required to use a minimum of four probe
holes (one on each shaft quarterline) beneath the shaft in advance of
construction, to enable him to test for the presence of potential inflows. Each
probe hole in the sandstones is required to be a minimum of 40 metres in length
with an overlap of 10 metres with previously drilled probe holes. This probe
hole pattern would be continued through the sandstones and Brockram and into the
top of the BVG. There is, therefore, scope for characterising the main controls
on spreading in the geosphere in the sandstones by means of complementary
observations using the probe holes and the groundwater pressure monitoring
system, as described in paragraphs 4.3<B> </B>to 4.13.</P>
<P><B>Natural and Induced Changes to the Geological Barrier</B></P>
<P>4.20 The role of the RCF in respect of natural change is to provide access
to examine fractures in the sandstones, Brockram and BVG for evidence of their
evolution and changes that may have occurred to them in the past as a
consequence of natural geological changes. Dr Chaplow presents evidence (<B>PE/NRX/14</B><A
HREF="../nrx14/nrx14.htm#Para7.25">para 7.25</A>) that the system of flowing
fractures has remained stable for a long period of time. During shaft sinking,
direct observations of associations of groundwater flows, mineral formation and
geological structures at depth will be undertaken in order to test the extent to
which this view is valid. The observations will be carried out during shaft
sinking as an integral part of mapping, and will take the form of:</P>
<UL>
<LI>observations and photography of fracture intersection and cross-cutting<B></B>(relative
age) relationships; and
</LI>
<LI>sampling of fracture infill for mineralogical analysis and radiometric age
dating.
</LI></UL>
<P>The observations will concentrate largely on recording and sampling
fractures which are significant for groundwater flow. This is expected to allow
the geological history of flow patterns established to date from analysis of
cores to be confirmed. This paleohydrogeological record will then be compared
with the present day flow patterns to test whether significant changes have
occurred in the past and may therefore occur in the future.</P>
<P>Excavation Disturbance</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.21"></A>4.21 An extensive programme of activities to monitor
the excavation of the shafts and galleries is planned for the RCF, in order to
test the assumption that the hydraulic conductivity of the excavation
disturbance zone is not increased by more than a factor of a hundred over a
distance equivalent to twice the diameter of the excavation. This programme
comprises the acquisition of data planned to be carried out during temporary
suspensions of shaft sinking operations:</P>
<UL>
<LI>monitoring of the in situ mechanical deformation of the disturbance zone by
convergence measurements (measurement of the reduction in diameter of the shafts
as the disturbance zone forms) and extensometer measurements (measurements of
radial displacements of points in underground boreholes drilled out from the
shaft), at stations in the sandstones, Brockram and BVG. Convergence and
extensometer measurements of deformation are common to a number of underground
laboratories in other countries, including the Canadian URL and the Swedish HRL
at &Auml;sp&ouml;;
</LI>
<LI>measurement of stress by overcoring techniques in the sandstones, Brockram
and BVG. The stress measurements will be taken close to the convergence
measurements where this is practicable. Measurement of stress by this technique
is common to a number of underground laboratories in other countries, including
the Canadian URL and the Swedish HRL at &Auml;sp&ouml;. The measurement of
stress by overcoring, and back-analysis of stress from convergence and
extensometer data, will validate the &quot;big picture&quot; of stress
magnitudes and directions for the sandstones, Brockram and BVG already built up
from a variety of techniques carried out in boreholes drilled from the surface.
These techniques include hydrofracture, overcoring and borehole breakout, as
described in Dr Chaplow's evidence (<A HREF="../nrx14/nrx14a1.htm#TA13"><B>Table
A.13</B></A>, page A.35);
</LI>
<LI>regular measurements of the excavation profile (shape) using a technique
such as laser profiling. This will identify any tendency for the shaft
excavations to form non-circular deformation in response to structural fabric of
the rocks and/or contrasts in horizontal stress magnitude;
</LI>
<LI>measurement of the in situ development of the disturbance zone and the
consequent changes in mechanical behaviour and hydraulic conductivity of the
rock as the shaft passes through a previously instrumented section installed
from within the deeper of the two shafts. This will be achieved by means of &quot;before
and after&quot; mechanical and hydraulic testing in horizontal underground
boreholes drilled towards, and around, the &quot;target&quot; shaft location
from the deeper of the two shafts. This is a variation of the under-excavation
method used in the Canadian URL, and is similar to the basic methodology
developed for the ZEDEX (Zone of Excavation Disturbance EXperiment, referred to
in paragraph 4.23) Project in the HRL at &Auml;sp&ouml;; and
</LI>
<LI>monitoring the acoustic emission from detectors located in the surface
boreholes and in underground boreholes. The acoustic emission data is expected
to give an indication of the extent of the excavation disturbance by locating
the sources within the rock mass of micro-crack events. This should provide
information on the extent of the zone where joint movements occur, and has
proved useful in the Canadian URL and in the ZEDEX project in the HRL at &Auml;sp&ouml;.
</LI></UL>
<P>4.22 The monitoring outlined in the preceding paragraph is expected to give
estimates of the general mechanical nature of the disturbance zone around the
shafts. It should also provide general indications and upper bounds of the
changes in hydraulic conductivity which occur within the disturbance zone. By
their very nature, these estimates cannot be achieved using boreholes drilled
from the surface.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.23"></A>4.23 A more comprehensive experiment aimed at
further quantifying the hydraulic changes which occur within the disturbed zone,
is planned to be carried out in a gallery towards the end of Phase 1. This
experiment is termed &quot;EDZ experiment number one&quot; and the form of the
experiment is similar to that jointly designed and managed by Nirex, SKB and
ANDRA in the ZEDEX programme in &Auml;sp&ouml;, as illustrated in the drill and
blast test drill configuration in the <I>&Auml;sp&ouml; Hard Rock Laboratory.
Test Plan for ZEDEX - Zone of Excavation Disturbance Experiment </I>(&quot;<I>ZEDEX
Test Plan&quot;) </I>(Figure 4-2, page 6) [NRX/16/1]. The experiment consists of
drilling several underground boreholes into the rock mass through which a
gallery will be subsequently excavated. These boreholes will be designed to pass
close to the gallery surface. The core retrieved from the borehole will be
described and characterised, and the boreholes will be tested using
geotechnical, geophysical and hydrogeological methods similar to those used in
surface-drilled boreholes and described in Dr Chaplow's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/14</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx14/nrx14a1.htm#Appendix1">Appendix 1</A>, ), and similar to the
methods used in the ZEDEX project in the HRL in &Auml;sp&ouml;. The programme of
hydrogeological testing gives the &quot;before construction&quot; baseline
hydraulic characteristics with which the &quot;after construction&quot;
measurements may be subsequently compared. Prior to excavating the gallery
through the characterised rock mass, instruments will be located in some of the
boreholes to measure mechanical changes within the rock mass in response to
excavation of the gallery. Construction of the gallery would then be allowed to
proceed through the instrumented region of rock. After every drill and blast
round fired, borehole instruments and convergence arrays in the gallery will be
used to quantify the extent and magnitude of mechanical changes within the
disturbance zone. When the gallery has been constructed through the instrumented
section, the &quot;after construction&quot; measurements of hydraulic
characteristics may be made.</P>
<P>4.24 The suite of &quot;before construction&quot; and &quot;after
construction&quot; hydraulic measurements will enable estimates of the magnitude
of the hydraulic conductivity changes within the excavation disturbance zone to
be made for that particular location depth, rock type and stress field. The &quot;after
construction&quot; behaviour of the disturbance zone, including hydraulic
conductivity, will be monitored throughout the life of the RCF. The nature and
extent of the disturbance zone measured in the borehole instruments and
convergence arrays at that particular location are expected to allow inferences
concerning upper bounds of the magnitude of the hydraulic properties of the
excavation disturbance zone to be made. It should also be possible to
extrapolate the hydraulic behaviour of the excavation disturbance zone measured
in that experiment to the general form and extent of the mechanical nature of
excavation disturbance zone built up progressively during shaft sinking, and
described in paragraph 4.21.</P>
<P><B>Design and Construction of the Repository</B></P>
<P>4.25 Phase 1 of the RCF will enable the testing to be carried out of the
validity of models used to make extrapolations throughout the BVG rocks of the
PRZ of the distribution of networks of connected fractures. This testing will be
used to confirm provisional views on the repository design parameters, in
particular depth, location, layout and orientation. This will be achieved by
making forward predictions of the expected geological and hydrogeological
characteristics of the BVG, and comparing these predictions with observational
data subsequently obtained from:</P>
<UL>
<LI>mapping the shafts;
</LI>
<LI>mapping the galleries;
</LI>
<LI>underground drilling from insets in the shafts and galleries;
</LI>
<LI>measurements of inflows to the excavations; and
</LI>
<LI>measurements of drawdown on the groundwater pressure monitoring system.
</LI></UL>
<P>4.26 Testing of our ability to make extrapolations in this way will be
carried out during shaft sinking and will continue to the point where the
decision on repository depth, and consequently RCF gallery depth, is made.</P>
<P><A NAME="PHASE2"></A><B>5. <A NAME="PHASE">PHASE 2 AND PHASE 3 SCIENCE
PROGRAMME</A></B></P>
<P>5.1 Completion of the Phase 1 Scientific programme could put Nirex in a
position to take a decision on whether to propose repository development, and
this is the working assumption for the RCF programme. If, for some reason, the
decision to propose repository development is not taken at the end of Phase 1,
then the nature of the science programme for Phase 2, and possibly Phase 3,
would be reviewed and possibly revised. Under such circumstances the balance of
science activities might be expected to shift from one which currently comprises
predominately experimentation on processes within flow channels in the BVG to
one which further emphasises the testing of extrapolations of distributions of
networks of connected fractures within the BVG rocks of the PRZ.</P>
<P>5.2 Although there are limited opportunities to provide some information in
the second category during Phase 1, most work on the second category will begin
when the Phase 2 galleries have been completed. As shown in the working
programme for the RCF in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>, on
the current Nirex assumption of a start date for the RCF of about July 1996, as
stated in the <I>Description of the Rock Characterisation Facility </I>(&quot;<I>RCF
Description&quot;)</I> (para 3.3, page 4) [COR/111], this would mean that work
on the second category would start in the year 2000. The precise form of the
experiments that are eventually carried out will be determined by the nature of
the rock and associated features that are encountered and by the particular data
needs finalised nearer the time, as stated in the <I>Environmental Statement
</I>(para 1.51, page 12) [COR/101]<SUP>.</SUP></P>
<P>5.3 Details of the experiments required to provide the second category of
information will be firmed up, and periodically reviewed, during Phase 1,
founded on the four important operating principles set out in Dr Holmes'
evidence (<B>PE/NRX/13</B><A HREF="../nrx13/nrx13.htm#Para5.2">para 5.2</A> ).
Additionally, sources of knowledge and expertise which will be used in
developing the detail of these experiments will include:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Nirex participation in other national and international programmes (for
example the HRL at &Auml;sp&ouml; in Sweden and the URL in Canada);
</LI>
<LI>use of contractors with direct experience in designing and implementing
experiments and reviewing and interpreting results of experiments in underground
laboratories in national and international laboratories;
</LI>
<LI>published literature; and
</LI>
<LI>peer review.
</LI></UL>
<P>5.4 The current outline plans for activities and experiments fall under the
same three headings as those used in the first category of information
requirements:</P>
<UL>
<LI>groundwater flow and radionuclide transport;
</LI>
<LI>natural and induced changes to the geological barrier, and
</LI>
<LI>design and construction of the repository.
</LI></UL>
<P>The current outline plans for activities necessary to generate the second
category of information are described in the following paragraphs.</P>
<P><B>Groundwater Flow and Radionuclide Transport</B></P>
<P>5.5 As set out in Dr Hooper's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.18">para 6.18</A>), information is required
on three potentially important processes:</P>
<UL>
<LI>rock matrix diffusion;
</LI>
<LI>colloid transport; and
</LI>
<LI>gas migration
</LI></UL>
<P>Measurements in situ in the RCF form an important link to laboratory studies
already completed on transport processes within fractures, as stated in the <I>Environmental
Statement</I> (parac 1.60, page 13) [COR/101].</P>
<P>5.6 In addition to testing evaluations of processes having the potential to
affect the transport of radionuclides, the second category of information will
include that required to fill out the information supplied on groundwater flow
and on spreading and dilution in the geosphere in the safety assessment prepared
for the first decision point, as stated in Dr Hooper's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.18">para 6.18</A>). It is currently envisaged
that two large scale experiments may be required to fill out this information on
groundwater flow, and these are the SCD experiment and the Ventilation Tunnel
experiment.</P>
<P>Site Characterisation and Demonstration Experiment</P>
<P><A NAME="Para5.7"></A>5.7 The SCD experiment will characterise the flow of
groundwater through connected fractures in the BVG on a sufficiently large scale
to further increase confidence in extrapolations across the PRZ. The objective
of the experiment is to address the hydrogeological behaviour of connected
fractures in the BVG on a lengthscale of the order of around a hundred metres,
accessed from boreholes drilled from a dedicated gallery in Phase 2 in order to
develop increasingly detailed models of the flow through a region of previously
undisturbed BVG. The SCD experiment is broadly comparable in outline to the
approach used in the Stripa Project Site Characterisation and Validation
Programme described in the
<I>OECD-NEA International Stripa Project 1980-1992 Overview Volume I: Executive
Summary</I>. (&quot;<I>Stripa Project Overview&quot;)
</I>(para 4.4, page 37) [NRX/16/2] and that planned for the Canadian URL
Moderately Fractured Rock ('MFR') experiment, described in the <I>Program of
experiments for the operating phase of the Underground Research Laboratory</I> (&quot;<I>Experimental
Programme for the URL</I>&quot;)<I> </I>(para 3.2, page 7) [NRX/16/3]. The
current schematic layout for the SCD experiment is shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>.</P>
<P>5.8 The experiment will be located in a volume of rock selected during Phase
1, or the early part of Phase 2. The location will be such that it is unaffected
by the disturbance zone of nearby excavations, and relatively unaffected by the
drawdown of nearby excavations. For planning purposes, the dedicated SCD roadway
is currently assumed to be located off the gallery which connects the two
shafts. The experiment will be conducted within a volume of BVG rock
approximately 100 metres by 100 metres by 100 metres in size, with an
approximate volume of about 1,000,000 m<SUP>3</SUP>. The experiment will
include drilling, instrumenting and testing a set of boreholes drilled from the
Phase 2 galleries to establish the geometry and hydrogeological properties of
the connected fractures within that rock. The value of the experiment lies in
developing a detailed characterisation of the hydrogeological behaviour of a
selected part of a fracture network for comparison with detailed numerical
models of the system. Comparisons are likely to be progressive and iterative
over the life of the experiment. Such detailed observations at these depths are
not practicable from surface drilled boreholes.</P>
<P>Ventilation Tunnel Experiment</P>
<P><A NAME="Para5.9"></A>5.9 This experiment test will measure the hydraulic
conductivity of the BVG on a large scale and will involve construction of an
environmentally controlled gallery about 100 metres long, as stated in the <I>Environmental
Statement
</I>(para 1.59, page 13) [COR/101]. The gallery will have a hermetic seal at the
access point. Through this hermetic seal ducting would introduce dry air at a
known and controlled rate, temperature and pressure. The return air would be
passed through a de-humidifier unit to measure the moisture removed by the
circulating air stream. Any free liquid water would be collected in gullies and
drained back through the hermetic seal for measurement and sampling. By these
means a mass balance of water would be obtained which enables estimates of
hydraulic conductivity, including that of the excavation disturbance zone, of a
lengthscale of about 100 metres to be inferred. This experiment is likely to be
initiated during Phase 3, though it would be possible to bring it forward should
this become necessary. The experiment is broadly comparable to the Ventilation
Test carried out by NAGRA in the Grimsel Test Site in Switzerland, as described
in the<I> Nagra Bulletin Special Edition 1988</I> (pages 46 to 49) [NRX/16/4],
and is illustrated schematically in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.3">Figure 5.3</A>.
Such an experiment is not possible in boreholes drilled from the surface.</P>
<P>5.10 The experiment will be located in a volume of rock selected during
Phase 3, or possibly during Phase 2 if it were to be brought forward. For
planning purposes, the experiment is assumed to be located off the SSE gallery
in Phase 3.</P>
<P>Rock Matrix Diffusion</P>
<P>5.11 The RCF is required to give direct access to, and measurements in,
fractures identified on the basis of their groundwater flow properties, and to
make measurements in situ with relatively little disturbance of the rocks.</P>
<P>5.12 The water filled fractures of the BVG are variable, natural systems. In
order to undertake meaningful in situ measurements relevant to rock matrix
diffusion in them, therefore, it is important to characterise them before
experiments are initiated. This is planned to be done in two stages before the
particular process of interest is studied within the fracture system:</P>
<UL>
<LI>characterise the geometry of the fracture system; and subsequently
</LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI>characterise the hydraulic behaviour of the fracture system.
</LI></UL>
<P>5.13 This two stage characterisation is undertaken by drilling boreholes
into the fracture system from insets in the galleries. The geometry of the
fracture system may then be inferred using a number of complementary techniques
in these boreholes including mapping of the drill core, borehole televiewer
examination of the borehole fractures, and geophysical techniques such as
seismic tomography. Complete and accurate characterisation of the geometry of
the fracture system is not essential because these features can be more fully
determined by drilling out large diameter cores from, or excavating into, the
experimental site to better examine it once the experiment has been completed.
Undue damage to the fracture system to be examined can be avoided using
excavation techniques developed at the Canadian URL in which the rock mass is
excavated by drilling closely spaced holes and subsequently splitting the rock
mass with hydraulic wedges located in the drill holes.</P>
<P>5.14 Once the geometrical and hydraulic characterisation work has been
adequately achieved, the experimental work may begin.</P>
<P>5.15 The intention is to study rock matrix diffusion in more than one site
in the Phase 2 galleries. These sites are currently planned to be of two types:</P>
<UL>
<LI>single fracture experiments, in which an individual fracture would be
identified, characterised and used as the test bed to measure rock matrix
diffusion; and
</LI>
<LI>fracture zone experiments, in which connected networks of fractures would
be identified, characterised and used as the test bed to measure rock matrix
diffusion.
</LI></UL>
<P>In practice more than one potential single fracture site and potential
fracture zone sites may be evaluated in the Phase 2 galleries prior to selection
for subsequent experimentation. Well characterised single fracture and fracture
zone sites are also likely to form good test beds for other experiments in
addition to those addressing rock matrix diffusion, including colloid transport
and gas migration experiments.</P>
<P>5.16 The rock matrix diffusion experiments comprise:</P>
<UL>
<LI>injection of non-sorbing tracers into the fracture system and collection
from sample points (i.e. other boreholes drilled as part of the characterisation
steps). The shapes of the breakthrough curves allow further characterisation of
the geometric and hydraulic properties of the fracture;
</LI>
<LI>injection of sorbing tracers into the fracture system;
</LI>
<LI>comparison of the shapes of the breakthrough curves for non-sorbing and
sorbing tracers will provide an indication of the extent to which sorption may
be expected to occur in the fracture and surrounding rock;
</LI>
<LI>comparison of the shapes of the breakthrough curves for tracers (both
non-sorbing and sorbing) of different diffusivities will provide an indication
of the extent to which rock matrix diffusion may be expected to occur in real
fractures, in situ in the BVG; and
</LI>
<LI>excavation or coring of the experimental site to measure the manner in
which the tracers have become distributed, and also the extent to which the
tracers have diffused into the rock matrix. The excavation, or coring, also
provides the final confirmation of the geometrical properties (shape and
dimensions) of the test bed fracture system, and allows analysis of the extent
to which sorbing tracers have been retarded by the fracture system as a measure
of the extent to which rock matrix diffusion may be expected to occur in real
fractures, in situ in the BVG.
</LI></UL>
<P>Many of these techniques have been developed and used in the Stripa Project,
and variants of them are common to a range of experiments in several other
international and national underground laboratories. It is not practical to
carry out experiments of this type in rocks at these depths from boreholes
drilled from the surface.</P>
<P>Colloid Transport</P>
<P>5.17 To address the issue of the existence of colloids in groundwater
described in Dr Hooper's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.36">para 6.36</A>), samples from carefully
drilled underground boreholes will be taken for analysis as part of the
geochemical sampling programme, referred to in the
<I>Environmental Statement
</I>(para 1.62, page 13) [COR/101]. These boreholes will be drilled from insets
in the galleries of Phase 2 and Phase 3 and will also include the Peripheral
Drilling underground boreholes described in paragraph 4.14. By drilling without
the use of conventional drilling muds, much of the particulate matter which may
be problematic in obtaining good groundwater samples in boreholes drilled with
mud may be avoided. Alternative drilling fluids include deionised or distilled
water and previously collected groundwater. These waters may be kept in pressure
vessels under nitrogen to control the dissolved gas content. Such techniques
have been developed in underground laboratories, including the HRL at &Auml;sp&ouml;
in Sweden. </P>
<P>5.18 The experiments envisaged to study colloid transport are similar to the
single fracture and fracture zone experiments for rock matrix diffusion. The
difference is that, instead of injecting sorbing tracers to study the extent to
which rock matrix diffusion is likely to occur, a range of different colloidal
suspensions would be injected. This allows the breakthrough of different
colloids to be compared with the non-sorbing tracer benchmark. The benefits of
such an approach would include the generation of experimental data on real
colloid transport processes within real, well characterised fractures in situ in
the BVG for the subsequent development of simple empirically based models of
colloid transport as outlined in Dr Hooper's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.38">para 6.38</A>). It is not practical to
carry out experiments of this type in rocks at these depths from boreholes from
the surface.</P>
<P>Gas Migration</P>
<P>5.19 The approach to studying gas migration processes within water filled
fractures in the BVG is similar to that described for in situ studies of rock
matrix diffusion. Studies of gas migration and two phase flow in the RCF will
follow groundwater flow studies. They will need to be located where fractures
and flow through the fractures have been previously characterised, as stated in
the <I>Environmental Statement </I>(para 1.63, page 13) [COR/101]. In practice,
it may be most efficient to complete the rock matrix diffusion experiments and
then initiate gas migration experiments in the same fracture systems. This would
have the substantial advantage that the test bed for the gas measurements would
be well characterised in advance of the introduction of a gas phase into the
fracture. This is particularly important for studies of two phase flow (i.e. a
gas and a liquid together in the same porous medium) because gas is a much more
mobile phase than water and its behaviour can be best studied in a system which
is reasonably well characterised. It is not practical to carry out experiments
of this type in rocks at these depths from boreholes drilled from the surface.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para5.20"></A>5.20 There are currently two types of experiments
considered important to addressing gas migration:</P>
<UL>
<LI>measurements of gas entry pressure into fractures, in which the gas
pressure is steadily increased until the gas/water meniscus is sufficiently
small to penetrate the water wetted and water filled fracture aperture; and
</LI>
<LI>measurements of the two-phase flow characteristics of the fracture system.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Natural and Induced Changes to the Geological Barrier</B></P>
<P>5.21 The observations described in paragraph 4.20 which will be carried out
during shaft sinking will also continue in Phase 2 and Phase 3 as an integral
part of mapping during gallery construction. Additionally, information from the
RCF is required to address the following induced changes:</P>
<UL>
<LI>chemical disturbance; and
</LI>
<LI>excavation disturbance.
</LI></UL>
<P>The current outline plans for activities to provide the required information
are described under these headings in the following paragraphs.</P>
<P>Chemical Disturbance</P>
<P><A NAME="Para5.22"></A>5.22 The experiments currently envisaged to address
chemical disturbance may be regarded as a variant of the rock matrix diffusion
experiments.</P>
<P>5.23 The objective will be to inject highly alkaline fluids, representative
of those emanating from the repository backfill, into well characterised
fracture systems. The presence of the alkaline fluids will cause fluid-rock
chemical reactions which could ultimately change the mineralogy of the fracture
surface and as a consequence also change the hydraulic properties of the
fracture system. The main fluid-rock reactions involved are believed to be
relatively slow and the experiments would be designed to build confidence in the
trends of changes to the rock properties rather than determining the long-term
characteristics of the disturbance zone by direct measurement.</P>
<P>Excavation Disturbance</P>
<P>5.24 The current assumption by Nirex is that the extent and magnitude of the
hydraulic characteristics of the excavation disturbance zone ('EDZ') will be
adequately determined by the end of Phase 1 for the purposes of informing the
decision on whether to propose development of a repository. Further work may
still be required to demonstrate the variation in hydraulic properties in the
disturbed zone as a function of gallery orientation in relation to the maximum
horizontal stress direction, and in the presence of faults or significant
flowing features. Currently, two further types of EDZ experiments are envisaged
for Phase 2 and Phase 3:</P>
<P>Stress-Dependent EDZ Experiments</P>
<P><A NAME="Para5.25"></A>5.25 During Phase 2, the current intention is to
identify locations for two galleries within the BVG to enable two further
experiments on the excavation disturbance zone to be carried out (EDZ
experiments number two and three). The form of the experiments would be
essentially the same as that described in paragraphs 4.23 to 4.24. The
fundamental difference is that one of the galleries would be excavated in a
direction parallel to the direction of maximum horizontal stress, currently
assumed to be an azimuth of 165&#176;, and the other would be at a right angle
to it. This approach would allow the relationship between stress direction and
the extent and magnitude of the mechanical and hydraulic characteristics of the
excavation disturbance to be measured. As with EDZ experiment number one
described in paragraphs 4.23 to 4.24, the disturbances will be monitored
periodically over the long term throughout the remaining life of the facility.
These two experiments will be located in a volume of rock selected during Phase
2 gallery construction. For planning purposes they are currently assumed to be
located off the SSE gallery.</P>
<P>Mine Through Experiment</P>
<P>5.26 The mine through experiment is intended to measure the hydraulic and
mechanical changes induced in a significant fault or fracture zone when mined
through. This is therefore a specialised form of EDZ experiment, and is aimed at
investigating the extent to which excavating repository vaults and access
tunnels through such features is likely to induce significant hydraulic and
mechanical changes in the rock mass. The experimental arrangement is similar to
that for the EDZ tests outlined in paragraphs 4.23 to 4.24. The exact location
for this work would be dependent upon confirmation from mapping Phase 3
galleries and from underground drilling in Phase 3. This work would therefore be
completed during the latter part of Phase 3. The outline of the experiment as
currently envisaged is broadly comparable in outline to the Mine By experiment
completed in the Canadian URL, described in the <I>Experimental Programme for
the URL </I>(para 3.9, page 18) [NRX/16/3]. This experiment would complete the
extensive suit of activities designed to characterise the disturbances to the
rock mass caused by excavations of a repository.</P>
<P><B>Design and Construction of the Repository</B></P>
<P>5.27 The testing of our ability to make extrapolations throughout the BVG
rocks in the PRZ of the distribution of networks of connected fractures will
continue throughout Phase 2 and Phase 3. This will continue to be achieved by
making forward predictions of the expected geological and hydrogeological
characteristics of the BVG, and comparing these predictions with observational
data subsequently obtained from:</P>
<UL>
<LI>mapping the galleries;
</LI>
<LI>underground drilling from insets in the galleries;
</LI>
<LI>measurements of inflows to the excavations; and
</LI>
<LI>measurements of drawdown on the groundwater pressure monitoring system.
</LI></UL>
<P>5.28 The finalised location, orientation and layout of the repository vaults
in the rock mass would be confirmed on the basis of underground drilling from
the Phase 3 galleries, possibly along the line of the vaults.</P>
<P>Sealing</P>
<P><A NAME="Para5.29"></A>5.29 To ensure post-closure safety of a potential
repository, it is important to demonstrate that man-made openings underground
can be sealed against water flow. Experiments will therefore be carried out on
the emplacement of seals in galleries, shafts and boreholes and on grouting of
fracture zones, to establish that the required properties of seal materials,
such as fluidity, durability or permeability (in set conditions) may be achieved
in situ. Additionally, it may be important to investigate the practicalities of
sealing the zone of excavation disturbance around openings or sealing fracture
zones around man-made openings. It is currently planned that experiments will be
implemented for shafts, galleries and boreholes. It is not an aim to evaluate
longevity of any emplacement. The general form of the experiments, or
demonstrations, will be to monitor the emplacement of seals to a stringent
quality plan. This will be followed by a period of monitoring to evaluate their
effectiveness. Finally, seals will be carefully excavated to determine the
uniformity and quality of their emplacement.</P>
<P>5.30 The location for the shaft seal experiment has not been finalised, but
for planning purposes is currently assumed to be constructed from galleries from
the North Shaft during Phase 2, as shown schematically in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.4">Figure 5.4</A>. The details of the experiment
have not been finalised, and will be developed during Phase 1 in the light of
developing experience and understanding of the geotechnical environment in the
BVG. The current form of the experiment is to construct an experimental shaft
between two observation galleries (the upper and lower shaft seal roadways of
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.4">Figure 5.4</A>). Within the experimental
shaft, the walls will be mapped in detail, and a plug, or seal, located
approximately centrally as illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.5">Figure 5.5</A>. Grouting above and below the
plug may be deployed. The emplacement and grouting will be carried out very
carefully, to stringent Quality Assurance guidelines. Over time, the hydraulic
performance of the seal will be tested by pressuring from the pressure chamber,
separated from the seal by the lower bulkhead shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.5">Figure 5.5</A> and monitoring for the passage
of fluids in the leakage observation chamber separated from the seal by the
upper bulkhead, also shown in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.5">Figure 5.5</A>.
The experiment will be completed with excavation of the seal towards the end of
Phase 3 to observe and record the efficiency of the original emplacement
procedures.</P>
<P>5.31 The gallery seal experiments are likely to be comparable in form to
those indicated for the shaft seal experiments. The location for the gallery
seal experiments has not been finalised, but for planning purposes is currently
assumed to be off the SSE gallery. The gallery seal experiments will be
performed in two galleries during Phase 2, one parallel to the maximum
horizontal stress direction, currently assumed to be an azimuth of about 165&#176;,
and the other at a right angle to this direction. This will enable the
effectiveness of gallery seals to be evaluated as a function of stress
direction. As with the shaft seal experiment, the gallery seal experiments will
be concluded with excavation of the seals towards the end of Phase 3 to evaluate
the efficiency of the original emplacement. The actual locations will be
confirmed during Phase 2.</P>
<P>5.32 The borehole seal experiments are likely to be broadly comparable in
form to the shaft and gallery seal experiments. For planning purposes, the
location for the borehole seal experiments is currently assumed to be off the
upper shaft seal roadway, as shown in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.6">Figure
5.6</A>. The seal will be emplaced during Phase 2, and excavated for detailed
examination towards the end of Phase 3, as illustrated schematically in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.7">Figure 5.7</A>.</P>
<P>5.33 During construction of the South Shaft there will be opportunities to
examine the seal emplaced in the shaft centre-line borehole, RCF3 which will be
sealed before shaft sinking commences.</P>
<P>5.34 Experiments to evaluate sealing of the fractures and the excavation
disturbance zone are likely to be undertaken at the site of one or more of the
EDZ experiments planned for Phases 2 and 3 and described in paragraphs 5.25 and
5.26, following completion of the experiments.
</P>
<P><B>6. <A NAME="DESIGN">DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION OF THE RCF</A></B></P>
<P><B>Overview of Construction and Operation</B></P>
<P>6.1 Construction of the RCF is programmed in 4 stages:</P>
<P></P>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD><U>Stage</U></TD>
<TD><U>Main Science Activities</U>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>Site Establishment
</LI></UL></TD>
<TD>Continuance of hydrogeological baseline monitoring;
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>Phase 1
</LI></UL></TD>
<TD>Science Programme comprising shaft sinking, excavation of galleries to
connect the shafts, and experiments;
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>Phase 2
</LI></UL></TD>
<TD>Science Programme comprising gallery excavation and experiments; and
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>Phase 3
</LI></UL></TD>
<TD>Science Programme comprising excavation to extend the galleries and
experiments.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>6.2 As stated in the &quot;<I>Description of the Rock Characterisation
</I>Facility&quot; (&quot;<I>RCF Description</I>&quot;)(para 3.2, page 4)
[COR/111] the RCF galleries are intended to be developed at the repository
horizon. The repository may be developed at any depth between 650 metres bOD and
900 metres bOD. The currently preferred repository horizon is 650 metres bOD and
this depth is currently used as the baseline planning depth for the RCF
galleries. If the RCF galleries are to be constructed as deep as 900 metres bOD
then the duration of the RCF Programme (shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>) would extend by a period
currently assumed to be about 4 months, assuming the durations of Phase 2 and
Phase  3 remained constant.</P>
<P>6.3 Subject to the granting of planning permission, construction of the RCF
is planned to commence in about July 1996.</P>
<P>Site Establishment</P>
<P>6.4 Site Establishment would commence with a cut and fill earthworks
operation designed to form a level platform providing the minimum working area
requirements for the RCF. Drainage would be established and the access road
constructed at this stage. The various structures required for the RCF would be
built as the prepared platform is made available for them. Services connections
would be established. The Longlands Farm buildings would be converted for use as
a visitor reception area and offices. Throughout Site Establishment the
hydrogeological baseline monitoring from the surface boreholes described in Dr
Chaplow's evidence will continue.</P>
<P>Phase 1</P>
<P>6.5 The shafts will be constructed through Sherwood Sandstone, Brockram and
the BVG. It will be necessary to undertake some form of ground treatment during
construction to control potential inflows of water into the shafts. The
technique which is likely to be employed is grout injection. Information from
the RCF boreholes will be used by the shaft sinker to determine areas where
ground treatment would be likely to be required. Additionally, the shaft sinker
will drill and test probe holes in advance of excavation to confirm ground
treatment. As explained in more detail in Section 4, valuable scientific
information will be derived from these probe holes and the ground treatment
itself. The sections of both shafts which will penetrate the sandstones will be
lined with concrete to form a hydrostatic lining which will restrict water
inflows from the sandstones as stated in the <I>RCF Description </I>(para 3.5,
page 4) [COR/111].</P>
<P>6.6 It will take approximately 3&#189; years to construct the South Shaft
and North Shaft to provide access to the galleries at 650 metres. Access to this
horizon will require a 30 metre deep sump at the bottom of each shaft below the
gallery horizon, taking the shafts to 680 metres bOD. As indicated in paragraph
6.2, the RCF galleries could be developed at any depth between 650 metres bOD
and 900 metres bOD. Shaft access to galleries at 900 metres bOD, together with a
35 metre deep sump, would result in a maximum shaft depth of 935 metres bOD. A
number of scientific activities (described in more detail in section 4) will be
integrated with construction throughout shaft sinking, which may be summarised
as:</P>
<UL>
<LI>mapping (described in paragraphs 4.4 and 4.5);
</LI>
<LI>hydraulic measurements(described in paragraphs 4.6 to 4.13); and
</LI>
<LI>excavation monitoring (described in paragraph 4.21).
</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="Para6.7"></A>6.7 At 650 metres bOD the shafts will be connected by
a gallery to establish a ventilation circuit (see
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A>). A telemetry room will be
constructed, adjoining the connecting gallery. The telemetry room will house
computing equipment which is needed to transmit data from the experiments of
Phase 2 and Phase 3 to the offices on the surface via fibre optic cables
installed in the shafts. If an horizon significantly deeper that 650 metres bOD
were to be selected for the RCF galleries then a second gallery connecting the
shafts would be constructed at this deeper horizon. Thereafter a series of
experimental activities (described in more detail in section 4) is planned to be
undertaken:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Peripheral Drilling to enable hydraulic testing of conductive features in
the BVG (described in paragraph 4.14); and
</LI>
<LI>EDZ experiment number one to measure the hydraulic and mechanical response
to excavation (described in more detail in paragraphs 4.23 and 4.24).
</LI></UL>
<P>Phase 2</P>
<P>6.8 It is important to retain sufficient flexibility in the RCF layout to
access particular features of interest in the rock mass, either by underground
drilling or excavation. It will not be possible to identify all those features
until construction is underway. For this reason, the layout of Phase 2 shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figures 6.2</A> and
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure6.3">6.3</A> is indicative of the likely
underground excavations. The importance of a flexible approach to the design and
construction underground layout to achieve the information which is required is
explained in detail in Section 7. It is possible that, in firming up the layout
of the Phase 2 galleries, the timing or duration of construction might change in
detail from that indicated in the RCF Programme shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.</P>
<P>6.9 Three main galleries at the horizon identified during Phase 1, each
about 150 metres in length, will be constructed During construction, mapping,
hydraulic measurements and excavation monitoring will be carried out. This is
likely to take about 6 months. It will enable the remaining Phase 2 Science
Programme to take place, during which testing of the BVG will be carried out
over a period of approximately 21 months. It may be advantageous to initiate
some, or all, of the Phase 2 gallery construction towards the end of Phase 1.
The advantages are two fold. Firstly, it would provide earlier opportunities to
undertake mapping, hydraulic measurements and excavation monitoring of BVG in
the PRZ in areas away from the shaft bottom in order to inform the decision to
propose development of a repository. Secondly, it is more practical and cost
effective to continue with the construction work from shaft sinking, and the
shaft sinker may be retained for this purpose. The current programme (<A
HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>) assumes that all of the Phase 2
gallery construction is completed towards the end of Phase 1.</P>
<P>Phase 3</P>
<P>6.10 Subject to the possibility of changes to the underground layout
described in paragraph 6.8, this will commence with the extension of two of the
Phase 2 galleries up to 375 metres and 600 metres in length and the addition of
three more galleries up to 200 metres in length (see
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure 6.2</A>). During construction, mapping,
hydraulic measurements and excavation monitoring will be carried out, and this
will take some 8 months to complete and would enable the Phase 3 Science
Programme to proceed, as stated in the <I>RCF Description </I>(para 3.10, page
6) [COR/111]. This will take approximately 3 years following completion of
gallery construction. <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>
illustrates the development if the shafts are deepened.</P>
<P><B>Underground Access Options</B></P>
<P>Shafts Versus Drifts</P>
<P>6.11 The RCF could achieve underground access to the BVG at the preferred
depth of 735 metres (650 metres bOD) by either inclined drifts or vertical
shafts, as stated in the <I>Environmental Statement</I> (para 2.69, page 29)
[COR/101].</P>
<P>6.12 It is important to be able to assess ground conditions ahead of
construction of either inclined drifts or shafts in order to avoid possible
inundation by water or collapse of the excavations due to unforeseen ground
conditions. The geology ahead of excavation can be predicted for a shaft by
means of a shaft centreline borehole. It is not practicable to drill a long
inclined borehole for the purposes of comparable prediction ahead of
construction for inclined drifts because of the greater distance and inherent
difficulty in keeping the borehole on the drift centreline. It is considered
that vertical shafts, with conditions proven initially by vertical centreline
boreholes, would best meet the requirement to be able to predict ground
conditions ahead of construction for the RCF. In general, shafts provide a more
economic means of primary access to rock at depth for underground excavations of
the limited scale required for the RCF. For these reasons, the option for
vertical shafts to gain underground access to the RCF was chosen as stated in
the <I>Environmental Statement </I>(para 2.72, page 30) [COR/101].</P>
<P>Number of Shafts</P>
<P>6.13 In excavation terms, the RCF will be similar to a deep mine and safety
considerations have been addressed as if it were a mine. The Mines (Safety of
Exits) Regulations 1988 require at least two separate exits to the surface in
most situations. While a single shaft could be appropriate to very limited
amount of gallery construction and exploratory work close to the shaft, two
shafts were deemed necessary to meet the safety requirements for all the phases
of the RCF.</P>
<P>Timing of Shafts</P>
<P>6.14 The programme shown in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>
requires the construction of both shafts to be completed, along with the
connecting gallery, before Phase 2 construction begins. This will provide two
separate exits to the surface for the initiation of the Peripheral Drilling and
EDZ experiments of Phase 1, and for the Construction of the Phase 2 galleries.</P>
<P><B>Shaft Construction Method</B></P>
<P>6.15 Three methods of shaft construction were considered - boring, drilling
and conventional shaft sinking (drill and blast), as stated in the <I>Environmental
Statement </I>(para 2.76, page 30) [COR/101].</P>
<P>Shaft Boring</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.16"></A>6.16 Shaft boring, in which the machine is operated
by men working underground on the body of the machine - rather like a tunnel
boring machine - is not an established method of construction for shafts at
these depths where there are no pre-existing underground workings for spoil
clearance via a pilot hole. The use of shaft boring was discounted for this
reason, leaving two methods for consideration.</P>
<P>Shaft Drilling</P>
<P>6.17 Shaft drilling has not been widely used in the UK, but is an accepted
and routine practice in some countries, though usually to shallower depths than
the RCF. Shaft drilling is similar to borehole drilling where the hole (shaft)
is kept filled with water or drilling mud and the rock fragments are removed by
the circulating fluid.</P>
<P>6.18 It is an important functional requirement for the RCF that the
construction method selected enables regular and routine access to the shaft
walls for mapping and other scientific measurements and observations during the
shaft sinking operation. During construction of the shaft by drilling there
would be no opportunity for immediate access to the shaft walls and the option
of shaft drilling was therefore discounted for this reason.</P>
<P>The Drill and Blast Method</P>
<P>6.19 The elimination of boring and drilling as options for construction of
the shafts leaves drill and blast as the preferred method, as stated in the <I>Environmental
Statement </I>(para 2.90, page 31) [COR/101]. In this method, a cycle of
drilling and blasting operations is used to construct the shaft. The cycle
starts with the drilling of holes in the rock, normally to a pre-determined
pattern, which are then charged with explosives. For the RCF shafts, the
pre-determined pattern will be designed to keep blast-induced damage to the rock
mass as low as practicable, as explained in more detail in paragraphs 6.26 to
6.28. The explosives are then detonated. Following blasting, fume clearance and
spoil removal, the newly exposed walls of the shaft can be temporarily
supported. Where an in situ concrete lining is used, then this will normally be
installed every few cycles of drilling and blasting.</P>
<P>6.20 The proposed depth of the access shafts will be well within the
capability of the drill and blast method, and the experience of shaft sinking
contractors worldwide. The RCF will therefore present no particular or unusual
technical difficulties with sinking, lining operations, groundwater control or
equipping the shaft.</P>
<P>6.21 During shaft sinking by the drill and blast method there will be
opportunity for regular and routine access to the rock mass for mapping and
other scientific measurements and observations (described in more detail in
Section 4). The information which is required from the RCF is therefore
generated continuously throughout, and as an integral part of, the shaft
construction operations.</P>
<P>6.22 Several countries have constructed underground research laboratories as
a part of their programmes into the deep geological disposal of radioactive
waste. Those countries which are investigating saturated, fractured igneous
rocks include Canada and Sweden. Each of these countries has selected the drill
and blast method as the principal method of gaining access to their underground
laboratory. Through its existing agreements with, and participation in these
programmes, the practical experience gained from using the drill and blast
method in these programmes will be used in constructing the RCF.</P>
<P>Shaft Diameter</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.23"></A>6.23 The shafts have to be of such a diameter as to
provide working space for the construction workers and to provide working space
for the scientists to map and undertake scientific measurements on the rock
mass. The selection of shaft diameter is based on the advice and practical
experience of Nirex's mining consultants and in-house mining engineers. Small
diameter shafts in the range 3 to 4 metres could be constructed by the drill and
blast method and would satisfy the ventilation, transportation and technical
requirements for the RCF. However, 5 metres is considered to be the minimum
practical diameter to provide a safe and efficient working environment for the
shaft sinking personnel. A 5 metre internal finished diameter was selected for
both shafts.</P>
<P>6.24 In order to ensure that an internal finished diameter of 5 metres is
achieved, it is essential to drill and blast a slightly larger diameter than 5
metres. This is because the blast holes have to be drilled at a slight angle
(the so-called look-out angle) away from the vertical, in order to allow
clearance between the drill and the shaft wall. The look-out angle on a 5 metre
diameter shaft is likely to result in a maximum working diameter in the BVG of
about 5.4 metres. As noted in paragraph 4.18, the maximum working diameter of
the excavation through the sandstones would be up to about 7.4 metres in order
to accommodate the thickness of the hydrostatic lining.</P>
<P>6.25 The option of providing a small diameter drilled shaft as the second
means of egress was considered. Such a shaft was constructed, for example, at
the Canadian URL. However, the Canadian facility is very significantly shallower
than the RCF permitting a 240 metre deep, small diameter shaft to be drilled for
ventilation and emergency access. This option was rejected for the RCF on the
grounds that it may not provide safe and effective access under all operating
conditions, as stated in the <I>Environmental Statement </I>(para 2.75, page
30) [COR/101].</P>
<P><B>Drill and Blast Approach</B></P>
<P>6.26 In general terms, creating an excavation in rock at depth by any method
is likely to cause a zone of disturbance to be created around the excavation.
Within this zone the mechanical and hydraulic properties will be different to
some extent to those which existed before the excavation was created.</P>
<P>6.27 Creating an excavation in rock at depth by the drill and blast method
in particular can further add to the level of disturbance in the rock mass
adjacent to the excavation, particularly in the first few tens of centimetres
into the rock mass from the wall or face of the excavation. These additional,
blast induced, changes are termed blast-induced damage.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.28"></A>6.28 In order to keep blast-induced damage to the
rock mass as low as is practicable, Nirex has used international blast
consultants to review blast damage mechanisms relevant to construction of the
RCF shafts, the influence of blast design parameters on damage to the rock mass
and the likely extent and degree of damage to the rock mass from blasting in
shaft construction. A blast design philosophy has been developed for the RCF
shafts which incorporates a cautious blasting technique in order to keep
blast-induced damage to the rock mass as low as is practicable. This approach is
similar to the use of careful blasting techniques to minimise rock damage used
by Atomic Energy of Canada Limited (AECL) in the construction of the Canadian
URL circular shaft extension, as stated in <I>Geological Characterisation for
the Underground Research Laboratory Shaft Extension</I> (&quot;<I>Geological
Characterisation for the URL</I>&quot;) (para 4.3, page 10) [NRX/16/5]. The
approach is also comparable to that developed by ANDRA in a smooth blasting
experiment carried out in the Canadian URL in 1991. The main result of the ANDRA
experiment was to prove that it was possible to reduce the extension of the
damage zone significantly (from less than one metre to 10 or 20 centimetres)
using gas-energy explosives combined with appropriate blast designs, as stated
in <I>ZEDEX Test Plan</I> (para 3.2, page 2) [NRX/16/1].</P>
<P><A NAME="Para6.29"></A>6.29 Shaft blasting for the RCF will be performed
using full face blasting, utilising blast designs similar to those used in the
circular shaft extension of the Canadian URL. Even with the use of cautious
blasting described in paragraph 28, the excavation process will introduce
induced fractures into the rock mass. In general terms, induced fractures are
likely to be recognisable as distinct from natural fractures by their symmetry
relative to the shape of the excavation and to remnants of the blasting centres,
and by their lack of (natural) mineral infillings and wall rock alteration, as
shown by the Canadian programme of mapping shafts constructed in hard, fractured
rock by the drill and blast method, as stated in <I>Geological Characterisation
for the URL</I> (para B.4.1, page B.3) [NRX/16/5].</P>
<P><B>Gallery Construction Method</B></P>
<P>6.30 The method selected for constructing the RCF galleries is also drill
and blast. There are no practical, economic alternatives to this method for such
a limited extent of underground layout. This method was also used to construct
galleries in the Canadian URL, in the Swedish Stripa Project and in the Swedish
HRL. </P>
<P><B>Gallery Orientation</B></P>
<P>6.31 As set out in Dr Chaplow's evidence (
<A HREF="../nrx14/nrx14a1.htm#TA13">Table A.13</A>, Appendix A.35)[<B>PE/NRX/14</B>],
there is a significant contrast in the magnitudes of the horizontal stresses.
The ratio of maximum to minimum horizontal stress is about 1.8 at 800 metres
depth, with the maximum horizontal stress direction averaging an azimuth of 165&#176;.
In order to make measurements and observations on the extent to which this
contrast in stress magnitude matters to the creation of excavations in the BVG,
and in particular to the behaviour of the excavation disturbance zone, some of
the Phase 2 and Phase 3 galleries are planned to be aligned approximately
parallel to, and others to be aligned approximately perpendicular to this
average azimuth of 165&#176;. This accounts for the orientations of the current
indicative layout of Phase 2 and Phase 3 shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figures 6.2</A> and
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure6.3">6.3</A>.</P>
<P><B>7. <A NAME="APPROACH">APPROACH TO PLANNING AND MANAGING ACTIVITIES IN
THE RCF</A></B></P>
<P>7.1 A recurring theme in the work of all national and international
underground programmes evaluating deep disposal of radioactive wastes is that it
is essential to retain a sufficient degree of flexibility to adapt the layout of
the laboratory, the underground experiments or both to the geological conditions
as found underground. For example, one of the main conclusions (<I>Stripa
Project Overview</I> (para 7.1, page 89) [NRX/16/2]) from the international
co-operative underground research programme at Stripa, Sweden is:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Due to variability and uncertainty in the geological environment,
the site characterisation process should be iterative and adaptive</I>&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.2 The Canadian research programme in the URL similarly found flexibility
essential<I> (Experimental Programme for the URL</I> (para 1.2 page 2)
[NRX/16/3]):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Flexibility was included in the design to accommodate the actual
ground conditions found during construction. In application, our initial URL
designs were based on the early characterisation data. As our understanding of
the rock mass in which we were working improved with additional characterisation
data, we adapted the URL layouts.&quot; &quot;For example, the 240 Level tunnel
direction was changed to avoid excavating into Fracture Zone 2 (FZ2), and the
tunnel layout and cross section were changed twice to achieve more stability
under the in situ stress conditions. In the shaft extension, the cross section
was made circular to better carry the increasing rock stress conditions</I>.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.3 The Swedish &Auml;sp&ouml; HRL operated by SKB has also found
flexibility to be essential (<I>&Auml;sp&ouml; Hard Rock Laboratory Annual
Report 1993</I> (para 3.2.1., page 22) [NRX/16/6]):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>The Operating Phase of the &Auml;sp&ouml; HRL will soon commence
and it was found essential that the layout of the laboratory be adapted to the
experiments planned for the Operating Phase and that potential experiment sites
be identified</I>.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.4 Nirex's own experience in planning and implementing the joint
SKB/ANDRA/Nirex ZEDEX Project located underground in the HRL at &Auml;sp&ouml;
has also confirmed the need for flexibility in both the details of the
experimental design and the exact location of excavations suitable to host
specific experiments, as indicated in the <I>ZEDEX Test Plan</I> (para 4.1,
page 4) [NRX/16/1].</P>
<P>7.5. It is therefore prudent to plan and manage the RCF on the basis that
changes in underground layout and/or the detail of the scientific activities are
likely. For this reason flexibility to adapt the underground layout and the
integrated science and construction programme (described in sections 4 and 5) is
essential.</P>
<P><B>Sectors</B></P>
<P>7.6 One of the main requirements of the RCF is to study networks of
connected fractures which control the flow of groundwater. These networks are
thought to be not uniformly distributed through the rock. Consequently, some
regions of rock may have networks of connected fractures passing through them,
whilst other regions of rock may have no networks of connected fractures passing
through them. </P>
<P>7.7 The approach which has been adopted for providing a flexible method of
managing activities in the RCF is to divide the shafts and galleries up into
sectors. The basic idea behind sectors is that there may be more potential for
providing the required information in one sector compared with another sector.
The detailed programmes of scientific activities for individual sectors,
therefore, will vary from sector to sector, according to the information which
is required.</P>
<P>7.8 The different sectors for Phase 1 are shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A>, which illustrates the twelve
sectors identified for use in managing the scientific programme if the Phase 2
and Phase 3 galleries are to be developed at 650 metres bOD. Should the Phase 2
and Phase 3 galleries be developed at a deeper horizon, then additional sectors
will be required, as shown in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure7.2">Figure 7.2</A>.
The definition and reasoning behind the Phase 1 sector boundaries is summarised
in <A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A>.</P>
<P>7.9 Nirex will release results from Phase 1 by sector, following completion
of work in each sector. Results from Phase 1 will therefore be released
progressively and continuously throughout shaft sinking. Results and experience
in completed sectors will be used iteratively to adapt work programmes and the
detailed design for excavation in successive sectors.</P>
<P><B>Sector Test Plans</B></P>
<P>7.10 A sector test plan sets out the scientific activities and experiments
which are to be undertaken in an individual sector in order to provide
information which is required to address the uncertainties identified in Dr
Hooper's evidence. To design the tests in the light of the most up to date
information so that the 'best' test is performed, each Sector Test Plan will be
developed progressively in outline form until three months before it is needed
for implementation. Whilst in outline status, the Sector Test Plans may be
revised and updated in the light of results and understanding from previously
completed sectors and from the continuing site characterisation programme. This
approach to refining the experiments and experimental layout makes use of
experience gained in planning and managing underground experiments in other
facilities, as in the example of the <I>ZEDEX Test Plan</I> (para 5.1, page 13)
[NRX/16/1]. The programme of activities described in Section 4 is therefore a
summary of how activities carried out in all the sectors shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A> (and
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure7.2">Figure 7.2</A> if the shafts access an horizon
deeper than 650 metres bOD) will produce information of the first category
identified as a requirement Dr Hooper's evidence.</P>
<P><B>Forward Predictions</B></P>
<P><A NAME="Para7.11"></A>7.11 The key to understanding how the RCF will be
used to reduce uncertainties and increase confidence lies in forward prediction,
as noted in Dr Hooper's evidence (<B>PE/NRX/15</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx15/nrx15.htm#Para6.10">paras 6.10</A> to 6.12). A forward
prediction is a description of significant findings which are expected to be
made in a particular sector, or experiment, before the sector is excavated or
the experiment is begun. The observations and findings of the sector, or
experiment, are subsequently compared with the predictions which were made
beforehand. By making a range of forward predictions based on alternative
conceptual models it should be possible to eliminate those conceptual models
which are least consistent with actual observations and significant findings.</P>
<P>7.12 Each sector and experiment in all three phases of the RCF will have
forward predictions completed before the sector is excavated, or before the
experiment is initiated. Reduction of specific uncertainty and increase in
confidence will follow where there is a reasonable match between a forward
prediction and actual observations. This approach is common to other national
and international underground programmes evaluating deep disposal of radioactive
wastes.</P>
<P><B>Duration of Phases</B></P>
<P>7.13 The current description of the RCF, and the working programme shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>, assumes that the decision by
Nirex to propose development of a repository may be taken at the end of Phase 1.
However, should this decision by deferred into Phase 2 or Phase 3, the layout
and the programme and durations of Phase 2 and Phase 3 might need to be revised.
For the current working programme, the durations of the three phases of the RCF
are:</P>
<P>Phase 1 Science Programme : 4 years 2 months</P>
<P>Phase 2 Science Programme : 2 years 3 months</P>
<P>Phase 3 Science Programme : 3 years 8 months</P>
<P>As explained in paragraph6.9, it may be advantageous to initiate some, or
all, of the Phase 2 gallery construction towards the end of Phase 1. The start
of the Phase 2 Science Programme therefore overlaps with the end of the Phase 1
Science Programme by some 9 months, as shown in
<A HREF="nrx16fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>. The current estimate of total
elapsed time for all 3 Phases of the RCF Science Programme is therefore 9 years
and 4 months. This is broadly in line with the durations of underground
programmes planned in other countries, as explained in Dr Holmes' evidence (<B>PE/NRX/13</B>,
<A HREF="../nrx13/nrx13.htm#Table8.1">Table 8.1</A>). These timescales may be
distinguished from those of generic laboratories (i.e. not specific to a
potential repository location) which are primarily concerned with the
development of techniques. Nirex participates in, or has links with, several of
these generic laboratories which has enabled us to gain knowledge and experience
of planning and managing underground characterisation.</P>
<P><B>8. <A NAME="REFERENCES">REFERENCES</A></B></P>
